<HEADLINE> Russia Vows to Expand Nuclear Cooperation With Iran </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Russian Atomic Energy Minister
Yevgeny Adamov said Wednesday that his country will expand its
cooperation with Iran in nuclear energy programs.
</P>
<P>
Adamov said that Moscow will honor its commitments to Tehran in
such programs and that the activities are consistent with
guidelines on nuclear nonproliferation, Interfax reported.
</P>
<P>
The Minister said Russia will step up the construction of the
first power unit in the Busher nuclear power station where over
1,000 nuclear and construction engineers are working.
</P>
<P>
Iran wants Russia to build three more power units in Busher and
such offer creates jobs and keeps factories running in Russia, the
minister said.
</P>
<P>
Adamov said that during his visit to the United States next
week he will "patiently explain to Iran in the development of
nuclear weapons."
</P>
<P>
Specifically, the minister said, he will tell the Americans
that the Research and Design Institute of Power Engineering and
the Mendeleyev Institute of Chemical Technology do not work on
nuclear weapons and do not cooperate with Iran in that field.
</P>
<P>
The two facilities were among a number of Russian institutions
that the United States accused of cooperation with Iran in weapons
programs, a charge denied by Moscow. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
