<DOCNO> XIE19990318.0002 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yeltsin, Primakov Say Skuratov Can not Retain Job </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin
and Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov said Wednesday that Yuri
Skuratov can not work as the prosecutor general because the post
requires "morally unstained" people.
</P>
<P>
The statement, issued by the Kremlin press service, came in
the wake of the Federation Council's rejection of Skuratov's
request for his resignation from the office of prosecutor general
earlier in the day.
</P>
<P>
The upper house of parliament rejected the resignation by a
vote of 142-6 with three abstentions at a session attended by
Skuratov.
</P>
<P>
The Kremlin said that Yeltsin and Primakov, who met at the
Central Clinical Hospital where the president is recuperating from
a stomach ulcer, "are unanimous that unscrupulousness and
politicking are incompatible with the high post of prosecutor
general."
</P>
<P>
Skuratov, who tendered his resignation in early February, said
Wednesday that he is prepared to continue working at the post.
</P>
<P>
"I will not give up the work, if you extend your trust and
support to me," Skuratov said.
</P>
<P>
Skuratov confirmed the existence of reported compromising
material against him but insisted he had not "done anything in
breach of the law," Interfax reported.
</P>
<P>
Skuratov's resignation, presumably for "health reasons," was
announced by the Kremlin on February 2.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin accepted the resignation right away and sent a letter
to the Federation Council, asking them to free Skuratov from his
duties immediately.
</P>
<P>
Under the Russian Constitution, the prosecutor general is
appointed and dismissed by the Federation Council on the
initiative of the President.
</P>
<P>
The State Duma, or lower house of parliament, hailed the upper
house vote.
</P>
<P>
"Thus, the Prosecutor General remains in office," Duma Speaker
Gennady Seleznyov said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
