<HEADLINE> World Bank Finances Municipal Services Project in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 17 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank announced on
Wednesday the approval of a credit of 138.6 million U.S. dollars
for the Municipal Services Project in Bangladesh to improve
environmental and infrastructure service delivery in urban areas.
</P>
<P>
The project will help strengthen the institutional capacity of
selected municipal corporations and secondary towns to provide
urban infrastructure services and improve the environmental
conditions in poor urban areas by financing critical urban
infrastructure and services, the bank said.
</P>
<P>
According to the bank, Bangladesh's urban population has been
growing rapidly at about 4.2 percent a year. Some 11 million of
the 25 million city dwellers live in poverty with monthly
household incomes of less than 75 dollars.
</P>
<P>
The social, economic, and political impacts of uncontrolled
growth and urban expansion on the urban poor are
disproportionately high. Many are unemployed and are forced to
live in squatter areas that do not receive even the most basic
services.
</P>
<P>
The first phase of the project will finance civil works for
water supply to rehabilitate existing systems in 12
municipalities. It will also provide sanitation facilities such as
public toilets and washing facilities to be maintained by local
communities in 15 urban centers, along with a pilot small-bore
sewerage program in Khulna.
</P>
<P>
This phase of the project also covers about 220 kilometers of
roads in all participating cities and secondary towns and will
finance renovation of deteriorated roads, road paving and
widening, bridge improvements and construction of footpaths and
culverts.
</P>
<P>
The interest-free credit is provided by the International
Development Association (IDA), the concessionary lending affiliate
of the World Bank Group, on standard IDA terms with 40 years to
maturity and a 10-year grace period. The government of Bangladesh
will provide 15.4 million dollars. Total project costs are 154
million dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
