<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-17 16:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arab League Warns of Israel's "Racist Ideology" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Arab League (AL) Secretary General
Esmat Abdel-Meguid warned on Wednesday of Israel's "racist
ideology" on security, politics and economy in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
In his report to the 111th session of the AL Foreign Ministers
Council, which opened here in the day, Abdel-Meguid said the
Israeli right-wing Likud coalition attempts to eradicate Arab
presence in Palestine to establish greater Israel.
</P>
<P>
The Jewish state also intends to impose its hegemony on the
Arab world as a whole, control the Arab destiny and usurp Arab
resources, the AL chief said.
</P>
<P>
Ever since it assumed power in 1996, the Israeli government of
Benjamin Netanyahu has been working on the expansion of the
Zionist scheme by confiscating more Palestinian land, activating
the settlement drive and depriving the Palestinian people of their
rights and freedoms, Abdel-Meguid added.
</P>
<P>
He maintained that the declaration of an independent state is a
legitimate right of the Palestinians, which is fully backed by the
Arab world.
</P>
<P>
But he cautioned that the choice of the appropriate date for
the declaration requires more time and contacts to realize the
aspired goal and confront Israeli challenges.
</P>
<P>
Abdel-Meguid criticized Israel for freezing the Middle East
peace process, rejecting resumption of negotiations on the Syrian
and Lebanese tracks.
</P>
<P>
On the issue of Iraq, Abdel-Meguid said, the Arab League will
not accept any military action or aggression on one of its member
states.
</P>
<P>
He called for an immediate halt to the aggression against Iraq
and warned against its continuation.
</P>
<P>
The Arab stance is united on the Arab solidarity with the Iraqi
people in their dilemma and the respect of Iraq's sovereignty and
territorial integrity, he added.
</P>
<P>
The Arab foreign ministers meet twice a year in March and
September to coordinate their countries' foreign policies and iron
out their differences.
</P>
<P>
The Arab foreign ministers will discuss in the two-day meeting
a number of key issues in the Arab world, including the Mideast
peace process, the Iraqi issue, the Lockerbie crisis between Libya
and the West. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
