<HEADLINE> Turkey Ready to Hold Talks with Greece: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, March 17 (Xinhua) -- A Turkish senior official said
here Wednesday that Turkey is ready to hold talks with
neighboring Greece in a bid to solve all the problems between the
two sides.
</P>
<P>
Turkish Foregin Ministry Deputy Undersecretary Faruk Logoglu
told reporters that the whole world should know that "we wish to
solve the disputes with neighboring Greece and we are ready to do
so."
</P>
<P>
Ankara has long accused Greece of aiding the outlawed
Kurdish Workers' Party (PKK), but Athens has categorically denied
the accusations.
</P>
<P>
Turkish press has reported that Greek Foreign Minister Yorgo
Papandreu will pay an official visit to Turkey in April in
order to ease the worsening tension between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Relations between the two long-time foes worsened after the
capture of PKK leader Abdullah Ocalan in Kenya in mid-February.
Ocalan was arrested by Turkish special agents when he was
leaving the residence of Greek AMbassador to Nairobi where he
had taken shelter for 12 days.
</P>
<P>
However, Logoglu said Turkey has not received any official
request from the Greek government for Papandreu's visit to Turkey
through diplomatic channels. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
