<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-17 16:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Second Iraqi Plane Lands in Saudi Airport </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, March 17 (Xinhua) -- An Iraqi plane carrying
around 110 pilgrims landed in Saudi Red Sea coastal city of
Jeddah Wednesday, the second batch of Iraqi pilgrims arriving in
Saudi Arabia.
</P>
<P>
The Kuwait News Agency quoted unnamed Saudi officials as
saying that Saudi authorities had allowed the Russian-made
Ilyushin-76 to touch down at 12:00 GMT.
</P>
<P>
The officials said the plane flew via Jordan before entering
the Saudi air space. The airliner can not cross Saudi space
directly because the U.S.-British forces enforcing the air embargo
against Iraq would force it to get back.
</P>
<P>
Baghdad is still under the U.N. sanctions imposed after the
1991 Gulf war triggered by Iraq's invasion of Kuwait in 1990.
</P>
<P>
The pilgrims will proceed by land to the Muslim holy city of
Mecca, 75 kilometers away from Jeddah, the Saudi officials said.
</P>
<P>
The first Iraqi plane carrying 110 pilgrims including Iraq's
Minister of Endowment and Religious Affairs Abdul-Munim Ahmed
Saleh landed in Jeddah Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Head of the Iraqi Airways Rabaee Mohammed Saleh said earlier
that Iraq was planning three flights to Saudi Arabia this year.
</P>
<P>
Some elderly men and women, who have found it hard to endure
the 2,000 kilometers land journey, would have chance to take the
flights, Saleh said.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Interior Minister Prince Nayef Bin Abdel-Aziz said that
Riyadh does not ban pilgrims to come to the kingdom to perform the
Hajj pilgrimage, regardless of the means of transportation.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Arabia "can not stop any pilgrim from coming to the holy
land," he said.
</P>
<P>
Iraq flew a civilian plane to Saudi Arabia in 1997, carrying
104 elderly and sick pilgrims to Mecca for the Hajj, a pillar of
Islam.
</P>
<P>
Iraq, with a population of more than 20 million, can send up to
22,000 pilgrims to Mecca under a quota system, which limits the
number of Muslims to attend the pilgrimage.
</P>
<P>
Earlier reports said that about 2,000 Iraqis had arrived in the
kingdom by land Monday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
