<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean Union Maintains Stance On Boycott </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Powerful Zimbabwe Congress of
Trade Unions (ZCTU) Wednesday said it will not enter into social
contract negotiations with the government as long as the ban on
job stayaways imposed by President Robert Mugabe last year remains
in force.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe slapped a six-month ban on stayaways and strikes using
the Presidential Powers Regulations following threats of weekly
job stayaways by ZCTU.
</P>
<P>
ZCTU organizing Secretary James Makore said the union could not
 participate in tripartite negotiations as it would be impossible
for government to treat it as a partner while the ban was in
force, the Zimbabwe News Agency Ziana reported.
</P>
<P>
"Before the ban is lifted there can be no smooth relations
between the government, business and labor. We will continue to
reserve our right to participate," Makore said.
</P>
<P>
The government last year set up a tripartite forum composed of
labor, business and itself to seek solutions to economic problems
facing the country.
</P>
<P>
Makore said the union was disappointed that prices of basic
commodities continued to rise after tripartite negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Makore said employers should not take advantage of
the ban to dismiss their workers when they strike as the ban was
imposed on ZCTU only.
</P>
<P>
"It is likely that some employers might take advantage of the
ignorance of workers on the ban to stop them from striking for
cost of living adjustments," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
