<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Absence in WTO Adversely Affects World: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 17 (Xinhua) -- China's continued absence from the
World Trade Organization (WTO) will adversely affect both the
international trading system at large and the members' bilateral
trading ties with China, a top WTO official said here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Conclusion on China's accession into the WTO will need strong
political will, determination and vision in the key capitals of
the world, said Chulsu Kim, deputy Director-General of the WTO,
when addressing a conference on "Asia and the Future of the World
Economic System."
</P>
<P>
"Although China has been far less affected by the financial
crisis in Asia than other economies, it has played a critical role
in containing the crisis," he told the conference hosted by the
British Royal Institute of International Affairs.
</P>
<P>
"China's decision not to devalue its currency despite the
competitive pressures and her decision to maintain the momentum of
economic reforms in adverse economic conditions have earned her
greater credibility as an important and responsible participant in
the international trade and economic system," he said.
</P>
<P>
Kim also noted the intensification of China's accession
negotiation in recent months, but said that "given the size and
importance of China's economy and wide-ranging trade interests
involved for a large number of WTO Members, it is not surprising
that these bilateral negotiations have also proved to be
time-consuming and complicated."
</P>
<P>
"We are now seeing a new determined push by China to conclude
its membership of the WTO as rapidly as possible," largely as a
result of China's wish to be a member of the WTO and to join the
new multilateral negotiations as a full and equal partner, he
observed, adding that similar situations occurred during the
Uruguay Round and before the establishment of the WTO in January
1995.
</P>
<P>
However, he noted, this time the difference seems to be that,
along with China, WTO members also regard the months ahead as "a
window of opportunity" to bring China into the WTO.
</P>
<P>
"This may spring from the conviction that failure would lead to
an indefinite delay and that China's continued absence from the
WTO would adversely affect both the international trading system
and Members' bilateral trading relationships with China," he
added.
</P>
<P>
"I consider this shared perception a very positive development
because it may be just the catalyst that we need to bring about
flexibility and accommodation between China and its trading
partners," he said.
</P>
<P>
Political inputs will be easier to make if the principal
constituents involved in the negotiations, namely the
international trading community, can agree on the terms and
conditions of China's entry, Kim said, adding that "this will also
have to be matched with the needs and requirements of China
itself."
</P>
<P>
"The balance therefore is a delicate and difficult one. An
added consideration is that the window of opportunity, though
immediate, is a short one," he said. "Herein lies the challenge.
The WTO stands to benefit substantially if this challenge is met
creatively and constructively." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990318.0014 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Accuses Serbs of ``Not Negotiating Seriously'' </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, March 17 (Xinhua) -- The spokesman of the United States
State Department James Rubin accused on Wednesday the Serb
delegation of ``not negotiation seriously'' at the peace
conference on Kosovo in Paris.
</P>
<P>
Rubin made the statement on the CNN after meeting with the
president of the Kosovo Albanian delegation Hashim Thaqi and the
U.S. mediator Christopher Hill.
</P>
<P>
He said that Hill told him the Serbs were not negotiating
seriously.
</P>
<P>
``They not only refuse to discuss the crucial problem
concerning the military aspects of implementing the agreement, but
also have re-opened a series of political questions which we think
were resolved in the last phase of the talks in Rambouillet,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
He also accused the Serbian leaders of refusing to recognize
``a state of rebellion'' in Kosovo, which he said was caused by
the attacks the Serbs launched in the past few months, and said
that the situation in the field is worsening continuously.
</P>
<P>
``The Kosovars have taken a courageous decision by accepting
peace, while the Serbs are continuing to attack and kill innocent
people in Kosovo,'' said Rubin.
</P>
<P>
He said he would invite the Kosovo Albanian leaders headed by
Thaqi, who is a member of the Kosovo Liberation Army separatist
force, to go to Washington and meet with U.S. leaders.
</P>
<P>
If the Serbs reject the peace proposal, it is up to NATO to
decide what will happen, he said.
</P>
<P>
The talks on Kosovo remained deadlocked on Wednesday as the
Serb delegation refuse to accept the military part of the peace
agreement, which calls for the deployment of up to 30,000 NATO
troops in Kosovo to guarantee the implementation of the plan of
autonomy.
</P>
<P>
The Serb delegation has also asked that some amendments be made
in the political part of the agreement.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Russia has called on the Serbs to adopt a
``constructive attitude'' so that an agreement can be reached at
the conference in Paris. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
