<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Somali Warlord, Businessmen Resume Fighting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Serious fighting has once again
resumed between the militiamen of warlord Muse Sudi Yalahow and
others funded by the business communities of Abgal clan at
Galgalato area, about five km north of capital Mogadishu on
Wednesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The thunderous noise of the rocket propelled grenades,
anti-tank recoilless rifles and heavy machine guns are heard
throughout the capital, creating a new round of fear especially
among the people of north Mogadishu, sources in the Somali capital
said.
</P>
<P>
Stray rounds of the anti-aircraft machine guns have reached
Mogadishu's second largest market in Karan district and the busy
intersection of Sana.
</P>
<P>
There are no casualty figures available at the moment. However,
the noise of the heavy exchange of gunfire is getting closer and
closer to Mogadishu, an indication that Yalahow's battle wagons
are retreating from the capital to their base at the residence of
their warlord, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
Unlike Yalahow, the businessmen are having more efficient
battle wagons with unlimited resources.
</P>
<P>
The reason for the renewed fighting is not known, nevertheless,
reports close to the Abgal clan traditional elders and business
communities indicate that negotiations between the two sides in
the past three days had deadlocked.
</P>
<P>
The traditional elders seemed to have accepted the logic of the
 businessmen who say that they should not pay any tax to any of
the politicians of the capital so as to defend their position of
neutrality.
</P>
<P>
Yalahow, who controls the militiamen fighting against the
businessmen, has claimed that he has the right to impose taxes
which he characterized as acceptable and reasonable following his
claim of eradicating the bandits along the roads leading to the
market a few days ago.
</P>
<P>
Serious fighting between the two sides has led to the closure
of Karan market for three days, claiming the lives of more than 14
 people while the wounded had exceeded 40. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
