<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean Opposition Party Petitions Parliament </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, March 17 (Xinhua) -- The National Constitutional
Assembly (NCA) of Zimbabwe Wednesday petitioned parliament to bar
the government from appointing individuals to a proposed
constitutional commission without consulting other stake-holders.
</P>
<P>
A statement signed by NCA coordinator, Isaac Maposa, was being
distributed to legislators imploring them to debate and pass a
motion on the merits of instituting a commission of inquiry
without adhering to conditions the assembly set.
</P>
<P>
These conditions included that constitutional reforms process
is broad- based and has support of all stake-holders and that it
is legitimate, transparent and not dictated by one party or group.
</P>
<P>
"The government involvement must be facilitative rather than
determinative," the NCA said.
</P>
<P>
The petition came at a time when the government's chief
constitutional negotiator, Minister without Portfolio Eddison
Zvobgo, gave the NCA an ultimatum to come up with options to its
intention to appoint a commission of inquiry immediately by
Thursday or the government would go it alone.
</P>
<P>
"We urge you to seriously consider the implications of setting
up such a commission of inquiry without consulting and considering
the alternative viewpoint by the NCA and other stake-holders," the
petition read.
</P>
<P>
The assembly's view is, a national conference to agree on and
define the process of drawing up a new national constitution
should be convened at which chosen representatives of people would
draw up an appropriate legal framework for an effective and
participatory constitution-making process, the Zimbabwe News
Agency Ziana said.
</P>
<P>
That framework should be independent of the government or
ruling party influence, said the NCA.
</P>
<P>
The government has argued against this suggestion saying it
needs more time than was available before the year 2000 general
elections. 
</P>
</TEXT>
