<HEADLINE> Iran's Non-Oil Exports Drop by 4 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Iran's non-oil exports fell by 4
percent in the first 11 months of the current Iranian calendar
year ending March 20 on a year-to-year basis, a senior Iranian
official said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Head of the Export Promotion Center of Iran Mojtaba Khosrowtaj
said the non-oil exports earned the country 2.704 billion
U.S. dollars, a slight drop from the 2.820 billion in the same
period last Iranian year, the Islamic Republic News Agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
Iran expected to make 5 billion dollars from non-oil exports
this Iranian year, but the non-oil exports showed a negative
growth in value during the first two quarters, mainly caused by
the fall in oil prices and its by-products.
</P>
<P>
In the third quarter, the exports shew an increase in value and
the upward trend continued in the last three months as oil price
recovered slightly.
</P>
<P>
Khosrowtaj said 1,181,569 tonnes of goods, with an estimated
value of 270 million dollars were exported in February, showing a
rise of 51 percent in weight and 32 percent in value compared with
the same month last Iranian year.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian government has taken some steps to revive the
country's non-oil exports, which have fallen since 1995 when the
then government imposed strict restrictions on the outflow of hard
currency.
</P>
<P>
In January, the Iranian cabinet decided to cede the policy-making
authority on exports to a special council in order to inject new
energy to the country's stagnant non-oil exports.
</P>
<P>
The High Council for Non-Oil Exports, instead of the cabinet,
will have the authority to make decisions on policies concerning
non-oil exports, reports said earlier. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
