<HEADLINE> Burundi Factions Agree on Refugees' Security </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, March 17 (Xinhua) -- All the Burundi warring
factions have agreed that security should be guaranteed to the
repatriation of Burundi refugees and internally displaced people
to their homes.
</P>
<P>
Sources in Tanzanian northern town of Arusha said Wednesday that
 delegates from the just concluded 10-day committees meeting on
Burundi peace process agreed that the refugees's return should be
voluntary and organized.
</P>
<P>
Hashim Mbita, spokesman for the peace facilitator Julius
Nyerere, told a press conference that the committees insisted that
refugees should not be forced to return immediately after a final
peace agreement is reached possibly in June.
</P>
<P>
They also agreed that refugees should be regularly briefed on
the ongoing peace process and be actively involved in any plans
for their repatriation.
</P>
<P>
The delegates welcomed an up-coming tripartite commission
meeting late this month by Tanzania, Burundi and the United
Nations High Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR).
</P>
<P>
Reports say that there are about 200,000 Burundi refugee
sheltered in western Tanzania at present stage.
</P>
<P>
The committees' meeting was facilitated by Nyerere, the founding
 President of Tanzania, who urged all delegates to speed up their
work so as to reach a feasible peace agreement in the fifth round
of talks expected in June. 
</P>
