<HEADLINE> Lebanese School Teachers Strike for Higher Pay </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Public high school teachers
throughout Lebanon went on an open-ended strike Wednesday to
demand better end-of-service payments.
</P>
<P>
The teachers, some of whom held a sit-in in front of the
parliament building, were demanding that end-of-service pay be
100 percent of their final salaries in the new pay scale
bill for the public sector, which was passed by the Parliament
last November.
</P>
<P>
But, the bill states that end-of-service payments will only
be calculated on 85 percent of the teachers' final salaries.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the teachers held similar strikes but suspended
later in the wake of the transfer of the country's regime, which
was taken over by President Emile Lahoud.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Salim Hoss has set up a three-member committee
to study teachers' demands.
</P>
<P>
The strike has reportedly halted classes for some 350,000
students across the country, but those in 800 private schools are
not affected. 
</P>
