<HEADLINE> Egypt, Uganda Sign Memo on Boosting Investment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Egypt and Uganda on Wednesday
signed a memorandum of understanding on boosting investment,
promoting cooperation in free trade zones and accelerating free
movement of capital.
</P>
<P>
Ibrahim Fawzi, chairman of Egypt's General Authority for
Investment and Free Zones, said at the signing ceremony that Egypt
and Uganda would promote reciprocal investments and set up
investment offices in both Cairo and Kampala.
</P>
<P>
The investment authorities of the two countries would supervise
the implementation of an agreement on avoidance of dual taxation,
which was signed last October, Fawzi said.
</P>
<P>
He said investment is badly needed by the two countries in the
fields of food industry, agriculture, infrastructure, health care,
tourism and power projects.
</P>
<P>
After the ceremony, Fawzi discussed with visiting Ugandan
Industry and Trade Minister Moussa Ali ways of expanding bilateral
trade and launching more joint projects, Egypt's Middle East News
Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Their talks also covered air freight exchange, promotion of air
transport and means of encouraging private sectors to join in
bilateral economic cooperation programs and encouraging Uganda to
launch more industrial projects in Egypt's free zones.
</P>
<P>
Egypt has set up six free trade zones in Cairo, Ismailia, Suez,
Alexandria, Port Said and Damietta in an effort to attract foreign
investments in export-oriented industries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
