<HEADLINE> Rwanda, Uganda Renew Commitment to DRC Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Rwanda and Uganda have renewed
their commitment to the peaceful settlement of the seven-month
civil war rocking the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC), a joint
communique between the two countries said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The communique was issued at the end of Ugandan President
Yoweri Museveni's two-day visit to Rwanda.
</P>
<P>
Museveni arrived in the Rwandan capital Kigali on Tuesday, and
has held talks with his counterpart, Pasteur Bizimungu, and
vice-president Major General Paul Kagame.
</P>
<P>
While reiterating their "already publicly stated legitimate
involvement" in the DRC crisis, both sides regretted that little
progress has been made because the rebels have been denied
participation in direct talks, the Rwanda News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
President Museveni said that Uganda sent troops to DRC to fight
Sudanese terrorism, while Bizimungu recalled that Rwanda went
there to fight the Interahamwe militia and the former government
forces.
</P>
<P>
Museveni's visit to Rwanda, the fourth since the beginning of
the year, came at a time when the rebels are steadily advancing on
several key towns in the southeast, northwest, and east of the
DRC.
</P>
<P>
Rwanda and Uganda also expressed concern about the conflict
tearing apart the Horn of Africa, and decided to send a joint
delegation to Ethiopia and Eritrea.  
</P>
