<HEADLINE> Ethiopia to Build Dams to Supply Water to Capital </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, March 17 (Xinhua) -- The Addis Ababa Water and
Sewerage Authority announced Wednesday that two huge dams will be
constructed on Sivilu and Gerbi rivers at a cost of some four
billion birr (515 million U. S. dollars) to supply safe drinking
water to the Ethiopian capital and its environs.
</P>
<P>
A report from the Ethiopian News Agency quoted the authority as
saying that the dam to be constructed on the Sivilu River would
enable the supply of 600,000 cubic meter water per day, which is
four times the volume being supplied to the capital by Legedadi
River.
</P>
<P>
According to the authority, the feasibility study and site
survey have been finalized while the design work is well underway.
</P>
<P>
Addis Ababa is a water shortage city and the daily water supply
is about two-thirds of the needs. The Akaki ground water project,
which will be finalized after four months, will help generate
72,000 cubic meter water every day. 
</P>
