<HEADLINE> World Economy Expected to Grow 2.2 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, March 17 (Xinhua)--The world economy will grow by 2.2 per
cent in this year and 3.1 percent in year 2000, a German economy
institute predicted on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Kiel Institute of World Economy expected Germany's gross
domestic product (GDP) to increase by 1.6 percent, slowing down
from the 2.8 per cent growth rate in 1998.
</P>
<P>
The economy of industry countries are expected to expand by 2.1
per cent in 1999, with West Europe growing by 1.8 per cent and the
United States 3.3 per cent.
</P>
<P>
East Asian nations' GDP will grow by 4.2 per cent in 1999, and
in year 2000 will accelerate to 5.7 per cent, the institute said
in its bulletin.
</P>
<P>
Although economic downswing is threatening Germany, the
institute ruled out possibility of a recession, saying that
general conditions of German economy remain favorable, and the
monetary policy of European Central Bank (ECB) will back up the
economy better.
</P>
<P>
The jobless in Germany will be 4.04 million this year and fall
to 3.8 million in 2000, the institute said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
