<HEADLINE> Ghana Works for Early Detection of Diseases </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, March 17 (Xinhua)--Ghana's Ministry of Health will
start recruiting and training volunteers in seven regions in the
development of a community based surveillance system which aims
at early detection and control of diseases.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters in Accra on Wednesday, George Amofah,
deputy director of public health, said the volunteers would
collaborate with sub- district health authorities in data
collection on diseases and report events such as unusual deaths,
the Ghana News Agency reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Other responsibility of the volunteers will be to report on
non-disease situation in addition to keeping a community register
of births and deaths.
</P>
<P>
Amofah said, "Surveillance involves data collection, analysis,
 interpretation and the action needed to contain epidemics."
</P>
<P>
 He said the program which has been piloted in the three
northern regions is being extended to the other regions and would
help in general disease control and also serve as tool to check
epidemics.
</P>
<P>
The national program is yet to take off because volunteers
would have to be trained to detect symptoms of diseases while
training manuals would also have to be developed for them.
</P>
<P>
The western, ashanti, central and greater accra regions have
already started corporating the community based surveillance
system into their plan of action on a small scale.
</P>
<P>
The program will cover a wide range of diseases since every
community or region is known to have locally endemic diseases such
as guineaworm and buruli ulcer which are common in certain parts
of the country.
</P>
<P>
Amofah said that non-communicable diseases such as cancer,
diabetes, hypertension and other cardio-vascular diseases, which
are not opened to community action will continue to be handled by
health institutions.
</P>
<P>
 The non communicable diseases program at the Korle Bu
Teaching Hospital aims at educating and reaching the larger public
through the formation of associations such as the Diabetes
Association of Ghana to help in the early detection and management
of these public health problems. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
