<DOCNO> XIE19990318.0028 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Legionnaire's Disease Kills 13 in Netherlands </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, March 17 (Xinhua) -- An outbreak of Legionnaire's
disease in the Netherlands has killed 13 people so far, official
from Dutch Ministry of Health said in The Hague on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The bacterial infection was traced to a flower show in
Bovenkarpsel, 40 miles north of Amsterdam. Last month, some 80,000
people visited the weeklong Westfriese Flora show. Now the Dutch
government is trying to trace visitors of the show and determine
the exact source of the bacteria.
</P>
<P>
The Dutch ministry official, Mr. Benno Bruggink, told Xinhua
that 200 patients have so far been reported to the ministry, 54 of
them were confirmed to have contracted Legionnaire's disease,
which is caused by the legionella bacterium. All the patients'
symptoms just look like influenza and pneumonia, he said.
</P>
<P>
So far, the results of the bacteriological test are not yet
known in the other 146 cases, Bruggink said. Earlier, Health
Minister Els Borst said she was deeply shocked by such an
epidemic. "We will do our utmost to ensure there is never a
recurrence of this sort of outbreak," she said.
</P>
<P>
Last week, the Dutch health authorities informed the World
Health Organization (WHO) of the legionella infection, as too many
people including foreign tourists visited the flower show.
</P>
<P>
Dutch experts believe that the bacteria stemmed from a fountain
which served as a centerpiece of exhibits. The disease derives
from bacteria in water.
</P>
<P>
Usually, several national flower shows are held throughout the
western Netherlands each spring, when the 6-billion-US-dollar
annual Dutch cut flower and bulb industry shows off its wares.
</P>
<P>
Bruggink confirmed that only five deaths were directly caused
by Legionnaire's disease, although eight others who had visited
the show since have died. He also said this is a very rare
disease. Last year, of the 40 ministry registered cases, 40
percent of the patients were foreigners who came to the
Netherlands as tourists, he added.
</P>
<P>
The country's National Institute of Public Health and the
Environment has started a large-scale investigation into the
source of the infection in the city of Stede Broec, part of which
belongs to Bovenkarspel. The institute has written to 5,000
visitors to the show over the age of 40, advising them to have a
urine test.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, local prosecutors are considering whether criminal
charges should be brought.
</P>
<P>
Legionnaire's disease was first discovered after an outbreak at
a convention of the American Legion in Pennsylvania in 1976, when
about 180 people fell ill and 20 died of the rare disease.
</P>
<P>
The bacteria that are believed to cause the illness are found
in soil and grow in air-conditioning ducts, storage tanks and
rivers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990318.0029 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-17 19:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UAE Urges Iran to Withdraw From Disputed Islands </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, March 17 (Xinhua) -- The United Arab Emirates (UAE) on
Wednesday called on Iran to withdraw its troops from three
disputed islands in the Gulf, Egypt's Middle East News Agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the opening session of the 111th Arab League Foreign
Ministers Council, UAE Foreign Minister Rashid Abdullah al-Nuaimi
said it is an illusion for Iran to keep good relations with the
Arab countries while maintaining "occupation of Arab land."
</P>
<P>
Al-Nuaimi criticized Tehran for defying the Arab will.
</P>
<P>
The UAE and Iran have been entangled in disputes over the
sovereignty of the islands of Abu Musa, Greater and Lesser Tunb at
the mouth of the strategic Strait of Hormuz.
</P>
<P>
The two countries have expressed readiness to solve the problem
through peaceful means. The UAE has proposed to determine the
sovereignty of the islands through international arbitration while
Iran insists on resolving the disputes by direct negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Al-Nuaimi said his country welcomes Iran's recent political
orientation, which he termed as positive. He voiced his country's
readiness to interact with it.
</P>
<P>
However, the UAE official said Iran's orientation has been
shadowed by its occupation of Arab territories, construction of
military and civilian facilities on the islands and launching of
naval exercises in the Gulf. 
</P>
