<HEADLINE> Italy Hopes to Link Egypt With NATO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Italy on Wednesday expressed hope
that it would be a link between Egypt and the North Atlantic
Treaty Organization (NATO) members.
</P>
<P>
There has been a tendency to boost cooperation between Egypt
and NATO members, visiting Italian Defense Minister Carlo
Scognamiglio told reporters after meeting with Egyptian
President Hosni Mubarak.
</P>
<P>
Terming NATO as "a defensive alliance," Scognamiglio said the
military bloc applies a new concept of expanded defense, which he
said has gone beyond Europe to regions close to Europe as well.
</P>
<P>
He called for NATO members to promote close cooperation with
Mediterranean countries in a bid to maintain regional peace,
stability and prosperity.
</P>
<P>
Egypt is a key player in helping keep peace and stability in the
Middle East and the Arab world, said the Italian minister.
</P>
<P>
Scognamiglio, who arrived here on Monday for a four-day visit,
said his ongoing trip is aimed at enhancing military ties between
the two countries.
</P>
<P>
"There is successful cooperation between Italy and Egypt," the
official said, adding that his country is looking forward to
further cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Egypt and Italy share identical views on international and
regional issues and they have witnessed tangible progress in military
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Italy joined Egypt and France in 1996 to stage naval exercises
every two years.
</P>
<P>
Italy has also pledged to support Egypt in its efforts to
remove land mines from the area of Alamein on the Mediterranean
coast under a memorandum of understanding signed a year ago.
</P>
<P>
Millions of land mines placed during the World War II remain
buried in the Alamein area, posing threats to people's life and
hindering development projects in the area. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
