<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> DaimlerChrysler Unveils Fuel Cell Compact Car </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 17 (Xinhua) -- DaimlerChrysler AG, the
world's fifth largest automaker, unveiled Wednesday a
newly-developed compact car powered by fuel cells, moving one step
closer to the company's goal of selling fuel cell vehicles by
2004.
</P>
<P>
The Necar 4 (New Electric Car), based on the Mercedes-Benz
A-class compact car, can seat five people, go 450 kilometers
before refueling and travel as fast as 145 kilometers per hour.
</P>
<P>
The car is the latest demonstration of progress on fuel cell
cars as the world's automakers continue their race to bring such
cars to the market by 2004. Fuel cells convert hydrogen and oxygen
into electricity to power a vehicle.
</P>
<P>
Fuel cell energy generated from hydrogen is the easiest to
produce, eliminates all carbon dioxide emissions, and produces
greater efficiencies than gasoline, diesel or methanol,
DaimlerChrysler said.
</P>
<P>
"Necar 4 is a major breakthrough in fuel cell because we've
developed a very powerful fuel cell system small enough to be
packaged in a compact car," said Dr. Ferdinand Panik, head of
DaimlerChrysler's fuel cell project.
</P>
<P>
"With Necar 4, we have already proven that fuel cell technology
is viable," said Bob Eaton, chairman of DaimlerChrysler. "Now, we
are working to make the technology affordable for every consumer."
</P>
<P>
"Fuel cells have the potential to be the most attractive
alternative propulsion system for the long term," said Juergen
Schrempp, also chairman of DaimlerChrysler.
</P>
<P>
DaimlerChrysler officials said the concept car would be
replaced with Necar X, which would run on methanol. Methanol
contains hydrogen and is the auto industry's favored fuel to power
fuel cells.
</P>
<P>
But DaimlerChrysler engineers say there is still a lot of work
to be done before next year, when they aim to develop a fleet of
demonstration cars based on the Necar X.
</P>
<P>
For example, the car is 1,100 pounds heavier than an equivalent
gas-powered car because of the fuel-cell technology. Engineers say
it must be 660 pounds lighter.
</P>
<P>
The fuel cells are also 10 times too expensive, engineers say.
For example, using current technology, a mass produced fuel cell
car would cost about 30,000 U.S. dollars just for the fuel cell
hardware alone.
</P>
<P>
Other companies -- including Ford Motor, General Motors and
Honda -- also said they hope to market fuel cell vehicles by 2004.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
