<DOCNO> XIE19990318.0034 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa to Readjust Size of Provincial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Three provincial
legislatures would be smaller and two will gain seats after this
year's general election, the Independent Electoral Commission
(IEC) decided Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The I EC determined that the Gauteng legislature would lose 13
seats, bringing it down to 73 members.
</P>
<P>
The Western Cape legislature would have 39 members compared to
42 at present, while the North West legislature is to be cut by
one seat, leaving it with 33 members.
</P>
<P>
The Eastern Cape legislature would grow from 52 to 63 members,
and that of the Northern Province from 40 to 49.
</P>
<P>
The KwaZulu-Natal legislature retained its current 80 seats.
The legislatures of the Free State, Mpumalanga, and Northern Cape
remained unchanged at 30 seats each.
</P>
<P>
The adjustments were based on the 1996 population census, said
the IEC.
</P>
<P>
The number of seats in the National Assembly would remain at
400, the IEC decided.
</P>
<P>
The IEC has rejected calls by political parties for bigger
legislatures in Gauteng, Free States and Western Cape.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
