<HEADLINE> Foreign Country Behind Killing of Top Shiite </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Iraq annnounced on Wednesday
that clerics from a foreign country were involved in the
asssassination of Iraq's most senior Shiite cleric Mohammed
Mohammed Sadiq al-Sader.
</P>
<P>
In a communique read on Iraq's national television, Iraqi
General Security Directorate said Iraqi security authorities
had arrested four assassins including Iraqis and clerics from a
foreign country, adding another assassin is still at large.
</P>
<P>
But he did not name the foreign country.
</P>
<P>
Grand Ayatollah Mohammed Mohammed Sadiq al-Sader and two of
his sons were assassinated on February 19 in Iraq's southern
province of Najaf.
</P>
<P>
In a program broadcast on Iraqi national television, Sheikh
Abdul Hassan Abbas al-Kufi, one of the assassins, confessed
he had disputes with al-Sader on moral and religious issues and
this made him get involved in the assassination of al-Sader.
</P>
<P>
Another assassin, Ahmed Mustafa Hassan al-Ardabily confessed
he worked in the Supreme Council of the Islamic Revolution in
Tehran, Iran from 1991 until 1994.
</P>
<P>
After al-Sader's assassination, some western agencies reported
of riots in southern Iraq and clashes between Shiites and the
police. However, the Iraqi government dismissed these reports as
groundless and untrue.
</P>
<P>
Al-Sader was close to the Iraqi government which appointed him
the grand ayatollah to replace the late Abul Qassim al-Khoei
in 1992.
</P>
<P>
In a move seen as an attempt to distance himself from the
government and establish him as an independent leader, Sader
issued an edict six months ago calling on the Shiites to attend
weekly Friday prayers in mosques. The secular government
disapproved of big crowds.
</P>
<P>
Al-Sader enjoyed high respect among Shiites who account for about
65 percent of Iraq's 22 million people. President Saddam Hussein
and most of Iraq's senior officials belong to the minority
Sunni Muslims. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
