Wednesday that it was "concerned" over Yugoslav troops movements
in and near Kosovo and warned NATO's patience was "growing
thin".
</P>
<P>
"We're obviously very concerned about what we're seeing in
terms of military movements by Serbia. It's a matter of serious
concern to us and it's something that the Serbs have heard
directly from us about our concerns," said White House deputy
National Security Adviser James Steinberg.
</P>
<P>
Yugoslavia on Tuesday asked a substantive changes to a
U.S.-drafted peace deal on Kosovo, which was rejected by the
so-called Contact Group that presided over the peace talks in
Paris between the Serbs and ethnic Albanians.
</P>
<P>
Ethnic Albanians have agreed to sign the peace deal and the
talks were deadlocked as the Serbs refused to let foreign troops
in their sovereign territory of Kosovo as NATO had demanded.
</P>
<P>
Steinberg said NATO's patience was growing thin, and repeated
warning of bombing Yugoslav targets if Belgrade does not give up
its sovereignty in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
"The president has made very clear that if Serbian
intransigence and continued aggression causes this peace effort
to fail, there will be consequences, and we are watching it very
closely," Steinberg told reporters. 
