<HEADLINE> Central African Republic to Honor Peace Accord </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, March 17 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Security Council
Wednesday called upon all political leaders of the Central African
Republic to join hand in order to promote the peace process in the
African country.
</P>
<P>
In a statement read to the press here, the president of the
15-member Security Council, Qin Huasun of China, said, "The
members of the Council expect President (Ange Felix) Patasse to
honor his commitments to implement the Bangui Agreements and the
National Reconciliation Pact, and calls on political leaders of
the Central African Republic to work jointly for the full
implementation."
</P>
<P>
The statement came after the Security Council was briefed by
the special representative of the secretary-general, Oluyeme
Adeniji, on the latest developments in the country.
</P>
<P>
"The members of the Council call on the Government, in
collaboration with all political parties, to take concrete steps
to establish the new electoral commission for the presidential
elections, and encourages the Government to continue the efforts
on restructuring its security forces," he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, "the members of the Council appeal to the
international community to contribute to the Trust Fund for the
CAR (Central African Republic)," he said.
</P>
<P>
"The members of the Council commend and support the efforts of
the special representative of the secretary-general and the
MINURCA (the United Nations Mission in the Central African
Republic)," he said.
</P>
<P>
In a February 18 presidential statement, the Security Council
decided unanimously to call on all political parties in the
Central African Republic to resume constructive dialogue in order
to achieve national reconciliation at an early date.
</P>
<P>
Under the Bangui Agreement, signed in January 1997, the
Government of the Central African Republic committed itself to a
number of reforms, of which the most important, concerning the
restructuring of the armed forces and the adoption of measures to
strengthen the economy, remain to be accomplished. 
</P>
</TEXT>
