<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 17 (Xinhua) -- A Protestant paramilitary group,
the Red Hand Defenders, blamed a rival faction the Ulster
Volunteer Force for the killing of a hardliner in Northern Ireland
on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Red Hand Defenders said Frankie Curry, a former leading
member of a Protestant "loyalist" guerrilla group, the Red Hand
Commando, was killed by the UVF and said it would "take military
action" against several leading loyalists, according to BBC
television report.
</P>
<P>
Curry was shot dead as he walked along a path in a stronghold
of pro-British Protestant loyalists.
</P>
<P>
Curry, released from prison on Monday, was said to have been
linked with dissidents, including the Red Hand Defenders, who
oppose the peace accord for the British province and ceasefires by
mainstream loyalist militias. The Red Hand Defenders were
responsible for the murdering of a prominent Catholic lawyer on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
The new violence would further cast shadow over the fragile
peace process in Northern Ireland which was stalled by the
decommissioning issues. 
