<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, March 17 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
DOHA -- Qatar has announced its annual exports of liquefied
natural gas will exceed 11 million tonnes by mid-1999.
</P>
<P>
Qatari Minister of Energy and Industry Abdullal Bin Hamad
Al-Attiya made the remarks at a conference on petroleum and gas in
Doha, the Arabic daily Alam Al Yom reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Qatar, owning the third biggest gas reserves in the world, has
invested tens of billions of U.S. dollars to exploit the resources.
</P>
<P>
RIYADH -- Some Gulf states which depend on crude oil for
operating their water desalination plants may have to import the
relatively cheap natural gas from Qatar, former Saudi Petroleum
Minister Ahmed Zaki Yamani has said.
</P>
<P>
Yamani said Saudi Arabia consumes 275,000 barrels of petroleum
a day, and Kuwait 50,000 barrels a day, to generate electricity to
operate the water desalination plants, indicating that they may
save their valuable resources should they import Qatari gas to do
the job, the Alam Al Yom reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
KUWAIT -- Nine world companies submitted offers to the Kuwaiti
Petroleum Establishment to build a factory to separate sulphur
from disel at Al Ahmadi port refinery.
</P>
<P>
According to the Alam Al Yom published Wednesday, the
construction of the new factory will cost about 125 million
dollars.
</P>
<P>
The factory, when in operation, can handle 70,000 barrels per
day in addition to the production of disel fuel with a low
percentage of sulphur and other aromatic components.
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- Lebanon's imports fell to a five-year low in February
to reach 472 million dollars, the Daily Star reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
It was the second consecutive month that imports fell, with
February's imports 5 percent less than the 495 million dollars in
January.
</P>
<P>
Exports in February rose to 52 million dollars, up 11 percent
compared with January.
</P>
<P>
Italy and Saudi Arabia remained Lebanon's top supplier and
buyer of goods respectively. 
</P>
</TEXT>
