<HEADLINE> Turkey Urges Europeans to Ban Pro-Rebel TV </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Turkey has taken another step in
urging European countries to ban pro-Kurdish media organizations
that support the outlawed Kurdish Workers' Party (PKK).
</P>
<P>
The Foregin Ministry summoned German Ambassador Hans Joachim
Vergau and British Embassy Charge d'Affairs Hugh Mortimer to the
ministry Wednesday morning.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Ministry deputy spokesman Sermet Atacanli said
they were summoned for urging their governments to take more
actions banning organizations such as Med TV, the daily Ozgur
Politika and the DEM news agency, which spread the propaganda of
the PKK.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has intensified efforts to have these media groups
banned, particularly following the capture of PKK leader Abdullah
Ocalan last month.
</P>
<P>
Following Ocalan's arrest, these organizations have been
encouraging Ocalan's sympathizers into carrying out bomb attacks in
Turkey, in which many innocent people were killed.
</P>
<P>
Atacanli added Turkey has long been trying to persuade the
host countries to close down the pro-Kurdish media organizations.
</P>
<P>
"There is no possibility to consider these organizations
within the framework of freedoms of press or expression," he
said.
</P>
<P>
The PKK has been since 1984 fighting a guerrilla war for an
independent Kurdish state in southeastern Turkey. 
</P>
</TEXT>
