<HEADLINE> S. Leone's Warring Sides to Hold Peace Talks in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, March 17 (Xinhua) -- A senior aide to Sierra Leonean
President Ahmed Tejan Kabbah said Wednesday in capital Freetown
that peace talks between the government and the rebels are likely
to take place in the first or second week of April.
</P>
<P>
A report reaching here Wednesday quoted the aide as saying that
"the venue is almost settled now. It will most probably be Lome,
the Togolese capital."
</P>
<P>
The presidential aide said that Revolutionary United Front
(RUF) leader Foday Sankoh who is being imprisoned in the capital
Freetown, instructed his field commanders by radio at the weekend
set up a team to meet him.
</P>
<P>
The team to be formed by Sankoh's military commander Sam
Bockarie will leave Sierra Leone for a third country in a week or
two, where the team will harmonize their position for forthcoming
negotiations with the government, the aide confirmed.
</P>
<P>
"One of the main problems left is for the RUF delegation to
meet with their leader and sort out their act to be able to
negotiate realistically," he said.
</P>
<P>
The rebel leaders will meet either in Lome of Togo or Abidjan
of Cote d'Ivoire before the peace talks start, the aide added.
</P>
<P>
Kabbah and his aides say the United States has been pushing the
latest peace talks and has offered to fly rebel commanders to a
third country.
</P>
<P>
Diplomats in Freetown said that both the Sierra Leonean
government and the rebels face intense foreign pressure to
negotiate.
</P>
<P>
Sankoh, who took up arms in 1991 and has since been fighting
successive governments, was sentenced to death last October over
the charge of treason.
</P>
<P>
A military junta overthrew the democratically-elected Kabbah
government in 1997 but the west African peacekeeping force known
as ECOMOG reinstated him in March 1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
