<HEADLINE> Russia Says U.S. ABM Bill Hinders START Treaties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, March 18 (Xinhua) -- The Russian Foreign Ministry said
Thursday that the bill passed by the U.S. Senate on the deployment
of a national anti-missile system undermines a whole series of
previously made agreements.
</P>
<P>
The deployment of such a system sets "a course for undermining
the 1972 ABM Treaty and the entire set of START agreements," the
ministry said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
"The ABM Treaty bans the deployment of such a system," the
document said.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. move "seriously jeopardizes the overall process of
curbing nuclear arms and strategic stability, for the sake of
which major international agreements have been drafted for
decades," the Interfax news agency quoted the statement as saying.
</P>
<P>
The statement noted that the U.S. Senate bill "urges the U.S.
Administration to elevate the creation of the nation-wide
anti-missile system to the level of national policy. It calls for
beginning deployment as early as is technically possible."
</P>
<P>
"Although Washington stresses that a decision on the system
will not be made before 2000, the very direction of the Senate's
actions cripple" the existing agreements in this sphere, the
statement said, adding that the ABM nd START agreements "are two
parts of the same thing."
</P>
<P>
The fact that a "possible reduction of strategic offensive
weapons depends on the execution of this treaty is stipulated in
the ABM, the START I and START II treaties," the statement said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990318.0050 </DOCNO>
