<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Gives Green Light to S. Korean Firms' Merger </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, March 18 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission said
here on Thursday that it has given the green light to two South
Korean companies for their merger.
</P>
<P>
The merger refers to the acquisition of Kia by Hyundai. Both
South Korean companies manufacture and sell motor vehicles
worldwide.
</P>
<P>
The commission said the merger will have only a limited affect
on the European Union (EU) market.
</P>
<P>
Hyundai Motor Company (HMC) has acquired control of the whole
Kia Motors Corporation (KMC). As a result, the transaction
constitutes a concentration under the EU Merger Law, the
commission said.
</P>
<P>
This transaction affects the EU passenger car sector as well as
those of vans under 3.5 tons and small buses.
</P>
<P>
The combined EU market for passenger cars of HMC and KMC is 1.3
percent, with exception for Greece, where the two South Korean
firms have 16 percent of the medium car share, according to the
commission.
</P>
<P>
Noting that HMC has a 9.6 percent share on the EU sport coupe
market with shares exceeding 40 percent in Greece and Spain, the
commission pointed out that the two firms' vans under 3.5 tons do
not exceed 2 percent of the average market share even though their
share in the Netherlands is 11.3 percent, and their small bus
market represents 0.2 percent in EU, with 2.3 percent in the
Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
The commission said the concentration is compatible with the EU
common market.
</P>
<P>
The EU executive commission resigned on Tuesday, but could not
leave its job until the EU member state governments appoint a new
team to replace it under the EU Treaty. The outgoing EU executive
body is still handling its day-to-day business, including
proposing and implementing laws. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
