<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 1500 GMT, March 18 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI -- Defense Minister George Fernandes said Thursday
that India had developed some nuclear protection systems.
</P>
<P>
In reply to questions at the Lower House of Parliament here, he
said that a number of protective systems capable of providing
individual and collective protection against contamination caused
by nuclear, biological and chemical (NBC) weapons have been
indigenously developed by Defense Research and Development
Organization (DRDO). (India-Nuke Protection)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
LONDON -- Northern Ireland erupted into fresh violence on
Wednesday night with nationalists, loyalists and police clashing
on the streets of Portadown, according to BBC report on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The unrest came as Catholic mourners prepared to pay their last
respects to lawyer Rosemary Nelson, who was killed by a car bomb
on Monday. A Protestant guerrilla group "Red Hand Defenders" later
claimed responsibility for the killing. (Britain-N.Ireland-
Clashes)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
YANGON -- The Myanmar government will provide Aung San Suu Kyi,
general secretary of the National League for Democracy (NLD), with
all possible assistance in joining her husband Michael Aris, who
is dying in England, if she decides to go, said an official
Information Sheet here Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
Michael Aris is seriously ill in England and has been
hospitalized with prostate cancer which has spread to his spine
and lungs, it said. (Myanmar-Aung San Suu Kyi)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ASMARA -- Fierce fighting between Ethiopia and Eritrea was
going on at Mereb-Setit near Badme, a senior Eritrean foreign
ministry official confirmed Thursday morning.
</P>
<P>
Tesfamariam Tekeste, head of the Afro-asia and Australia
Department of the ministry, told Xinhua in a telephone interview
that by 9:00 p.m. local time Wednesday, Eritrea had destroyed four
Ethiopian tanks, captured one other and destroyed three vehicles
armed with machine guns. (Eritrea-Fighting Going on)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Sudan on Thursday denied reports that it has agreed to
let its southern states break away from the north.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters on the sidelines of the 111th session of
the Arab League Council held here, Sudanese Minister of State for
Foreign Affairs Ali Abdel Rahman Numeiri dismissed the reports as
"bare of truth." (Egypt-Sudan-Denial) 
