<DOCNO> XIE19990318.0062 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hungary Imposes Fuel Tax on Vehicles Making Multi-entries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUDAPEST, March 18 (Xinhua) -- Hungary Wednesday began to
impose fuel tax on vehicles entering the country more than once a
day, as a means to crack down on fuel smuggling from neighboring
countries, where gasoline is cheaper, the local press reported.
</P>
<P>
Smugglers used to fill the tank of their vehicles with oil in
Ukraine, Romania or other neighboring countries, and then drove
into Hungary, where gasoline and diesel oil are under government
monopoly.
</P>
<P>
Smuggled fuel was usually sold to small gas stations and
individuals.
</P>
<P>
Investigation shows that before the tax imposition, one-third
of the 6,000 to 6,500 vehicles entering Hungary everyday smuggled
fuel more than once a day.
</P>
<P>
Up to now, about 130,000 liters of fuel was smuggled into the
country yearly, causing financial loss of 60 billion forints (261
million U.S. dollars) to the government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
