<HEADLINE> ASEAN Plus 3 Finance Ministers Meet in Hanoi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, March 18 (Xinhua) -- Deputy finance ministers and vice
central bank governors from the nine-member ASEAN plus China,
Japan and the Republic of Korea met here Thursday, emphasizing the
need to strengthen short-term capital flows monitoring.
</P>
<P>
The meeting agreed, according to a chairman statement of the
meeting released Thursday evening, "the forum is very important,
timely and very useful."
</P>
<P>
Participants, known as "9+3 meeting" on finance, exchanged
views on the ways to monitor short-term capital flows and on the
subject of international financial architecture.
</P>
<P>
The meeting noted that rapid movement of short-term capital
flow is one of the causes of the financial crisis and agreed to
work together to monitor the movement of capital flows to prevent
future crisis.
</P>
<P>
The meeting also noted efforts undertaken in various fora on
the issue of international financial architecture. The meeting
concluded that there has been a convergence of views on the issue,
particularly the need to involve emerging economies in the
process.
</P>
<P>
They agreed to maintain close cooperation in addressing these
issues and present the outcome to the forthcoming ASEAN Summit
later this year.
</P>
<P>
The convening of the "9+3 meeting" on finance was proposed by
Chinese Vice President Hu Jintao at the second informal summit of
East Asian countries last December.
</P>
<P>
China's Vice Finance Minister Jin Liqun and Vice Governor of
the People's Bank of China Xiao Gang led the Chinese delegation to
the meeting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
