<HEADLINE> African Youth Discuss Conflict Prevention </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, March 18 (Xinhua) -- Under the banner of "the role of
the youth on conflict prevention and resolution", over 20 African
youth leaders attended a Conference to discuss Conflict Prevention
and Resolution in the continent which opened here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The participants from Ethiopia, Uganda, Somalia, Kenya, South
Africa, Sudan, Eritrea, Burundi, Tanzania and the World Federation
of Democratic Youth, will air their views and share their
collective experiences and knowledge on conflict resolution.
</P>
<P>
In his opening speech, Chairman Mohiadin Shengeb of the
National Union of Eritrean Youth and Students, said the
conference provided them with a forum to discuss the role of youth
in building peace within their respective countries, with special
focus on the current Ethiopia-Eritrea border conflict and the
civil war in Sudan.
</P>
<P>
He said a youth peace network should be established which would
enable young women and men to become partners in the conflict
resolution and peace building process, and create a better
understanding of the causes to conflicts and the mechanisms used
to resolve them.
</P>
<P>
Shengeb urged that youth organizations in eastern and southern
Africa should often organize similar forums to discuss the
problems facing youth in this region of the world.
</P>
<P>
President Salah Eldin Elzain of the National Federation of
Sudanese Youth, said that the civil war in his country was the
result of colonial times and foreign interference, adding that
without foreign interference, the peace building process in Sudan
would go on smoothly.
</P>
<P>
During the three-day meeting, the participants will give their
 presentations on peace building in Somalia, Eritrea-Ethiopia
conflict, the civil war in Sudan and conflict resolution, and
have panel discussions.
</P>
<P>
Sponsored by the Swedish "Save the Children" Foundation, the
conference is organized by the National Union of Eritrean Youth
and Students. 
</P>
</TEXT>
