<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, March 18 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- Oil and mineral ministers of the Gulf Cooperation
Council (GCC) members will hold a consultative meeting in Vienna
on Tuesday to coordinate the position of GCC states on the agenda
of the ministerial conference of the Organization of Petroleum
Exporting Countries (OPEC).
</P>
<P>
According to Thursday's Arabic daily Al Hayat, the OPEC meeting
will discuss the planned cut in oil production, in collaboration
with non-OPEC states, of over 2 million barrels a day in order to
shore up oil prices.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Ahmed Abdulla Al Akiel, board chairman of the Arab
Bank for Economic Development in Africa, has agreed to offer new
loans to the tune of 425 million U.S. dollars to a number of
African states.
</P>
<P>
Of this amount, 407 million dollars will be used in financing
five projects, and 18 million dollars for technical cooperation.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egypt's Investments in industrial firms put into
operation in 1998 amounted to 11 billion Egyptian pounds (3.24
billion U.S. dollars), the country's Middle East News Agency
reported on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian Industry Minister Suleiman Reda told a seminar
organized by the Alexandria Businessmen Society late Wednesday
that 6 billion pounds (1.76 billion dollars) were invested in new
industrial towns and 5 billion pounds (1.47 billion dollars) in
various parts of the country.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israel's current-account deficit in 1998 plunged
by 46 percent to 2.3 billion U.S. dollars, according to figures
issued Thursday by the Central Bureau of Statistics (CBS).
</P>
<P>
Last year's capital transfers slid to 1.8 billion dollars from
2.2 billion in 1997, while newly accumulated foreign assets
dropped more than 50 percent, from 9.5 billion dollars in 1997 to
4.3 billion in 1998. 
</P>
