<DOCNO> XIE19990318.0079 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> African Ministers Meet on Education </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, March 18 (Xinhua) -- A two-day conference of the
African education ministers started in Harare Thursday, examining
developments in education in Africa and charting future courses of
action.
</P>
<P>
Before the conference, the three-day experts meeting ended
Wednesday with a lot of recommendations on the development of
African education.
</P>
<P>
more than 120 education ministers and experts from 52 member
states of the Organization of African Unity (OAU) attended the
conference. The ministers are expected to discuss and adopt the
Final Report on education in Africa, recommendations and Program
of Action of the Decade.
</P>
<P>
At the opening ceremony, Deputy Director-General of UNESCO
Colin Power said the ministers are about to approve and adopt the
Draft program of Action of the Decade of Education in Africa, and
this should be read as a sign of our continuing collaboration with
the African continent in the ever so crucial sector of education.
It is regarded as a positive contribution to attainment of the
endeavors of the African people on this threshold to the 21st
Century.
</P>
<P>
He said that the specific objectives of the conference were to
"examine developments in education in Africa since the beginning
of the 1999's and to chart future courses of action, within the
context of the OAU' Decade of Education in Africa (1997-2006) and
the United Nations Special Initiative for Africa."
</P>
<P>
Apart from establishing or strengthening adequately funded
pan-African mechanisms, Power said, the OAU Decade emphasizes
objectives of vital importance to UNESCO, namely: The need to
provide access to basic education to all, particularly to girls
and children of disadvantaged groups; The highest priority given
to the role, status and training of teachers; Quality education
obtained through adequate learning materials and assurance of
minimum levels of nutrition and an enlightened language policy;
The inclusion of basic skills such as dealing with HIV/AIDS,
drugs, human rights and preparation for the world of work and the
fundamental recasting of institutions of higher learning and
research.
</P>
<P>
The progress registered in literacy and in both primary and
secondary education enrolments during the 1960s stagnated and
receded during the 1980s, in face of the general deterioration of
social, political and economic conditions of most countries in the
African continent, he said.
</P>
<P>
The dominant trend in the education sector was that of lack of
infrastructure, low participation rates, disparities in access and
general limitation of resources for recurrent and capital
expenditure, said Power.
</P>
<P>
Most African governments are making great efforts to allocate
more resources to the education sector. Most African countries
have designated national coordinators, the UNESCO official said.
</P>
<P>
He wished to restate UNESCO's enthusiastic support for the
Decade for Education in Africa. 
</P>
</TEXT>
