<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WTO Hits Canada on Dairy Export Pricing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, March 18 (Xinhua) -- The World Trade Organization (WTO)
has outlawed a Canadian trade policy, zeroing on exports of
Canadian dairy products such as ice cream and cheese.
</P>
<P>
Canada's system of pricing its dairy exports at lower rates
than its domestic milk is classified as an illegal export subsidy
and must be fixed, the WTO ruled on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The ruling affects between 33 million to 66 million U.S.
dollars in Canada's dairy exports, or half of the total.
</P>
<P>
The WTO also condemned Canada's system of limiting milk imports
to the bags of groceries that consumers bring across the border.
</P>
<P>
The dairy ruling stems from a challenge from the United States
and New Zealand. The two countries criticized parts of the ruling
as an export subsidy, an accusation Ottawa denies.
</P>
<P>
The Canadian federal government says it will talk to the
provinces and industry to see if it should appeal.
</P>
<P>
"The (WTO) report deals only with some dairy exports and has no
effect on Canada's domestic supply management system," Canadian
Agriculture Minister Lyle Vanclief said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
"Canada is committed to supply management and will continue to
defend its dairy industry," added the minister. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990318.0083 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Eritrea Strives to Eliminate Illiteracy: Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ASMARA, March 18 (Xinhua) -- The Eritrean government is trying
to eliminate illiteracy in the country so that every child can go
to school, Minister of Education Osman Saleh said here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"Education is one of the factors for the development of the
country. It is central to producing skilled human resources,"
Osman told Xinhua in an interview here.
</P>
<P>
He said some 65 percent of the 3.5 million people in the horn
of Africa country are still illiterate, and that only 52 percent
of school-aged children have the chance to go to school.
</P>
<P>
To solve these problems, the Eritrean government is making
every effort to provide equity education, or equitable access to
education, to the whole population especially children, the
minister said.
</P>
<P>
The Eritrean government has set up more than 250 schools across
the country since independence in 1993, Osman said.
</P>
<P>
At present, there are a total of 741 schools with 385,000
students, from elementary schools to junior and senior secondary
schools, he said.
</P>
<P>
Every year, Eritrean schools enroll some 35,000 to 40,000
children, and accordingly, 30 to 50 new schools are established,
he added.
</P>
<P>
In elementary schools, pupils are taught in eight different
ethnic languages, which makes people happy and willing to receive
education, the minister noted.
</P>
<P>
Osman acknowledged that Eritrea is short of teachers in junior
schools. There are 7,800 teachers nationwide but the junior
secondary schools are still understaffed.
</P>
<P>
Usually, teachers in the secondary schools are staffed by
graduates from Eritrea's only two higher education institutions,
the University of Asmara and the Teachers Training Institute, both
of whom are located in the capital Asmara.
</P>
<P>
Each year some 400 to 600 students are graduated from these two
higher learning institutions. Those with degrees can teach in
senior secondary schools while others with diplomas can be
teachers in junior secondary schools, said the minster.
</P>
<P>
In fact, teachers are quite well paid -- for graduates from the
higher education institutions, the standard monthly wage is
equivalent to 225 U.S. dollars, Osman pointed out.
</P>
<P>
In order to overcome the staff shortage problem in junior
secondary schools, the government plans to set up one more
teachers training institute in the central Keren Province this
year. Several people have been sent to Europe and South Africa to
study for postgraduate degrees so that they could teach in the new
institute, which needs 35 teachers, he said.
</P>
<P>
Students graduated from this institute will be teachers in
basic education, the elementary schools and the junior secondary
schools, he added.
</P>
<P>
In addition to the human resources, the Eritrean government
also provides "big " financial and material support for education,
the minister said, but he did not give the specific figure.
</P>
<P>
Osman also said that dropouts only account for eight percent of
the students in his country. In capital Asmara, 51 percent of the
students are girls while nationally 43 percent of students are
girls.
</P>
<P>
The minister noted that his government pays much attention to
the idea of "from theory to practice," organizing all high school
students to spend 45 days in summer doing any kind of work, such
as afforestation and road construction.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the on-going conflict, the minister said that it
has little effect on schools, though it does affect the schools in
the border areas and affect the mentality of the parents. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990318.0084 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 </DATE_TIME>
