<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 132 Million People Above Age 60 In China Next Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, March 18 (Xinhua)-- China will have 132 million
people above the age of 60, or 10 percent of the population next
year, according to Yuan Xinli, vice-president of the China
National Committee on Aging.
</P>
<P>
Yuan told a press conference today that, by the end of last
year, China had 120 million people above 60, or 9.7 percent of the
population. China has half of Asia's elderly and a fifth of the
world's.
</P>
<P>
China is expected to have 280 million elderly by 2025, who will
account for 18.46 percent of its population. Yuan says that this
aging population means a growing need for businesses that cater to
the special needs of the elderly.
</P>
<P>
They will become a promising economic growth point and provide
ample room for Chinese and overseas businesses to use this
potential, he says. Shanghai is the first Chinese city with an
aging population, with 13 million people aged 60 or older,
accounting for 18 percent of the city's population.
</P>
<P>
The press conference was held to announce an international
welfare products fair to be held here October 3-6. The 6,000-sqare-
meter fair will attract companies producing medical equipment,
rehabilitation facilities, recreation and entertainment equipment,
and food and clothing for the elderly.
</P>
<P>
Insurance companies, schools, travel agencies, and retirement
home representatives will also participate. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990318.0086 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ADB Not to Provide Loans to India Now </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, March 18 (Xinhua) -- Resident representative of the
Asian Development Bank (ADB) Frank J. Polman said here Thursday
that the bank could not provide 1.3 billion U.S. dollars loans to
India at the moment for its power sector.
</P>
<P>
Talking to reporters, he said that the loans have been affected
due to the sanctions imposed on India after it conducted nuclear
tests in May last year.
</P>
<P>
"The loans will go through only after the sanctions on India
are lifted," he said.
</P>
<P>
Economic and technical feasibility reports on five loan
proposals aggregating about 1.3 billion dollars had been completed
and were in different phases of preparations with some almost
ready to go. The Board of Directors of ADB, however, will have to
approve the loans only after the sanctions were lifted, he further
said.
</P>
<P>
The existing loans were not affected, he added.
</P>
<P>
The five loan proposals are slated for disbursement in the next
three years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
