<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 12:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Palestinian Official Meets Foreign Diplomats in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, March 18 (Xinhua) -- Days after Israel exchanged
words with the European Union over the status of Jerusalem,
dozens of foreign diplomats, most of them from European
countries, Thursday met with a senior Palestinian official in
Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was held in the Oriental House in east Jerusalem,
which is serving as a representative office of the Palestinian
National Authority (PNA).
</P>
<P>
Diplomats from France, Holland and other European countries
met with PNA Minister for Jerusalem Affairs Faisal al-Husseini.
Other diplomats from Canada, Jordan and South Africa also took
part in the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Following the meeting, al-Husseini told reporters that the PNA
rejected Israel's position on the status of Jerusalem. He noted
that Jerusalem is the capital of the Palestinians in all aspects.
</P>
<P>
Al-Husseini stressed that Israel could not determine the fate of
Jerusalem without taking into account the Muslim and Christian
residents in the city.
</P>
<P>
He also said that the foreign diplomats will continue to visit
the Oriental House despite Israel's rejection.
</P>
<P>
Last week, German, currently holding the E.U. presidency, sent a
letter to Israeli Foreign Ministry reconfirming the EU's support
for the internationalization of Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
In response, Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu said
that Jerusalem is the eternal capital of Israel and any attempt to
undermine Israel's position on the issue will be rejected outright.
</P>
<P>
Israel also demanded the foreign diplomats refrain from
visiting the Oriental House and meeting with Palestinian officials
in Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Israel occupied the east Jerusalem from Jordan in the 1967
Mideast war and later annexed it. The Palestinians want to
establish an independent nation with east Jerusalem as its
capital.
</P>
<P>
Under peace agreements signed by the two sides, the status of
Jerusalem should be settled in the final status talks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
