<HEADLINE> Sudan Denies Reports on Possible Partition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, March 18 (Xinhua) -- Sudan on Thursday denied reports
that it has agreed to let its southern states break away from the
north.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters on the sidelines of the 111th session of
the Arab League Council held here, Sudanese Minister of State for
Foreign Affairs Ali Abdel Rahman Numeiri dismissed the reports as
"bare of truth."
</P>
<P>
Numeiri denounced the reports as "outside attempts" aimed at
splitting his country.
</P>
<P>
According to media reports, the Sudanese government was
considering a partition of the country into a Muslim north and a
Christian and animist south.
</P>
<P>
Sudanese rebel groups have been fighting for greater autonomy
in the south in a 16-year civil war. Peace talks between the
government and the rebel groups have so far yield no tangible
results.
</P>
<P>
Sudan is now seeking to "put its own house in order" and to
close ranks in an effort to "confront outside attempts" to
dismember the country, Numeiri said.
</P>
<P>
"In Sudan, we are in agreement on the settlement of the south
issue through a political dialog. Results will be presented at a
national referendum within the framework of a unified Sudan," he
added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
