<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Experts Warn Sea Level Rise Along Bay of Bengal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, March 18 (Xinhua) -- Experts on climate and environment
Thursday warned that 8.6 percent of the land on the coast of Bay
of Bengal would be totally submerged while 66.6 percent low-lying
area across Bangladesh is likely to become vulnerable if sea level
registers one meter rise due to global warming and green-house
effects.
</P>
<P>
At least 75 percent of the Sundarbans, the largest mangrove in
the world, situated in southwestern Bangladesh, might be lost if
the sea registers one meter rise and if the sea rises two meters
even parts of the capital Dhaka will be inundated, one expert
pointed out.
</P>
<P>
They expressed the view at an international seminar on "Sea
Level Rise and Sustainable Coastal Management", which is jointly
organized by the University of Asia-Pacific (Dhaka) and the
National Oceanographic and Maritime Institute.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh is greatly concerned about sea level rise and
coastal erosion, Bangladeshi Water Resources Minister Abdur Razzak
said while inaugurating the seminar here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"Though it is not very easy to predict quantitatively the exact
extent of sea level rise over the next 100 years, it is obvious
that even nominal sea level rise will inundate a considerable area
of the coastal Bay of Bengal region affecting agriculture,
forestry, cottage industry and pushing the coastal people at a
great peril," he said.
</P>
<P>
The shoreline along the coast of Bangladesh encompasses 7,720
kilometers and some 21 percent of the population live in the
coastal belts, he stated, adding that the sea level rise will
compel internal migration causing disruption and serious
socio-economic problems.
</P>
<P>
Stating government vision, Razzak said that the Bangladeshi
government is fully aware of the problem of sea level rise and is
keen to see that necessary efforts are taken both in public and
private sectors to address the major issues.
</P>
<P>
"The threat of sea level rise is very real and global in
nature, specifically for the countries with low-lying coastal
areas like Bangladesh," he observed.
</P>
<P>
The scientific community has predicted that potential change
(in climate) would be visible approximately in the year 2070 in
grains yields if green-house effects are not contained and global
warming process is not slowed down, said Dr. Ata Qureshi, director
of Global Environmental Programs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990318.0094 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ADB to Aid Health Care Project in Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, March 18 (Xinhua) -- The Asian Development Bank (ADB)
has approved a concessional loan of 40 million U.S. dollars from
its special fund to promote the primary health care (PHC) of the
urban poor in Bangladesh.
</P>
<P>
The bank's PHC project focuses on the preventive, promotive and
simple curative services, and will help increase the coverage of
health services like immunization, micro-nutrient support, family
planning and prenatal care among the urban children and women,
including the slum dwellers in the cities, bank sources said here
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The project will finance at least 15 partnership agreements
with the private sector and non-government organizations in
delivering packages of basic services to improve the accessibility
of health services to the poor.
</P>
<P>
To deal with the inadequacy of PHC infrastructure, about 190
two-story health centers will be constructed near the slums and
other decently populated sites, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
In the long run, the project will reduce the economic costs of
poor health by decreasing workdays' lost due to disease, increase
productivity and reduce the chances of illness, according to the
sources. 
</P>
</TEXT>
