<HEADLINE> Indian Minister Eyes Free Trade Area in South Asia by 2001 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NUWARA ELIYA, Sri Lanka, March 18 (Xinhua) -- Indian External
Affairs Minister Jaswant Singh said here Thursday afternoon that
South Asia should have a treaty in place by 2001 to usher in a
free trade area in the next century.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the 21st session of the SARRC Council of Ministers
at Sri Lanka's central town of Muwara Eliya, Singh said much
progress has been made in trade liberalization with the conclusion
of third round of South Asian Preferential Trade Arrangement
(SAPTA) negotiations since the Colombo Summit last July.
</P>
<P>
"Negotiations on the fourth round of SAPTA are to commence in
July this year," said Singh, adding that these talks should be
concluded after two meetings in August.
</P>
<P>
The Colombo Summit of South Asian countries had taken a
significant decision to negotiate a separate treaty for
establishing a South Asian free trade area.
</P>
<P>
The Council of Ministers comprises foreign ministers of the
South Asian Association for Regional Cooperation (SAARC).
</P>
<P>
The 21st session of the Council of Ministers are attended by
Singh, Bangladesh Foreign Minister Abdus Samad Azad, Maldivian
Minister of Foreign Affairs Fathulla Jameel, Pakistani Minister
for Foreign Affairs Sartaj Aziz and Sri Lankan Minister of Foreign
Affairs Lakshman Kadirgamar.
</P>
<P>
Nepal is represented by Minister of Population and Environment
Ramesh Nath Pandey.
</P>
<P>
Bhutan is represented by Foreign Secretary Dasho Ugyen Tshreing
as Deputy Bhutanese Minister for Finance Lyonpo Yeshey Zimba
could not come due to the reported bush fire in the capital.
</P>
<P>
The council meets twice a year and may also meet in extra
sessions by agreement of member states.
</P>
<P>
SAARC groups Bangladesh, Bhutan, India, Nepal, Pakistan, the
Maldives and Sri Lanka. 
</P>
</TEXT>
