<HEADLINE> Philippine Govt Welcomes Rebels' Plan to Free Hostages </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, March 18 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government Thursday
welcomed a plan by the National Democratic Front (NDF) to release
four military and police officers, but said that should be
complemented by a principled, sincere commitment to the peace
process.
</P>
<P>
The government's main concern at this time is for the NDF to
undertake confidence-building measures to sustain the peace
process, presidential spokesman Jerry Barican told reporters here
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
He said that the NDF should show proof of its good faith by
stopping all their kidnapping and terrorist activities.
</P>
<P>
"The reported intention of the NDF to release the officers is a
positive development in this regard," Barican said.
</P>
<P>
The NDF said Wednesday that it will release in a month's time
Brig. Gen. Victor Obillo, Capt. Eduardo Montealto, Police Chief
Inspector Roberto Bernal and Sgt. Alipio Lozada, who had been
abducted by the rebel group during the past month.
</P>
<P>
The need right now is for the NDF to make a strategic and
principled commitment to the peace process and not merely a
tactical commitment intended to be used as a cover to prepare for
armed conflict, Barican said.
</P>
<P>
He said that should the NDF continue to ignore this appeal, the
 military and the police are both fully prepared to meet "any
contingency" that may arise from the rebels' criminal acts.
</P>
<P>
In an interview Thursday morning, Executive Secretary Ronaldo
Zamora said the government will not suspend rescue operations for
the four police and military officers until the NDF specifies the
time and place of their release. 
