<HEADLINE> Malaysian Military, Police to Help Tackle Virus Outbreak </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, March 18 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia's police and the
military have been called to help deal with the Japanese
encephalitis (JE) outbreak, the national JE task force announced
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
They will destroy some 64,000 pigs in three areas in the
southern state of Negeri Sembilan by Sunday, task force chief and
Health Minister Chua Jui Meng said after the task force's first
meeting here Thursday, according to the Malaysian national news
agency Bernama.
</P>
<P>
The task force, also comprising Agriculture Minister Sulaiman
Daud, Housing and Local Government Minister Ting Chew Peh and
representatives from the defense, home and information ministries,
was formed by the Cabinet Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Chua said that 1,400 security forces personnel were expected to
start work Friday using light arms.
</P>
<P>
Chua said fogging and larvaciding would also be intensified in
the three areas concerned using fire and rescue service
helicopters as well as land mobile teams to annihilate Culex
mosquitoes which transmit the deadly JE virus from pigs to humans.
</P>
<P>
"The top priority now is to bring the JE outbreak down," he
said.
</P>
<P>
So far there have been 47 deaths, 15 in the northern state of
Perak and 32 in Negeri Sembilan, and 47 others are still being
warded in various hospitals, according to Chua.
</P>
<P>
Last week, the Cabinet allocated 35.5 million ringgit (9.342
million U.S. dollars) to conduct vaccination on 500,000 pigs and
292,000 residents in the affected areas in the two states.
</P>
</TEXT>
