<HEADLINE> World Bank to Fund Municipal Project in Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, March 18 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank (WB) will provide
Bangladesh with an interest-free loan of 138.6 million U.S.
dollars to finance a municipal services project in the South Asian
nation, the national news agency BSS reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The project, which was approved by the WB in Washington
Tuesday, is aimed at improving environmental and infrastructure
facilities in urban areas, the BSS quoted WB Bangladesh country
office sources as saying.
</P>
<P>
The project would provide sanitation and drainage facilities,
widen roads and pavements, and improve water supply and street
lighting in the first phase, and would help establish a municipal
development fund to provide funding for municipal sub-projects in
the second phase.
</P>
<P>
The urban population in Bangladesh has been increasing quickly
at a rate of about 4.2 percent annually while the poverty rate in
the city remains high, with 11 million out of the 25 million city
dwellers living in poverty.
</P>
<P>
The total cost of the project is estimated at 154 million
dollars, with 138.6 million dollars from the WB's soft lending
window, the International Development Association, and the rest to
be mobilized by the Bangladeshi government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
