<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manila Confident of Attaining 1999 Growth Target </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, March 18 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government remains
optimistic that it can attain its economic growth target for this
year despite a different forecast made by the World Bank, an
official said here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press briefing, presidential spokesman Jerry
Barican said the government's target growth of 3-3.7 percent for
gross national product (GNP) and 2.6-3.2 percent for gross
domestic product (GDP) for l999 "is within reach."
</P>
<P>
The World Bank's recent forecast of 1.9 percent growth in the
Philippines this year did not carry a sectoral breakdown, he said.
</P>
<P>
GNP refers to the total value of goods and services produced in
a given year in the country as well as those coming from
Philippine businesses and services rendered abroad.
</P>
<P>
GDP, on the other hand, refers only to the total value of goods
and services produced within the country.
</P>
<P>
Barican said the sectoral growth suggests a 2.6-3.2 percent
growth for the GDP.
</P>
<P>
"This is virtually identical to the forecast of the
International Monetary Fund which is 2.5-3.0 percent," he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Director General Felipe Medalla of the National
Economic and Development Authority said structural policy reforms
have the overall effect on further expanding the domestic economy.
</P>
<P>
These structural policy reforms, according to Medalla, include
trade liberalization anchored on tariff reduction and removal of
quantitative import restrictions, privatization and deregulation
of basic sectors.
</P>
<P>
Medalla also said there are positive factors that would point
to a steady recovery of the economy this year.
</P>
<P>
Among these factors are the strengthening of the Philippine
peso against the U.S. dollar and the continuing decline of
interest rates, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
