<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading French Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, March 18 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news items
in leading French newspapers on Thursday:
</P>
<P>
Liberation:
</P>
<P>
-- The number of people killed in traffic accidents in France
in 1998 stood at 8,437, which represented a 5.6 percent rise over
the previous year and was the worst in 10 years. Apart from over-
speeding, drunkenness and tiredness which are blamed for causing
the accidents, the lack of police patrol, historical and cultural
backgrounds of the Latin people, and commercial offensives by the
auto industry are also elements contributing to the especially
murderous situation on French roads.
</P>
<P>
-- The Finnish forensic medicine doctor Helana Ranta gave a
prudent report on the result of her team's examination of the
bodies of 45 Kosovo Albanians who were massacred on January 25 in
Racak. The only conclusion of the report by the experts is that
the victims were unarmed civilians, which disputed the version
given by the Yugoslav authorities, who said they were Kosovo
Liberation Army fighters killed in combat.
</P>
<P>
Le Figaro:
</P>
<P>
-- The French nuclear security watchdog, the Direction de la
Surete des Installation Nucleaies, Wednesday criticized the state-
owned electricity monopoly Electricite de France (EDF) for letting
376 incidents take place in the country's nuclear centers last
year. The EDF was accused of ``negligence, laisser-faire and
forgetting very simple things'' in the security of the centers,
but said that none of these accidents have raised any grave
problem.
</P>
<P>
-- After the French automaker Renault announced on Tuesday its
intention to buy 35 percent of the capitals of the Japanese
automaker Nissan, both financial players and unionists of France
are questioning the justification for the project. The stocks of
Renault dropped by 6.2 percent on Wednesday in Paris. 
</P>
</TEXT>
