<HEADLINE> Clashes Erupt in N.Ireland Ahead of Lawyer's Funeral </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 18 (Xinhua) -- Northern Ireland erupted into
fresh violence on Wednesday night with nationalists, loyalists and
police clashing on the streets of Portadown, according to BBC
report on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The unrest came as Catholic mourners prepared to pay their
last respects to lawyer Rosemary Nelson, who was killed by a car
bomb on Monday. A Protestant guerrilla group "Red Hand Defenders"
later claimed responsibility for the killing.
</P>
<P>
Sectarian violence flared at about 2000 GMT on Wednesday in
the Corcrain area of Portadown, just hours after loyalist leader
Frankie Curry was gunned down in Belfast during St Patrick's Day
festivities.
</P>
<P>
Officers from the Royal Ulster Constabulary (RUC) intervened --
many of them in full riot gear -- but the unrest quickly spread
with petrol bombs and paving slabs being hurled at police, the
report said.
</P>
<P>
A RUC spokesman said 38 officers had been hurt in the clashes,
although most had superficial injuries.
</P>
<P>
The police attended after reports came in of nationalists and
loyalists stoning each other, but when police intervened, they
came under attack from nationalist rioters.
</P>
<P>
The RUC responded with a volley of plastic bullets as at least
one car went up in flames in the Garvaghy Road, the spokesman
added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
