<HEADLINE> China Vows to Expand Hi-tech Machinery, Electronic Exports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DALIAN, March 18 (Xinhua) -- China plans to export more
machinery and electronic products, especially large complete units
and name brands with high added value, according to Xu Bingjin,
assistant to Minister of Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The focus will be on eight types of products for export
including power generators and transmitters, ship and marine
equipment, aircraft and aviation equipment, communications
equipment, automatic data processing units, high-grade household
electrical appliances, automobiles (motorbikes) and parts, and
farm and engineering construction machinery, Xu said at a national
meeting on machinery and electronics exports which opened here
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that 59.4 billion U.S. dollars worth of
machines, electrical equipment and products, and transportation
tools and instruments were exported last year, up 12.9 percent
over 1997.
</P>
<P>
This shows that China's hi-tech products are strongly
competitive and are essential to the country's effort to realize
the goal of 71.5 billion dollars in exports in machinery and
electronic products this year, Xu said.
</P>
<P>
He added that his ministry will cooperate with the Ministry of
Science and Technology in order to boost trade.  
</P>
</TEXT>
