<HEADLINE> Nigeria, Chad Call for Closer Coop in Lake Chad </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, March 18 (Xinhua) -- Nigerian and Chadian heads of state
 reiterated the urgent need for convening a summit of member
states of the Lake Chad Basin Commission in order to revitalize
their cooperation.
</P>
<P>
In a joint communique signed Wednesday in capital Abuja at the
end of the three-day official visit to Nigeria by Chadian
President Idriss Deby, the two leaders said the Nigeria-Chad Joint
Commission will hold its third session from April 20 to 25.
</P>
<P>
According to the communique, Nigeria and Chad are determined to
 establish two direct road links between the two west African
countries in order to promote cooperation between them.
</P>
<P>
Nigerian Head of State General Abdulsalami Abubakar and Chadian
 president agreed to set up a joint ministerial committee for
regular consultation with a view to reaching a final decision on
the two road links, The Punch newspaper reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
A joint team of experts will be formed within three weeks to
undertake a physical study of the terrain in order to determine
the first route to be constructed.
</P>
<P>
Deby who arrived in the Rivers State in southern Nigeria Monday
said while visiting Port Harcourt that Chad will use the abundant
port facilities in Nigeria for export of its products as it is a
landlocked country.
</P>
<P>
The president said he is in Nigeria and Rivers State in
particular, to learn from the experience of Nigeria, especially in
the oil and gas industry as Chad is set to develop oil and gas
resources.
</P>
<P>
He disclosed plans to import a large quantity of Nigeria's
fertilizers to enrich his country's soil and boost agricultural
production. 
</P>
</TEXT>
