<HEADLINE> S.African President to Visit Libya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, March 18 (Xinhua) -- South African President
Nelson Mandela will hold talks in Tripoli on Friday with Libyan
leader Muammar Qaddafi over Lockerbie bombing, and would then
address a rally in the capital Tripoli.
</P>
<P>
Mandela would therefore only arrive back home in the early
hours of Saturday, South African Press Association (SAPA) Thursday
quoted Mandela's spokesman Parks Mankahlana as saying through
telephone from Stockholm.
</P>
<P>
Mandela is on the last day of his week-long state visit to five
north European countries.
</P>
<P>
Mandela's special envoy on Lockerbie, Jakes Gerwel, will also
attend the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Mankahlana said Mandela had received a special exemption from
the United Nations to fly to the Libyan capital, despite the U.N.
air embargo.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this week, U.N. spokesman Fred Eckhard confirmed that
U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan was aware of Mandela's
forthcoming trip.
</P>
<P>
"President Mandela's trip to Libya is done in coordination with
the secretary-general, and in support of the secretary-general's
ongoing efforts in the Lockerbie case," he said.
</P>
<P>
Mandela is scheduled to leave Stockholm at 5:30 p.m. (1530
GMT). The flight to Tripoli would last about four to six hours,
Mankahlana said.
</P>
<P>
Mandela has played a central role in efforts to break the
deadlock over the trial of two Libyan intelligence agents accused
of the bombing of a Pan Am jetliner over Lockerbie, Scotland, in
1988. A total of 270 people died in the incident.
</P>
<P>
After refusing to have the pair tried in the United States or
Britain, Qaddafi agreed to a proposal that the trial be conducted
by Scottish judges and under Scottish law in The Hague, the
Netherlands. 
</P>
</TEXT>
