<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK's Visitor Arrivals in February Surge 17 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Total cumulative arrivals for January and February reached 1.6
million, an increase of 13.9 percent over the corresponding period
last year.
</P>
<P>
The association attributed the increase mainly to the Chinese
Lunar New Year activities encouraged travel to Hong Kong and more
stable foreign exchange rate against the HK dollar.
</P>
<P>
Markets showing the strongest growth in February included the
Chinese mainland, from which arrivals rose by 65.2 percent due
mainly to favorable outbound policies, a shorter visa processing
time, and the Chinese New Year holiday period which encouraged
travelers to go overseas.
</P>
<P>
Arrivals from the Republic of Korea, the Philippines and
Indonesia rose by 47.2 percent, 39.2 percent and 28.1 percent
respectively.
</P>
<P>
A growth of 11.5 percent was recorded in arrivals from Taiwan
and an increase of 10 percent in arrivals from Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
The association said that the stabilizing economy, the
strengthening Yen and a new air service between Tokyo and Hong
Kong helped to account for an increase of 3.2 percent in arrivals
from Japan in February.
</P>
<P>
The only shorthaul market to register a significant fall in
arrivals in February was Singapore from which the number of
visitors fell by 14.2 percent and arrivals from almost all
longhaul markets fell during the month due mainly to the Chinese
New Year holiday.
</P>
<P>
These longhaul markets include New Zealand, Switzerland,
Britain, South Africa, Australia, Germany, Italy, France, the
Netherlands and the United States.
</P>
<P>
Amy Chan, executive director of the HKTA, said: "We are very
encouraged to see that the strong growth in January has carried
through the Chinese New Year period, and arrivals so far this
month are also up."
</P>
<P>
However, she said there are still many challenges ahead, and
everyone in the tourism industry must continue to work hard to
maintain Hong Kong's competitiveness. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
