<HEADLINE> India, Vietnam to Cooperate in Atomic Energy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, March 18 (Xinhua) -- Minister of State for External
Affairs Vasundhara Raje said Thursday that India and Vietnam have
agreed to cooperate in peaceful utilization of atomic energy.
</P>
<P>
She told the on-going session of the Upper House of Parliament
here that the agreement included training, exchange of scientists,
setting up of a semi-pilot plant for manufacture, controlling and
assessing the quality of U02 ceramics, and joint exploration of
uranium ore mines in Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
The government is open to specific offers for private
participation, Indian or foreign, in the nuclear power sector, she
said.
</P>
<P>
The government has so far not received any concrete proposal
for setting up nuclear power plants but when received, they would
be considered on the basis of technical suitability, economic
attractiveness, regulatory requirements and the conditions
attached to the offers, she further said.
</P>
<P>
Nuclear power contributed 2.59 percent of the total electricity
generated in the country in 1998 and a target of 6,660 MWe from
nuclear power had been fixed for the Ninth Five-Year Plan
(1998-2002), she added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
