<DOCNO> XIE19990318.0123 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> hke031848- Pak May Sign CTBT before Sept. if Sanctions Lifted: FM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, March 18 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan said Thursday it may
Sign the Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty (CTBT) before September
this year if the coercive atmosphere of sanctions is removed.
</P>
<P>
"Pakistan may sign CTBT even before September 1999. But that
will happen only under pressure-free conditions and in the best
interest of the country," Foreign Minister Sartaj Aziz said in a
written reply to a question at the National Assembly.
</P>
<P>
He said there is already some good progress towards creating a
conducive environment. "We sincerely wish this progress to
continue so that Pakistan can adhere to the CTBT within the time
frame announced by Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif," he added.
</P>
<P>
Aziz recalled Sharif's address to the United Nations General
Assembly in September last year stating that Islamabad was
prepared to adhere to the CTBT by September 1999, "but only in the
conditions free from coercion or pressure." "This has been our
basic position," he said.
</P>
<P>
The foreign minister said that since September last year when
Pakistan faced unjustified sanctions following its nuclear tests
in response to those of India, "the coercive atmosphere has
eased."
</P>
<P>
He said sanctions against Pakistan on lending of International
Financial Institutions (IFIs) have been removed and the long
standing issue of F-16s with the United States has been resolved.
</P>
<P>
Similarly, he noted, the bilateral sanctions imposed by the
United States, Japan and other countries are also being gradually
softened.
</P>
<P>
Aziz said the U.S. administration has already initiated the
process of further expanding the Brownback Amendment, also lifted
the sanctions from humanitarian assistance and, "hopefully, our
on-going bilateral discussions (on export control of nuclear
technology) would yield further good results."
</P>
<P>
"There are all positive developments. We hope efforts at
creating a coercion-free atmosphere would continue, enabling
Pakistan to fulfill its commitment," said Aziz.
</P>
<P>
He said Islamabad is not against CTBT in principle. Pakistan
had participated in the negotiations for the treaty, he added.
</P>
<P>
However, Aziz said that as clearly stated by Prime Minister
Sharif, Pakistan would not adhere to it in a coercive atmosphere.
"This is our principled position and cannot be compromised," he
stressed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990318.0124 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ARATS Addresses Implementation of Four-Point Consensus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TAIPEI, March 18 (Xinhua) -- The Association for Relations
Across the Taiwan Straits (ARATS) voiced hope today for enhancing
dialog between it and the Straits Exchange Foundation (SEF) to
arrange and prepare for ARATS President Wang Daohan's visit to
Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
ARATS Deputy Secretary General Li Yafei made the remark during
a morning meeting to exchange of views with SEF Deputy Secretary
General Jan Jyh-horng.
</P>
<P>
The ARATS official suggested the two organizations should host
either forums or seminars in July or August this year.
</P>
<P>
Li proposed that the mainland host a forum on cross-Straits
relations to discuss issues of common concern, including political
topics, with Taiwan hosting a seminar on cross-Straits economic
ties.
</P>
<P>
Li said ARATS favors in-depth discussions on procedural matters
related to cross-Straits political negotiations and political
issues of common concern.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the two sides can also discuss issues
involving cross-Straits economic cooperation, and direct postal,
commercial and transportation links, as well as topics related to
agricultural, scientific and pharmaceutical cooperation.
</P>
<P>
ARATS holds that officially ending the state of hostilities and
realizing direct postal, commercial and transportation links are
prominent issues affecting the interests of compatriots on either
side of the Taiwan Straits.
</P>
<P>
Related issues should be resolved through dialog and
negotiations at the earliest possible date, said Li, adding that
matters involving life and property of compatriots on both sides
of the Straits and various other practical issues must be
effectively dealt with prior to the resumption of ARATS-SEF talks.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the two sides can discuss how to remove
political barriers hampering talks on substantial issues if SEF so
desires.
</P>
<P>
Last October, Wang and SEF Chairman Koo Chen-fu reached a four-
point consensus during Koo's visit to the mainland. The two sides
agreed that arrangement shall be made for Wang to visit Taiwan at
the appropriate time.
</P>
<P>
However, the two sides have not as yet officially discussed the
proper time, Li noted, referring to an earlier SEF announcement of
"Wang's Taiwan visit in spring".
</P>
<P>
He said any unilateral announcement of Wang's timetable for the
visit and declaring it as a common understanding would not
indicate mutual respect.
</P>
<P>
According to Li, Wang is expected to visit Taiwan this fall.
</P>
<P>
Li reaffirmed the invitation for the SEF deputy secretary
general to visit the mainland to continue discussions, and said
ARATS is willing to invite Shi Hwei-yow, vice-chairman and
secretary general of SEF, to visit the mainland in June to make
arrangements for further ARATS-SEF dialog.
</P>
<P>
The two sides can further exchange views on Wang's Taiwan tour
by that time, Li said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
