<DOCNO> XIE19990318.0125 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Offer 4.8 Billion Yuan for Major Innovation Program </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 18 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese government will spend
4.8 billion yuan (570 million U.S. dollars) for the implementation
of a state "knowledge-innovation program" through the end of next
year.
</P>
<P>
According to the newly released 4th Yellow Paper on China's
science and technology, China expects to acquire strong technical
support and make strategic scientific discoveries by the
implementation of this major program.
</P>
<P>
China hopes to be among the top-10 scientifically competitive
countries in the world by the year 2010.
</P>
<P>
A senior official with the Ministry of Science and Technology
said the effective investment in science and technology
development, the early creation of a national knowledge-innovation
system, and a greater number of high-tech ventures are all part of
the major measures taken by the government to greet the 21st
century, a time when a knowledge-based economy will prevail.
</P>
<P>
Statistics indicate that the central government has greatly
increased its financial support for the development of science and
technology.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, the annual financial allocation for science and
technology development was 40.8 billion yuan (4.8 billion U.S.
dollars up 15.9 percent over the previous year.
</P>
<P>
Playing a major role in the implementation of the national "
knowledge-innovation program", the Chinese Academy of Sciences (
CAS) last year began a trial operation of the program.
</P>
<P>
The CAC, the country's highest scientific research institute,
plans to establish 100 advanced scientific research institutions
and 20 interdisciplinary research centers by the year 2005.
</P>
<P>
CAC Vice President Chen Yiyu told Xinhua that the CAS knowledge-
innovation projects will focus on strategic basic research,
sustainable development and high-tech fields.
</P>
<P>
He explained that basic research will include the breeding of
high-yield crop seeds, the application of genetic resources, and
new pharmaceuticals for the treatment of wide-spread common
diseases.
</P>
<P>
Chen added that sustainable-development related research
projects include the development of the Yangtze and Yellow river
valleys and eco-agricutlural development.
</P>
<P>
High-tech innovations will focus on the future development of
information, telecommunications, genetic engineering, and the new-
materials industry.
</P>
<P>
A Yellow Paper has been issued once every two years by the
Ministry of Science and Technology since 1992. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
