<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks Close Weaker </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, March 18 (Xinhua) -- The Australian sharemarket
limped through trade Thursday, succumbing to the pull of a sliding
Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
The benchmark all ordinaries index slipped 10.1 points to close
at 2,967.7, up off its 2,962.0 intra-day low.
</P>
<P>
Morgan Stockbroking's Simon Reed said the market fell Thursday
in line with Wall Street which slipped for the second consecutive
day.
</P>
<P>
On the Australian bourse, the all industrials index offloaded
20.7 points to 5,348.9, while the all resources index dipped only
0.6 of a point to 1,017.3.
</P>
<P>
The all resources was helped by a resilient BHP, Australia's
largest industrial company, which shrugged off speculation of a
possible dividend cut, to be 21 cents firmer at 12.95 Australian
dollars. The diversified resources giant brings down its third
quarter profits next week.
</P>
<P>
The weaker industrial sector followed falls among a cross
section of majors although strong performance by Commonwealth Bank
of Australia (CBA) stood out.
</P>
<P>
In the banking sector, CBA was the only one of the country's
big four banks to move upward, rising 21 cents to 25.98 Australian
dollars.
</P>
<P>
National Australia Bank was down 11 cents to 27.98 Australian
dollars, ANZ bank shed six cents to 11.10 Australian dollars and
Westpac bank lost nine cents to 11.01 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
Gold stabilized with a 0.15 U.S. dollar rise to 283.90 U.S.
dollars an ounce in Sydney.
</P>
<P>
National turnover was 385.77 million shares valued at 636.8
million U.S. dollars, with 723 falls, 468 rises and 445 stocks
steady. 
</P>
</TEXT>
