<HEADLINE> Thailand, Myanmar Reach Agreement on Maritime Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, March 18 (Xinhua) -- Thai and Myanmar officials have
reached an agreement to end a maritime dispute that led to naval
conflicts late last year, Thai News Agency reported on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was reached at a two-day meeting that ended
Wednesday. The meeting, under the Thai-Myanmar Regional Border
Committee (RBC), was held in Phuket, southern Thailand.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, both armed and unarmed vessels of the two
countries must be identified with national flags when sailing in
disputed areas to avoid clashes.
</P>
<P>
A radio frequency for boat-to-boat communications would be also
established so that both sides could immediately notify the other
on any incident.
</P>
<P>
"We have achieved cooperation and understanding between each
other, which will help lessen all undesirable incidents and
strengthen bilateral ties and cooperation," the report quoted Maj.
Gen. Thein Sein, Myanmar commander of the coastal region, as
saying.
</P>
<P>
The two governments have agreed that the joint RBC holds talks
regularly to exchange information and discuss border problems.
</P>
<P>
Armed vessels of Thailand and Myanmar exchanged fire on
disputed waters late last year, resulting in deaths on both sides.
The two sides have held a series of talks to end their dispute
through peaceful means. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
