<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines' Balance of Payments in 1998 Posts Surplus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, March 18 (Xinhua) -- The Central Bank of the
Philippines Thursday announced that the overall balance of
payments position for the 1998 yielded a surplus of 1.35 billion
U.S. dollars, a reversal of the year ago deficit of 3.36 billion
U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Central Bank governor Gabriel C. Singson attributed the
turnaround to the 1.29-billion-U.S. dollar current account
surplus, only the second to be recorded since 1980 and a definite
improvement from the 4.4-billion-U.S. dollar deficit in 1997.
</P>
<P>
For 1998, merchandise exports reached 29.496 billion U.S.
dollars to end the year with a robust 16.9 percent growth, Singson
said.
</P>
<P>
The growth in exports was "quite a feat considering the
substantial decline in exports of other Asian countries," he
added.
</P>
<P>
Imports, on the other hand, amounted to 29.524 billion U.S.
dollars, falling by 18.8 percent from last year's level of 36.355
billion U.S. dollars, he said.
</P>
<P>
The drop in the demand for imported raw materials and capital
goods indicated the contraction in overall economic activity when
gross domestic product slumped by 0.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
During the period, net investment flows recorded an increase of
119.4 percent. What was notable in the investment flows was that
the growth was driven by direct investments and not by portfolio
investment, Singson said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
