<HEADLINE> Shanghai Opens 24-hour Legal-Service Hotline </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, March 18 (Xinhua) -- Shanghai today opened a round-
the-clock telephone hotline to offer residents ideas on how to
seek legal assistance.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai has thus become the first Chinese city to open such a
service, covering all of its urban districts and rural counties.
</P>
<P>
Some 365 volunteer lawyers and government officials will man
the phones and take questions and complaints and offer legal-aid
suggestions.
</P>
<P>
Miao Xiaobao, director of the Shanghai Municipal Judicial
Bureau, said that an automatic voice-based information research
and data system will also be established later.
</P>
<P>
Since the opening of a temporary legal service telephone
hotline on January 28, 1,330 calls have been received, according
to Miao, who said that these calls were mostly about medical
treatment, neighborhoods, debt and labor disputes.
</P>
<P>
The new hotline received 31 calls between 9:00 a.m. and 11:30 a.
m. today, and many of these calls were about debt, marriage and
real estate disputes, he said.
</P>
<P>
A similar legal-service hotline was first set up in Dongming
County in Shandong Province, and currently similar hotlines have
been opened in some areas of 12 Chinese provinces, municipalities
and autonomous regions.  
</P>
</TEXT>
