<HEADLINE> Xinjiang Airlines Carries Pilgrims to Mecca </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, March 18 (Xinhua) -- Xinjiang Airlines in northwest
China's Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region has dispatched four
chartered planes carrying 1,101 pilgrims to Mecca in Saudi Arabia,
Islam's holiest city. The last of these flights took off from
Urumqi on March 12.
</P>
<P>
According to Hu Yamin, assistant general manager of the
airlines, a special group of public security and safety inspection
personnel, along with members of other departments, are ensuring
the safety of the flights and the smooth operation of the
chartered planes.
</P>
<P>
The Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region is the home of many Muslim
minority ethnic people.
</P>
<P>
Each year, thousands of Muslims from Xinjiang go to Mecca to
perform the annual religious pilgrimage, known as the hajj, which
is required of every able-bodied Muslim who can afford it at
least once in their life.
</P>
<P>
Xinjiang Airlines began offering chartered planes for the hajj
in 1995, and over the past five years the airline has transported
nearly 10,000 pilgrims.
</P>
<P>
The pilgrims from Xinjiang are schedule to return home on
chartered planes in the middle of April, Hu said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
