<DOCNO> XIE19990318.0139 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Preliminary Results Show Lagos Lagoon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, March 18 (Xinhua) -- Preliminary results of a study
indicated that the Lagos lagoon system could be over-polluted due
to the discharge of faecal waste, trace metals and hydro-carbons.
</P>
<P>
The study on Lagos lagoon is part of a study for the Gulf of
Guinea Large Marine Ecosystem being undertaken by a team of
scientists from Benin, Cameroon, Cote d'Ivoire, Ghana, Nigeria and
Togo, according to a New Nigerian report Thursday.
</P>
<P>
According to the study, which is aimed at testing the manual of
standard methods for pollution monitoring in the six participating
nations, the Ido section of the Lagos lagoon has been found to be
highly polluted with faecal waste.
</P>
<P>
Professor Dapo Afolabi of Nigerian Federal Environmental
Protection Agency, who plays host to the team of scientists, said
detailed results of the tests on samples collected from the lagoon
were yet to be released.
</P>
<P>
Lagos has a population of more than six million and about 2,000
 industrial establishments most of which discharge effluents
directly into the lagoon.
</P>
<P>
Lagos lagoon system is suspected to be one of the worst
polluted inland fresh water bodies in Africa.
</P>
<P>
Afolabi said the tests would determine the presence of heavy
metals, hydro-carbons and other harmful elements in the lagoon and
their impact on the lagoon's carriage capacity. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
