<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Reports 1997 High-Tech Foreign Trade Volume </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 18 (Xinhua) -- China's export-import volume for
high-tech products surged from 12.3 billion US dollars in 1991 to
some 30 billion dollars in 1997.
</P>
<P>
China recently released its 4th Yellow Paper on Science and
Technology showing an average 16.8 percent growth rate for the
high-tech foreign trade volume between 1987-1997.
</P>
<P>
The Paper noted that high-tech foreign trade mainly focused on
the computer, telecommunications, space technology and electronics
sectors.
</P>
<P>
The Paper also noted the import volume exceeded the level for
exports.
</P>
<P>
The Yellow Paper, issued by the Ministry of Science and
Technology, said China conducted high-tech trade with over 180
countries and regions between 1996-1997, with major trade partners
including the United States, Japan and a number of other developed
countries.
</P>
<P>
The annual trade volume for 10 provinces and municipalities,
including Beijing and Shanghai, as well as Guangdong, Jiangsu,
Liaoning, Fujian and Shandong provinces, accounted for 93.5
percent of China's total high-tech trade volume.
</P>
<P>
The industrial output value for the nation's high-tech industry
hit 640 billion yuan (77 billion dollars) in 1997, 390 billion
yuan more than in 1993.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990318.0142 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Bourse Up 6.11 Points </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, March 18 (Xinhua) -- The Stock Exchange of Thailand
(SET) index on Thursday gained 6.11 points from Wednesday to close
at 362.91.
</P>
<P>
Some 241 million shares worth 4.52 billion baht (122.3 million
U.S. dollars) changed hands Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The SET index Wednesday gained 1.85 points from Tuesday to
close at 356.80. 
