<HEADLINE> Manila Hopes to Halt Operations Against Rebels for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, March 18 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government Thursday
expressed willingness to suspend military operations against the
rebel New People's Army (NPA) in exchange for the release of four
officers abducted by the NPA.
</P>
<P>
This was disclosed by Executive Secretary Ronaldo Zamora in
response to a call from the rebels for the suspension of military
operations.
</P>
<P>
However, Zamora said in an interview that "we will not allow
ourselves to be hoodwinked in putting ourselves at a
disadvantage."
</P>
<P>
"If the captors of these hostages say why don't you give us a
month, obviously, those are outrageous and unreasonable demands,"
he added.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the rebels' leader Jose Ma. Sison called on the
government to withdraw and halt its military operations so the
release of prisoners of war could be safely effected.
</P>
<P>
Sison said preparations for the release may take about three
weeks to one month since both sides will have to agree on the
terms of the withdrawal of military troops in the area.
</P>
<P>
Philippine army general Victor Obillo and his aide were
abducted on February 17 by the NPA guerrillas. Police inspector
Roberto Bernal and army staff sergeant Alipio Lozada were snatched
later in separate raids.
</P>
<P>
The abductions forced the government to call off peace talks
with the rebels last month and to suspend the scheduled release of
about 50 jailed rebel guerrillas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
