<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ex-wife Confirms Australian IOC Member Accepted Jewelry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, March 18 (Xinhua) -- Australian International Olympic
Committee (IOC) member Phil Coles was left in a serious danger of
expulsion after his former wife claimed on Thursday he accepted
jewelry from Athens' bidders for the 1996 Olympic Games, a fact he
had just flatly denied.
</P>
<P>
Coles was among the ten IOC members who were given a severe
warning by the IOC for accepting free holidays from Salt Lake
City's bid committee for the 2002 Winter Games. He has been
warned that his position on the IOC was at risk if more evidence
was uncovered.
</P>
<P>
Georgina Coles told The Australian Financial Review the couple
received a gold necklace, and a pair of diamond-encrusted
cufflinks which she later had converted to earrings, when visiting
Athens during the city's bid for the 1996 Games.
</P>
<P>
"Yes I've still got the jewelry," she told the daily. "It was
given to us in Athens 10 years ago on one of our Olympic trips."
</P>
<P>
Canadian IOC vice-president Dick Pound, who led the IOC
investigation, said the new claim would be investigated.
</P>
<P>
The jewelry in question is worth about 10,000 Australian
dollars (6,300 U.S. dollars) and was allegedly given to Coles at a
time when IOC rules limited the value of gifts to 200 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The former canoeist flatly denied accepting the jewelry during
a radio appearance earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
Though he escaped this week's round of expulsions from the
Olympic body, the IOC has said it plans to investigate the jewelry
allegations laid by organizers of Melbourne's unsuccessful bid for
the 1996 Olympics. 
</P>
</TEXT>
