<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambia, DRC Discuss 750 Soldiers' Plight </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, March 18 (Xinhua) -- The Zambian and Democratic
Republic of Congo (DRC) governments have opened bilateral talks
aimed at finding ways of repatriating the 750 Congolese soldiers
and policemen.
</P>
<P>
United Nations High Commissioner Refugees (UNHCR) spokesman in
Zambia Dominik Bastch said Wednesday the soldiers were not being
treated as refugees but as ex-military.
</P>
<P>
Thursday's Zambian newspaper, the Post, quoted Bastch as saying
:" Soldiers don't come under our mandate. They are not refugees."
"But if the negotiations between the Zambian and the DRC
governments are protracted, we will continue to extend
humanitarian assistance to them," he added.
</P>
<P>
Bastch said the influx of refugees fleeing renewed fighting in
the DRC has reduced and there had been no reports of new arrivals
since the over 5, 000 refugees crossed into Zambia on March 15.
This figure includes some 750 soldiers and policemen, who have
since been separated from the civilian refugees.
</P>
<P>
Bastch, however, could not state the exact number of refugees
who have crossed into Zambia so far.
</P>
<P>
"We still don't know what the total tally is. There has been no
update in terms of numbers," Bastch said.
</P>
<P>
This week a high level mission, comprising representative from
the World Food Program (WFP), the UNHCR, the International Red
Cross Society and the Zambian government are scheduled to travel
to Kaputa in Northern Province, to assess the situation on the
ground.
</P>
<P>
And according to Bastch, Angolan refugees have continued to
trickle into Zambia at a rate of 20 every week. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990318.0153 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pakistan's Imports Down Dramatically in 8 Months </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, March 18 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan's imports in the first
eight months (July to February) in the 1998-99 fiscal year stood
at 5.846 billion U.S. dollars, registering a major decline of
1.192 billion dollars against the same period in the previous
year.
</P>
<P>
The imports of wheat and machinery during the eight months
declined sharply in comparison with the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
The latest figures by the Federal Bureau of Statistics show
that Pakistan purchased a total of 671.33 million dollars of wheat
in the first eight months of last fiscal year. However, the import
bill of wheat from July to February period in the 1998-99 fiscal
year fell to 224.50 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Machinery import during the period also decreased to 1.299
billion dollars from 1.662 billion dollars in the corresponding
period of last fiscal year mainly because of differences between
the government and the private power producers on the tariff
issue.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the import in petroleum group declined by 28.23
percent, and that in agricultural and other chemicals group fell
by 15.40 percent.
</P>
<P>
Sources from the Finance Ministry claimed Thursday that the
government policy of cash margin condition levied on the opening
of letter of credit played a key role in bringing down import bill
in the wake of suspension of loans by the donors and sanctions
imposed by some western countries after Pakistan's nuclear tests
in May last year.
</P>
<P>
It is believed that Pakistan's import bill will further fall at
the end of the current fiscal year because of the slow economic
activities in the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990318.0154 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 08:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Microsoft to Open Regional Office in Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, March 18 (Xinhua) -- The United States' software giant
Microsoft is to open an office in Beirut, which is responsible
for its businesses in Lebanon, Jordan and Cyprus, the Daily Star
reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The plan was announced by Bahram Mohazzebi, general manager
for Microsoft Gulf and Eastern Mediterranean at a news conference
on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The announcement came just one day after Lebanese parliament
passed the controversial intellectual property rights bill
designed to combat software piracy.
</P>
<P>
"If you don't have copyright laws in a country, it would be
difficult for us to invest in that country, because we would have
no protection for our investment," Mohazzebi said.
</P>
<P>
Microsoft has warned that if Lebanese parliament postponed to
pass the law, it would set up the regional office in Jordan or
Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Under strong pressure from international software companies,
especially Microsoft, Lebanese parliament Wednesday endorsed the
copyright law attached with an amendment saying a school or
university could take original program copies for educational
purposes and not for profit.
</P>
<P>
Some deputies have been firmly opposed to the law, citing such
a bill would eventually harm the interest of students who can't
afford to buy a costly original computer program.
</P>
<P>
However, software manufacturers complained that they lost
millions of dollars each year due to illegal software reproduction
in Lebanon, where the piracy rate is estimated at 90 percent or
higher.
</P>
<P>
Mohazzebi said his company would do its best to help the
government with the implementation of the approved law.
</P>
<P>
But he didn't give exact investment figures, saying only
that Microsoft's biggest investment in Lebanon would be in the
form of knowledge and know-how. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
