<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa to Tighten Arms Control </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, March 18 (Xinhua) -- The South African parliament
on Wednesday approved an arms bill which restricts the lending of
licensed firearms, The Citizen paper reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The owners of licensed firearms can only lend their weapons to
other licensed arm owners in terms of the Arms and Ammunition
Amendment Bill.
</P>
<P>
The current legislation allows licensed firearm owners to lend
their arms to anyone, provided they signed a letter of
authorization.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Safety and Security Minister Joe Matthews told the
parliament that the amendment bill was an interim measure, and a
comprehensive new Arms and Ammunition Bill was being drafted to
replace the outdated one.
</P>
<P>
He said the old law was widely abused, especially by gangsters
in the Western Cape, parts of which have been plagued by repeated
violence in recent years.
</P>
<P>
The new bill, which will come before parliament later this
year, would deal with issues like training for potential firearm
owners, limited periods of license validity and strict criteria
for obtaining licenses, Matthew said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
