<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt Surprised at Israeli Fury over Arms Purchase </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, March 18 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak
has expressed surprise at Israel's fury over Egypt's planned
purchase of U.S. weapons, the Egyptian Gazette newspaper reported
on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the Arabic-language Al-Gomhuria daily on
Wednesday, Mubarak said that Israel makes a big fuss every time
Egypt seeks to acquire weapons.
</P>
<P>
During his visit in Cairo a week ago, U.S. Defense Secretary
William Cohen announced that the U.S. will sell 3.2 billion
U.S. dollars worth of advanced weapons to Egypt in the coming
years.
</P>
<P>
The weapons, some of which Cohen said are the most
sophisticated in the U.S. arsenal, include 24 advanced-model F-16
fighters, 200 M1-A1 tanks and one eight-unit Patriot 3 model
anti-missile battery which has 32 missiles.
</P>
<P>
Egypt was the first Arab country to sign a peace treaty with
Israel in 1979. But the two countries have been in a "cold peace"
due to the intransigent policy toward the peace process adopted by
the Likud coalition of Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu
since it assumed power in 1996.
</P>
<P>
"They (Israelis) obviously do not want anybody (else) to own
these weapons (in an attempt) to maintain their supremacy in the
region," Mubarak stressed.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian president made it clear that seeking sophisticated
weapons does not mean preparing for a war. "Our policies are clear
to everybody. We seek to establish peace and nothing but peace,"
Mubarak said.
</P>
<P>
He maintained that every country is entitled to have the
necessary arms to defend its own security.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak said that Egypt is a major defender of regional peace
because it knows that realization of peace will bring stability
and development to the whole region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
