<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Expert Assesses Qinghai Weather Conditions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XINING, March 18 (Xinhua) -- A Qinghai meteorologist attributes
the strong winds and persistent sandstorms which swept through
southern Qinghai Province between March 3 and 10 to the region's
high altitude and warm temperatures.
</P>
<P>
Gao Wuxiang, a senior expert and deputy chief of the Qinghai
Provincial Meteorological Station, said persistent strong winds
rarely occur in pastureland areas located at 4,000 meters above
sea level.
</P>
<P>
However, according to Gao, the closeness of the ground to upper
air currents due to the region's high altitude creates conditions
for the circulation of strong winds.
</P>
<P>
Continuous warm temperatures and dry weather since winter also
contributes to the strong winds which killed an estimated 20,000
head of livestock, mostly sheep. An additional 5,200 head of
livestock died later from starvation resulting from inadequate
grass cover.
</P>
<P>
The strong winds and sandstorms also damaged 130-odd houses and
24 sheep pens, destroyed some 30 percent of the grass coverage,
and cut power supply, telecommunications and closed TV circuit
lines in some places.
</P>
<P>
The northwestern China province witnessed warmest year in 60
years during 1998, when average temperature was one to three
degree centigrade above normal. In the first half of March, the
average temperature was even four to seven degree above normal.
</P>
<P>
In addition, a prolonged drought hit vast stretches of pastoral
areas which normally record between 7-20 mm of snow in March.
</P>
<P>
Precipitation in most parts of the province have ranged between
70-100 percent below normal since last autumn, according to
meteorological data.
</P>
<P>
Strong winds normally accompany prolonged periods of drought,
said Gao, adding that the frequency of winds is directly related
to the severity of drought conditions.
</P>
<P>
Meteorological departments predict that southern and western
portions of Qinghai Province, as well as areas around Qinghai Lake,
will continue to experience strong winds over the next few days,
with related conditions posing a severe threat the maturation of
grass in pastoral areas.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
