<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 09:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Water Raises Tension Between Jordan, Israel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, March 18 (Xinhua) -- Jordanian-Israeli relations are
facing a major challenge as the crisis over water-sharing between
the two countries starts to build up tensions.
</P>
<P>
The tensions originated from an Israeli plan earlier this week
to reduce its water supplies as stipulated in the peace treaty to
this desert kingdom by 40 to 60 percent in the coming summer.
Reason: a drought is hitting both of them.
</P>
<P>
The water crisis is the worst of its kind since the two
countries signed a peace treaty in 1994. It also posed the first
diplomatic challenge to the brand new Jordanian government headed
by Prime Minister Abdel Raouf al-Rawabdeh, appointed by King
Abdullah Bin Hussein on March 4.
</P>
<P>
The Rawabdeh government has rejected the Israeli plan as a
violation of the peace treaty, and declared that Jordan would
under no circumstances agree to a reduction of water share from
the Jewish state.
</P>
<P>
Under their treaty by which Jordan became the second Arab
country to realize peace with the Jewish state, Israel is entitled
to 12 million cubic meters of water from the Yarmouk River from
May 15 to October 15. Jordan extracts the rest of the river flow.
</P>
<P>
From October 16 to May 14, Israel pumps out 13 million cubic
meters of water from the Yarmouk river, and Jordan allows Israel
to pump an additional 20 million cubic meters from the river.
</P>
<P>
In return for the additional water, Israel promised to
transfer 20 million cubic meters of water to Jordan from the
Jordan River that runs between them in summer time. It now wants
to nearly half its compensation.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli plan also met with fierce opposition from the
Lower House of the Jordanian parliament, which issued a statement
on Wednesday, saying the "Israeli move casts suspicion on the
Middle East peace process as a whole."
</P>
<P>
"It`s a violation of the fundamentals of peace treaty and
sheds doubts on Israeli commitments to the treaty," said the
sharply-worded statement.
</P>
<P>
Seventeen out of the 80 lawmakers even lodged a motion to
revoke the whole peace treaty to protest Israel`s plan to cut
water supplies, but motion was aborted as it failed to win a 41
simple majority.
</P>
<P>
Jordan has viewed the water clauses as the key and most
fundamental elements in the 1994 peace treaty between the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli side, however, tried to play down the issue by
saying that it was only a suggestion to cut the water supplies,
and it is open to discussion.
</P>
<P>
The summer is drawing near and the regional drought is still
prevailing, but how to share water in the coming month would put
to test their bilateral relations as well as the 1994 peace
treaty. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990318.0170 </DOCNO>
