<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel's Current Account Deficit Plunges in 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, March 18 (Xinhua) -- Israel's current-account
deficit in 1998 plunged by 46 percent to 2.3 billion U.S. dollars,
according to figures issued Thursday by the Central Bureau of
Statistics (CBS).
</P>
<P>
The current account measures the balance between inflows and
outflows of foreign currency, whether from imports or exports of
goods, services, or unilateral transfers.
</P>
<P>
Last year's capital transfers slid to 1.8 billion dollars from
2.2 billion in 1997, while newly accumulated foreign assets
dropped more than 50 percent, from 9.5 billion dollars in 1997 to
4.3 billion in 1998.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, Israel's overseas liabilities rose by 5.7
billion dollars from 8.7 billion dollars in 1997.
</P>
<P>
In goods traffic, there was a decline from 1997's 5.2 billion
dollars to 1998's 3.3 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Israel's overall debt and liabilities in 1998 totalled 74
billion dollars, including an estimated 19 billion dollars in
foreign investments.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Israel's job seekers reached 157,000 in February,
representing a 2.7 percent increase from January. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
