<HEADLINE> Zambia's Bombings Probe End </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, March 18 (Xinhua) -- The experts from the Diplomatic
Security Wing (DSW) of the state department and the Bureau of
Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms (BATF) of the United States have
handed over their findings on Zambian Capital Lusaka bombings to
the government.
</P>
<P>
United States Information Service (USIS) director George Newman
 confirmed the experts' conclusion of their assignment into the
Lusaka bombings Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Newman said the bomb experts who have since left Zambia had
handed over their report on the bombings to the State, Times of
Zambia newspaper reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Newman said details of the experts findings would be made
public by the Zambian government as the undertaking was only to
offer technical expertise to the local team.
</P>
<P>
He clarified that the experts were not agents from the Federal
Bureau of Investigations (FBI) but from DSW and BATF.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Zambian Government Spokesman Newstead Zimba, who is
Information and Broadcasting Minister, said the experts could have
directly submitted their findings to Zambian President Frederick
Chiluba.
</P>
<P>
A series of bomb blasts aimed at destabilizing Zambia by
cutting off electricity and water supply rocked Lusaka three weeks
ago. Bombs were planted at vital installations with others in
residential areas.
</P>
<P>
A security guard at the Angolan embassy was killed by one of
the bombs planted at the embassy. Three other people were
seriously wounded.
</P>
<P>
The government described the bomb blasts as acts of terrorism
and Chiluba immediately called on all Zambians to be vigilant.
</P>
<P>
Later, the government asked for assistance from the U.S. and
other countries to investigate the bombings. 
</P>
</TEXT>
