<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jiang's Visit "A Historical Event": Austrian Ambassador </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 18 (Xinhua) -- The upcoming state visit of
Chinese President Jiang Zemin to Austria is "without any
exaggeration a historical event," said the new Austria ambassador
to China Erich Buttenhauser.
</P>
<P>
Arriving in China less than a month ago, the ambassador is
returning to his country to prepare for President Jiang's visit.
Before his departure, he answered Xinhua's questions on Jiang's
visit and bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
He underlined that "this is the first time that a Chinese head
of state will pay a visit to our country, and President Jiang
Zemin is reciprocating two state visits to China by Austrian
presidents in 1985 and 1995."
</P>
<P>
According to Buttenhauser, President Jiang is expected to "have
a wide-ranging exchange of views with his Austrian counterpart,
President Thomas Klestil, on all matters of common concern, and
discuss ways and means of promoting bilateral relations,
especially in the field of economic cooperation."
</P>
<P>
Since Austria and China established diplomatic relations in
1971, the economic and trade cooperation between the two countries
have "developed impressively," he said, adding that there is still
untapped potential on both sides in various fields, including
environmental protection projects.
</P>
<P>
Concerning China's relations with the European Union (EU), he
said that "all EU member states follow a common approach toward
China as spelled out on the 'Building A Comprehensive Partnership
with China' document adopted last year by the EU's Council of
Foreign Ministers."
</P>
<P>
With an integrated domestic market and the Euro as the single
currency, the EU is "an important partner for China economically
and politically beyond any doubt," he noted, adding that both
sides have "enormous potential to enhance cooperation."
</P>
<P>
Cultural exchanges between China ad Austria have witnessed
tremendous growth in recent years, and the ambassador said he
considers such contacts "very important to further mutual
understanding between the two peoples."
</P>
<P>
Austrians are now enjoying more Chinese cultural performances
staged in Vienna and other cities, while Austrian musicians, in
particular the Vienna Philharmonic Orchestra and the Vienna State
Opera have been welcomed in China, he said.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, according to the ambassador, there will be a Viennese
music garden at the World Horticultural Fair in Kunming, capital
of southwest China's Yunnan Province later this year, and a Johann
Strauss exhibition and folk music performances are planned for
Beijing in October. "We will continue to promote bilateral
cultural activities between our two countries," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
