<DOCNO> XIE19990318.0180 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Calls for Strengthening Monitoring of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, March 18 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Vice Finance Minister Jin
Liqun Thursday urged the international community to strengthen the
monitoring of short-term capital flows and to reform the
international financial architecture.
</P>
<P>
Jin made this call in a speech at the first meeting of finance
and central bank deputies from nine members of ASEAN plus China,
Japan and the Republic of Korea (9+3).
</P>
<P>
The convening of the "9+3 meeting" on finance was proposed by
Chinese Vice President Hu Jintao at the second informal summit of
East Asian countries held in Hanoi last December.
</P>
<P>
In his speech, Jin said the financial crisis in Asia has been
going on for well over one year now. Financial crises are not new
demons wrecking havoc of the economies in the world. But none of
the crises witnessed so far hit so hard on many economies in a
matter of months, and with such devastating impact.
</P>
<P>
Analyzing the causes of the financial crises, Jin said there
are some defects within the affected economies. But there are also
serious deficiencies in the international financial system.
</P>
<P>
Particularly destabilizing are swings of huge volumes of
short-term capital flows prowling around the globe in pursuit of
quick profit, said the Chinese senior financial official.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that "international efforts on crisis resolution
and prevention cannot be effective if their focus is just directed
on domestic issues of individual economies, while marginalizing
the destabilizing factors external to those economies."
</P>
<P>
Jin noted that the Asian financial turmoil has revealed serious
flaws in the structure of financial markets and in the ways the
players in the markets are regulated. While the trend of global
integration is irreversible, appropriate actions can certainly be
taken to reduce the frequency and amplitude of financial market
swings.
</P>
<P>
"Financial markets would not swing so wildly if financial
institutions were more closely monitored," the official said,
adding "this has particular relevance for emerging economies, as
an interplay of domestic financial-sector weakness and
international capital flows inflicts even more violent impact."
</P>
<P>
Jin said the quick spreading of the recent crisis has offered
us so much food for thought in contemplating reforming the
international financial architecture.
</P>
<P>
Obviously, he said, in an increasingly integrated world,
financial turmoil in any one economy also poses serious danger to
others. Crisis does not stay confined in one economy, or even one
region. It can spread through current-account linkages among
economies, through capital account transactions, or just be
triggered by sheer investor perception of linkages.
</P>
<P>
Jin said there is no absolute "safe haven." No "firewalls"
between economies with "resilient financial systems" and emerging
market economies.
</P>
<P>
"It is in the interests of every economy to cooperate closely
with each other in strengthening the monitoring of short-term
capital flows and mitigating the potential violence of financial
system turmoil," Jin stressed.
</P>
<P>
However, the Chinese official also noted that strengthening
monitoring of short-term capital flows is not intended to impede
the flows of capital. "Rather, such efforts aim at promoting
capital flows in an orderly fashion," Jin said.
</P>
<P>
Jin said that "concerted efforts in this area will be a big
step forward in making the global financial system more conducive
to sustainable economic growth and social development." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
