<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnam Gains Success in Anti-Drug Abuse Campaign </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, March 18 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam's anti-drug abuse campaign
has achieved successes in the past more than three months, press
reports said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Details of the campaign were reported at a meeting of Vietnam's
National Drug Control Committee held in Hanoi Wednesday, which
reviewed the implementation of the prime minister's decree
ordering the campaign against drug abuse.
</P>
<P>
From November 30, 1998 to March 15, 1999, policemen, customs
officers and border guards nationwide detected 3,826 cases of drug
trafficking involving 7,640 offenders and confiscated more than 14
kilograms of heroin, 106 kilograms of opium and 68.3 kilograms of
marijuana.
</P>
<P>
Vietnamese people's courts in this period tried 541
drug-related cases involving 857 offenders, of whom 19 were given
death sentences.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam now has 97,000 registered drug addicts, including 8,000
prisoners.
</P>
<P>
Most drug trafficking cases were detected along the
Vietnam-Laos border but marijuana trafficking was also detected
along the border with Cambodia.
</P>
<P>
About 45,000 square meters of opium poppy fields and 760 square
meters of marijuana and coca crops were destroyed in the period.
However, some destroyed fields along the Vietnam-Laos border have
been re-grown with opium poppy.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam has also intensified the fight against drug abuse in
offices, resident communities and schools. Almost 2,200 drug
addicts were sent to detoxification centers in the period.
</P>
<P>
The media also carried extensive reports aimed at raising
public awareness of drug control policies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
