<DOCNO> XIE19990318.0185 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Drought Conditions Threaten Winter Wheat in Northern China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The drought has adversely affected over a third of China's
cross-winter crops, the Ministry of Agriculture said today.
</P>
<P>
The ministry has urged local governments to strengthen field
management in areas such as irrigation and fertilization.
</P>
<P>
The rapid growth of winter wheat during the unseasonably warm
winter increased the vulnerability of the crop to colder weather,
according to one ministry official.
</P>
<P>
"Wheat is subject to freezing if temperatures drop suddenly,"
the official said.
</P>
<P>
Chinese farmers planted cross-winter crops on 33 million
hectares in 1998, including some 26 million hectares of winter
wheat.
</P>
<P>
The lack of sufficient precipitation and higher temperatures
since September last year have exacerbated the situation in the
country's leading wheat growing bases in the Yellow and Huaihe
River valleys, as well as various areas in northern China.
</P>
<P>
However, drought conditions have eased somewhat in parts of the
Huaihe River Valley, including Anhui, Jiangsu and Hubei provinces,
as well as southern areas in Shandong and Henan provinces.
</P>
<P>
Local meteorological departments forecast the arrival of
measurable precipitation in northern wheat-growing areas over the
next several days.
</P>
<P>
Summer grain yields account for approximately 25 percent of
China's annual grain production. The total grain output for 1998
hit 490 million tons, with 14.6 million top drop in the summer
grain output offset by an increase in autumn grain production.
</P>
<P>
China recorded good grain harvest for four consecutive years
prior to 1988.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
