<TEXT>
<P>
HOHHOT, March 18 (Xinhua) -- Eighty-eight projects funded by
the central Government over the past six months, concerning
renovation of power grid, transportation and telecommunications,
have promoted economic development in north China's Inner Mongolia
Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
The Government allocated an additional 200 billion yuan (24
billion US dollars) in the latter half of last year for
infrastructure construction in the region.
</P>
<P>
Related funding has also sparked growth in investments from non-
state enterprises and individuals, with the latter category alone
rising by 16.6 percent. Fixed asset investments for 1998 grew by
10 percent on the previous year's level to 35 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
The sales rate for industrial products grew from 92 percent for
the six months of 1998 to 96.6 percent for the year as a whole.
The heavy industry sector reversed low-speed, or in some cases
negative growth, and recorded 6.5 percent growth by the end of
last year.
</P>
<P>
The new funds have mainly gone to infrastructure construction,
including housing, transportation, telecommunications and
infrastructure projects in urban areas. The region has also
encouraged development of the service sector in order to create
more jobs.
</P>
<P>
Real estate, community services, and post and
telecommunications sector have recorded the most rapid economic
development. 
