<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Scientists Say Laws Needed To Prevent Disasters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 18 (Xinhua) -- Chinese geologists said at a
recent Chinese government meeting that a legal system is needed to
prevent geological deterioration.
</P>
<P>
The scientists from the Chinese Academy of Sciences and the
Chinese Academy of Engineering said that nearly 50 percent of the
land, mud, and rock slides, land subsidence, erosions, sea water
encroachment, and desertification are caused by human beings and
that these are an obstacle to economic growth and social stability
in the areas where they occur.
</P>
<P>
More than 400 cities and counties and about 10,000 villages in
China are threatened by land, mud, and rock slides and land
subsidence has been reported in 46 large and medium-sized cities.
</P>
<P>
Desertification is largely attributed to the building of
reservoirs and dams that go against the law of nature.
</P>
<P>
Officials say that a thorough study has been done and that a
related regulation issued by the Ministry of Land Resources is
working well and that conditions are right for the National
People's Congress to pass a related law.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, government institutions have monitored
disasters caused by human beings. During last year's floods, 52
mud and rock slides were successfully predicted.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
