<HEADLINE> Lebanese Woman Wounded in Israeli Bombardment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, March 18 (Xinhua) -- An elderly Lebanese woman was
wounded Wednesday night when Israeli warplanes staged several
raids on villages in south Lebanon, the Daily Star reported
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli warplanes dropped bombs between Jabal Botom and
Zibqine, north of the western sector of the Israeli occupied
border zone in south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
The planes returned 20 miniutes later and bombed the area
surrounding Shaitieh, north of Zibqine, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
Wassila Khalil, 67, from Zibqine, was struck in the head by
shrapnel when a bomb exploded beside her as she was working in a
field.
</P>
<P>
Eight houses in the village were also damaged in the raids,
which came shortly after the nearby Israeli Blat and Teir Harfa
outposts were shelled by Lebanese guerrillas of the Iran-backed
Hezbollah, or Party of God.
</P>
<P>
Another civilian, Youssef Alayan, was wounded earlier Wednesday
when Hezbollah guerrillas fired rounds at the Israeli Biyada
radar station inside the border zone.
</P>
<P>
Israel set up the self-proclaimed security zone in south
Lebanon in 1985 with the claimed aim of protecting its north from
Lebanese guerrillas' cross-border attacks.
</P>
<P>
Since then, Lebanon's resistance movement spearheaded by
Hezbollah has been fighting to drive Israeli occupation forces
and its ally South Lebanon Army out of the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
