<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading Israeli Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, March 18 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading Israeli newspapers on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Jerusalem Post
</P>
<P>
-- The Teachers Union of Israel will step up its strike on
Thursday with kindergartens around the country cutting short
openning time by two hours a day. The teachers are protesting
"the stalling tactics" by the Finance Ministry in negotiations on
a new wage agreement with them.
</P>
<P>
Haaretz
</P>
<P>
-- Israeli Government Employment Service said on Wednesday
that the number of Israelis seeking work rose 2.7 percent from
January to February. There were 157,000 Israelis looking for work
last month, compared with 152,900 in January.
</P>
<P>
Yediot Aharonot
</P>
<P>
-- Aryeh Deri, who is chairing the powerful Shas Party of
Israel, was convicted of bribe-taking, fraud and breach of public
trust by Jerusalem District Court on Wednesday. In response, Deri
rejected the verdict and said he would appeal to the supreme
court. 
</P>
</TEXT>
