<HEADLINE> Minnesota, San Antonio to Play in 1999 NBA Japan Games </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, March 18 (Xinhua) -- The Minnesota Timberwolves and the
San Antonio Spurs will play two regular season National Basketball
Association (NBA) games in Tokyo in November, the NBA announced
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The scheduled fixtures mark the fifth time NBA has staged
regular season games in Japan, according to the league.
</P>
<P>
"The NBA Japan Games have become a highlight of our calendar,"
said NBA Commissioner David Stern. "Our Japanese fans are among
the most enthusiastic, and we are pleased to continue our
tradition of playing regular season games at Tokyo Dome."
</P>
<P>
In 1990, the NBA became the first American professional league
to stage regular season games outside North America when the
Phoenix Suns and the Utah Jazz opened the 1990-1991 season in
Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
In 1992, the Houston Rockets and Seattle SuperSonics opened the
season with two games in Yokohama, as did the LA Clippers and the
Portland Blazers in 1994. In 1996 the event moved to the lager
Tokyo Kome, where the two games between the New Jersey Nets and
the Orlando Magic drew over 75,000 fans.
</P>
<P>
Minnesota and San Antonio will play at Tokyo Dome on November 6
and 7. It will be the first time to play in Japan for the two
teams.
</P>
<P>
The complete 1999-2000 NBA regular season schedule will be
announced in mid-July while tickets will go on sale in mid-June.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
