<HEADLINE> Roundup: China, Switzerland Sees Steady Trade Growth (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 18 (Xinhua) -- From Nescafe to Rolex watches,
from Schindler elevators to Swiss knives, products made in
Switzerland are becoming increasingly familiar to Chinese citizens.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Chinese products, such as garments and textile goods,
machinery and electrical appliances, and chemical goods, have also
become very popular in Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
In recent years Sino-Swiss trade relations and economic
cooperation have been expanding steadily, officials with the
Chinese Ministry of Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation MOFTEC)
said in an interview with Xinhua on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"Leaders from China and Switzerland have had a frequent
exchange of visits since 1992 and the two sides have signed a
dozen bilateral agreements on trade and other issues," said an
official with the European Affairs Department of the MOFTEC. "The
upcoming state visit by President Jiang Zemin to Switzerland will
further boost the bilateral trade and economic cooperation."
</P>
<P>
Switzerland is China's second largest trade partner in western
Europe after the European Union. Bilateral trade volume hit a
record in 1997 of 1.486 billion US dollars.
</P>
<P>
However, the volume of imports and exports in 1998 between the
two nations reached 1.43 billion US dollars, down 3.8 percent.
China's exports to Switzerland were recorded at 634 million US
dollars, up 3.4 percent, and imports from Switzerland 796 million
US dollars, down 8.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, Swiss investment in China has grown in a big
margin in the 1990s. The Roche company, the Ciba-Geigy company and
the Nestle company, for instance, have established many
pharmaceuticals and foodstuff joint ventures in China.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990318.0203 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: China, Switzerland Sees Steady Trade Growth (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In addition, China and Switzerland have enjoyed smooth
cooperation in the financial sector, said MOFTEC officials. The
Swiss Government has provided four government loans to China since
August 1984, totaling 350 million Swiss Francs (about 260 million
US dollars).
</P>
<P>
Those loans have been used in the construction of more than 60
projects in the areas of textiles, telecommunications, medicine,
machine-building, electricity, environmental protection and civil
construction.
</P>
<P>
Switzerland is also a major technology supplier to China.
Between 1979 and the end of 1998, China has approved the signing
of 640 technology transfer contracts with Switzerland, involving
some 1.41 billion US dollars.
</P>
<P>
China and Switzerland established diplomatic relations in 1950,
and Switzerland was one of the first western countries to
recognize New China. And the Sino-Swiss Joint Trade Committee,
established in December 1974 following the signing of a bilateral
trade agreement, has held 14 meetings so far in Beijing and Berne
respectively.
</P>
<P>
The Swiss Government granted China universal favorable
treatment in 1979 and has always given an active support to China
in its bid to join the World Trade Organization (WTO). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
