<HEADLINE> Zambian, Malawian Police Curb Cross-Border Crime </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, March 18 (Xinhua) -- Zambian and Malawian police have
strengthened their cooperation in a bid to effectively curb
cross-border crime involving car thefts, Zambia Daily Mail
reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The local newspaper quoted Eastern Division police commanding
officer, Lyson Simwanda, as saying Wednesday that thefts
especially involving cars have been reduced due to the "cordial
relations" existing between the wings.
</P>
<P>
He said the two wings have on a number of occasions consulted
each other on some crime prevention methods.
</P>
<P>
"We have had a lot of consultative meetings on how best to
bring down the rate of crime which has rocked the border area," he
said.
</P>
<P>
He appreciated police command for installing good communication
 facilities, making it easier for his men to effectively
communicate with their counterparts in an effort to nab criminals.
</P>
<P>
The two wings extended their relations to social activities
such as football and other activities, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
