<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Northeast Industrial Province Expects More Tourists </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, March 18 (Xinhua) -- Liaoning Province, an old
industrial base in northeast China, expects to receive 39.13
million tourists this year.
</P>
<P>
Chen Xi, director of Liaoning Provincial Tourism Administration,
said they hope revenue from tourism sector will make up five
percent of the province's gross domestic product (GDP).
</P>
<P>
According to Chen, the province will have an increase of 13.6
percent in total earnings this year from the tourism sector which
will generate 2.39 billion U.S. dollars, including 270 million U.S.
dollars from overseas tourists.
</P>
<P>
Ying Zhongyuan, Chen's assistant, outlined measures to attract
more tourists to this northeast Chinese province, including
redoubling efforts to improve local tourism environment, intensify
promotion of tourism programs and opening 49 carefully-selected
major tourist projects to overseas investors.
</P>
<P>
Liaoning received 35.2 million tourists last year, and raked in
2.22 billion U.S. dollars in total earnings from its tourism
industry, up 13 percent over 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
