<DOCNO> XIE19990318.0212 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Everbright Bank Acquires Assets, Liabilities, Offices of CIB </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 18 (Xinhua) -- China Everbright Bank officially
takes over assets and liabilities of former China Investment Bank
(CIB) today along with the transfer of 137 banking offices under
the CIB all over the country.
</P>
<P>
Zhu Xiaohua, chairman of Everbright, signed the agreement with
Chen Yuan, president of China Development Bank (CDB), at the Great
Hall of the People this morning.
</P>
<P>
The CIB was merged into the CDB last December and its 20
regional branches were converted into CDB branches on March 16.
</P>
<P>
Total assets involved in this transfer are 80 billion yuan (9.6
billion US dollars), according to the People's Bank of China, the
country's central bank.
</P>
<P>
Non-performing loans from the CIB, which largely stem from sub-
loans from the World Bank, will be reduced to less than 20 percent
after the write-off of the bad loans, Zhu said.
</P>
<P>
He also said that non-performing loans in foreign exchange,
which account for 78 percent of CIB's total non-performing loans,
will be dealt with by Everbright acting as an agent to collect
these loans for the Finance Ministry.
</P>
<P>
The rest of the non-performing loans will be written off by net
asset and capital reserves of the CIB as well as capital from
Everbright, Zhu added.
</P>
<P>
The 137 banking offices of the CIB in China's major cities
including Beijing, Shanghai, Shenzhen, and Guangzhou will be
complementary to Everbright's business, and the cost of the
transfer will be much lower than that of establishing new offices
there, he said.
</P>
<P>
China Everbright Bank is a joint-stock commercial bank with
state-owned companies as its major stockholders. Its pre-tax
profit in 1998 was 1.31 billion yuan, and its per capita profit
was number one among China's domestic banks.
</P>
<P>
Zhu anticipates that the bank's profit next year will reach 2
billion yuan after absorbing the assets of the CIB properly, and
he expects that this figure will grow to 2.6 billion yuan in 2001.
</P>
<P>
All the certificates of deposits, treasury bonds, and other
securities issued by the CIB will remain effective, and all
contracts and agreements on loans, inter-bank lending and
borrowing, and bond repurchases by the CIB will remain valid,
according to Everbright.
</P>
<P>
Wang Guangying, vice-chairman of the Standing Committee of the
Chinese National People's Congress, attended the signing ceremony
along with officials from the central bank and the Ministry of
Finance.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
