<HEADLINE> Shanghai's Banks Show More Interest in Small Firms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, March 18 (Xinhua) -- Commercial banks in Shanghai,
China's leading industrial and commercial city, are now taking
steps to give greater support to small and medium-sized
enterprises.
</P>
<P>
The first bank to enhance these is the Bank of Shanghai which
began to provide special loans to small and medium-sized firms in
1996, setting up a service center for these enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Among the 210,000 enterprises that have opened accounts with
the bank, 170,000 are small and medium-sized high-tech,
manufacturing and retail businesses.
</P>
<P>
Another bank, the Shanghai Branch of the Industrial and
Commercial Bank of China, recently announced ten new measures to
support these firms, including a special department in charge of
loans and the simplification of loan procedures.
</P>
<P>
"Small and medium-sized enterprises are more flexible and
competitive than larger ones, and they should get greater
financial support," said branch chief Jiang Jianqing, adding that
his branch will grant loans on the basis of efficiency rather than
size.
</P>
<P>
Small and medium-sized enterprises have usually been neglected
by banks, and many have found it difficult to expand due to a lack
of funds over the past decades.
</P>
<P>
Local experts say this new support represents a strategic
change in bank lending policy which is intended to foster new
growth areas.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
