<DOCNO> XIE19990318.0221 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Regional Disarmament Meeting Opens in Kathmandu </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, March 18 (Xinhua) -- The 11th Regional Disarmament
Meeting in Asia and the Pacific began here Thursday, bringing
together 38 participants from 25 countries and organizations in
the region.
</P>
<P>
The three-day meeting is hosted by the Regional Center for
Peace and Disarmament in Asia and the Pacific of the United
Nations Department for Disarmament Affairs.
</P>
<P>
In his opening statement, Evgeniy Gorkovskiy, deputy to the
United Nations Under Secretary-General for Disarmament Affairs,
said the meeting will focus on nuclear tests in South Asia,
security issues in the Korean peninsula and cooperation between
the United Nations and regional organizations.
</P>
<P>
The Asian financial crisis, flow of arms in civil society,
poverty eradication and cooperation on environment conservation
are also on the agenda of the meeting, he said.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. official said the nuclear tests conducted last year by
India and Pakistan posed great challenges to the well-established
and globally-supported norms of non-proliferation and non-testing
of nuclear weapons as well as the norm of nuclear disarmament.
</P>
<P>
He noted that at their recent summit, prime ministers of the
two countries agreed to make efforts to reduce tensions in the
sub-continent, which included commitment to taking immediate steps
toward reducing the risk of accidental or unauthorized use of
nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
The two sides also agreed to review existing
confidence-building measures and where necessary, to engage in
mutual consultations on the monitoring and implementation of such
measures, he said.
</P>
<P>
"This meeting will provide an opportunity for participants from
the two states to inform the Asia-Pacific community about the
details of the agreements and how these states expect to implement
them," he added.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. official said for the first time, the three existing
regional organizations in the region -- the South Asian
Association for Regional Cooperation, the South Pacific Forum and
the Association of Southeast Asian Nations, will present reports
on their respective activities.
</P>
<P>
"I hope this meeting will serve as an opportunity for both the
regional center and the three organizations to work out a way of
maintaining contact and increasing interaction to tackle common
recognized challenges," he said.
</P>
<P>
Established and given a clear mandate by U.N. General Assembly
resolutions, the regional center for peace and disarmament is the
broadest-based dialog mechanism in the region, encompassing South
Asia and Central Asia in addition to all of East Asia, Oceania and
the United States.
</P>
<P>
The annual gathering in Kathmandu has been often referred to as
the Kathmandu Process.
</P>
<P>
The meetings "provide an invaluable forum for leading
diplomats, government officials, scholars and non-governmental
organizations to exchange views on current challenges in the field
of disarmament and security," Evgeniy Gorkovskiy said.
</P>
<P>
"Our experience so far confirms that such an informal
atmosphere facilitates the friendly and constructive discussion of
even the most sensitive and highly contentious issues," he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990318.0222 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Timely Snowfall for Northeastern China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGCHUN, March 18 (Xinhua) -- Another light snowfall last
night, the fourth this month, has brought moisture to drought
stricken northeastern China's Jilin Province.
</P>
<P>
There has been more snow than usual in March in northeastern
China's Jilin Province, as opposed to its usual windy climate at
this time of the year. This has helped alleviate drought problems
and pollution which have persisted throughout the winter.
</P>
<P>
Another snowfall is predicted for today or March 19. The
average amount of snowfall has been around 17 millimeters.
</P>
<P>
Discussing their relief at the change in the weather, a
resident of Changchun City said, "Most families keep warm by a
coalfire, which gives off a lot of dust and smoke, and a shortage
or lack of snow has made the air condition even worse."
</P>
<P>
And farmer Liang Shuhua said, "We were afraid that the lack of
snow might result in drought and affect our spring sowing."
</P>
<P>
Zhu Qiwen, head of the Jilin Provincial Meteorological
Observatory, noted that snowfalls made the temperature of the
whole province this March four degrees centigrade lower compared
with corresponding periods in the past.
</P>
<P>
An official with the Changchun Environmental Protection Bureau
said that the snow has improved the air quality in a big way.
</P>
</TEXT>
