<HEADLINE> President Jiang's Visit Historical: Italian Ambassador to China (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Rome is the political center of Italy, Milan a city of
economics and trade, and Venice world renowned for its stunning
architecture and scenic views, Paolo Bruni said.
</P>
<P>
Following Italian president Oscar Luigi Scalfaro's visit to
China last year, President Jiang Zemin will pay a state visit to
Italy from March 20 to 25, the first stop of a three-leg European
tour, which also includes Switzerland and Austria.
</P>
<P>
Bruni believes that the itinerary reflects the purpose of
Jiang's visit -- promoting cooperation between the two countries
in political, economic, cultural and other sectors.
</P>
<P>
Jiang's visit is also historical and signals the importance of
the good relations between Italy and China, Bruni said during a
recent interview with Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
The ambassador added that the visit will create an opportunity
for the two presidents to discuss a number of international and
regional issues of common concern, and to explore ways to further
promote world peace and security as well as ways to avoid the
negative effects of the continuing Asian financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
Bruni said diplomatic ties and trade relations between the two
countries can be traced back to ancient times. Since Marco Polo's
book allegedly first introduced China to the world some 750 years
ago, many contacts in the cultural and scientific fields have been
made.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990318.0224 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> President Jiang's Visit Historical: Italian Ambassador (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"All of these factors have considerably promoted bilateral
cooperation in a wide range of sectors," Bruni said, expressing
the conviction that Jiang's visit would push forward such
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
For most Chinese, Italy is known for its glorious wine and
fashionable clothes, Bruni said. However, he pointed out that some
80 percent of Italian exports to China are products based on
science and technology. "The present economic and trade
cooperation is sound, but there's still immense development
potential," he added.
</P>
<P>
According to him, China now is Italy's third largest trade
partner out of Europe. "The two governments are encouraging
cooperation between small and medium-sized enterprises, seeking to
expand trade volumes and mutual investment."
</P>
<P>
The ambassador revealed that Jiang's entourage would include a
number of high-ranking economic and trade officials and that they
will meet representatives of a number of Italian industrial groups.
</P>
<P>
"For two countries with such ancient civilizations, cultural
exchange is one of the most important aspects of dialog," Bruni
commented. Last year, the Teatro Communale di Firenze presented
Puccini's opera Turandot in China's Forbidden City and in March
this year the China Peking Opera Theater is performing in Italy.
</P>
<P>
"People are looking forward to more such cultural events which
can help them better understand each other," Bruni said.
</P>
<P>
According to the ambassador, President Jiang will probably find
some time to enjoy an Italian opera during his stay in his country.
</P>
