<HEADLINE> China Puts Its First Steam Locomotive into Retirement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HEFEI, March 18 (Xinhua) -- China's first domestic manufactured
steam locomotive was "retired" recently after 47 years of service
and is expected to be put on display in the locomotive museum in
Datong in north China's Shanxi Province.
</P>
<P>
The locomotive was manufactured by the Sifang Rolling Stock
Plant in east China's Shandong Province in July 1952 and had been
in use in east Anhui Province until 1992.
</P>
<P>
China stopped producing steam locomotives in 1987 due to
environmental and economic reasons and so far there are only a
small number of them still running in the country.
</P>
<P>
China now mainly produces internal-combustion and electric-
power locomotives.
</P>
<P>
As many as 927 million passengers traveled by trains in China
in 1998, with cargo traffic reaching 1.523 billion tons.
</P>
<P>
China added 994 kilometers to the length of its electrified
railways lines in 1998.
</P>
<P>
In 1999, the country will invest 55 billion yuan on railway
capital construction, in a bid to add 1,320 kilometers to its
railway lines and 730 kilometers to the electrified lines. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990318.0226 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Government Calls for Improved Enterprise Management </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 18 (Xinhua) -- China's State Economic and Trade
Commission (SETC) recently issued a circular calling for improving
enterprise management in order to accelerate reform and help state-
owned enterprises escape financial difficulties.
</P>
<P>
The circular urges all large and medium-sized state-owned
enterprises, with the exception of venture anticipating bankruptcy
or closure, to formulate and complete rectification and reform
plans by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
State-owned enterprises, especially ventures operating in the
red, have been urged to strengthen management, enhance quality
control, improve cost management and curb non-production
expenditures.
</P>
<P>
The enterprises are also required to introduce a budget
management system and establish a stricter financial system.
</P>
<P>
The SETC called on state-owned enterprises to reach or exceed
the average national rate for circulating capital by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
Related enterprises will also be required to introduce
investment and financing decision-making mechanisms suited to
market conditions.
</P>
<P>
Large and medium-sized enterprise have also been urged to deal
with redundant workers and improve efficiency.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
