<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe Rejects FBI Probe Offer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, March 18 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Federal Bureau of
Investigation (FBI) has sent an officer to Harare to discuss the
arrest of three American nationals with the Zimbabwean government
and offer assistance to investigating agencies, but the officer
was rejected, the daily Herald reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
A U.S. embassy spokesman in Harare confirmed Wednesday that one
FBI agent and a U.S. customs officer arrived in the country Monday
from Pretoria, South Africa, ostensibly to offer assistance to the
Zimbabwean multi-agency investigating team.
</P>
<P>
However, the two left Harare Wednesday after their offer was
turned down.
</P>
<P>
It is understood that the offer was first made to Zimbabwean
Police Commissioner Augustine Chihuri, who told them the
multi-agency investigating team did not want any assistance from
outside forces. The offer was also turned down by the Zimbabwean
government.
</P>
<P>
Source said the FBI and customs officers were refused access to
the arrested Americans at Chikurubi Maximum Security Prison in
Harare.
</P>
<P>
The three U.S. nationals were arrested at the Harare
International Airport on March 7 for illegal possession of
offensive weapons and other war materials.
</P>
<P>
However, embassy officials were Wednesday granted permission to
visit the trio.
</P>
<P>
The multi-agency investigating team is yet to receive
additional information on the activities of the three suspects
from the U.S. embassy.
</P>
<P>
The embassy last week dissociated itself from the three
suspects who were found with a wide range of arms of war.
</P>
<P>
It is understood that the three Americans have admitted
plotting to assassinate President Laurent Kabila of the Democratic
Republic of Congo as part of their efforts to install a "godly"
government in the war-torn country, the Herald reported. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
