<DOCNO> XIE19990318.0233 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China To Plant Trees along Yellow River Delta </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JINAN, March 18 (Xinhua) -- East China's Shandong Province
will launch a massive afforestation campaign this year in the
Yellow River Delta, one of the country's three major river deltas.
</P>
<P>
About 80,000 hectares of land will be afforested over the next
five years.
</P>
<P>
This move is designed to further improve the ecological
environment of the delta, paving the way for fast economic
development, said Sun Qingchuan, vice director of the provincial
forestry department.
</P>
<P>
According to Sun, the Yellow River Delta has long been
economically backward because of saline soil and various disasters,
and this is in sharp contrast to the prosperity and high economic
growth of the Yangtze River Delta and the Pearl River Delta.
</P>
<P>
Shandong, which depends largely on the Yellow River for its
water supply, has been suffering from a water shortage in recent
years as flow stoppages occur more frequently on the river because
of reduced rainfall.
</P>
<P>
The new forests, which will be planted at a cost of 240 million
yuan, will grow along the lower reaches of the river.
</P>
<P>
The province has selected trees such as locusts and willows
which can better survive in the saline soil for this project.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990318.0234 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 </DATE_TIME>
