<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan's Trade Surplus Down 26.9 Percent in February </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, March 18 (Xinhua) -- Japan's trade surplus in February
dropped 26.9 percent from a year earlier to 934.2 billion yen (8.2
billion U.S. dollars) due to a larger decline in exports than
imports, the Finance Ministry said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
It is the first time that Japan's trade surplus has fallen in
three straight months.
</P>
<P>
Japan's exports contracted 12.3 percent to 3,591.2 billion yen
(31.5 billion dollars) for the 60th straight month decline, while
imports decreased 5.7 percent to 2,657 billion yen (23.3 billion
dollars) for the 14th straight month, the ministry said in a
preliminary report.
</P>
<P>
Japan's politically sensitive trade surplus with the United
States fell 22.7 percent to 414.9 billion yen (3.6 billion dollars)
because of a 49.4 percent plunge in shipments of steel to the US,
the ministry said.
</P>
<P>
Japan's exports to its Asian neighbors dropped 18 percent while
imports increased 1.8 percent. As a result, Japan's surplus with
these countries slumped by 57.3 percent to 208.8 billion yen (1.8
billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
The surplus with the European Union inched down 0.1 percent to
348.4 billion yen (3.1 billion dollars), its first fall in three
months, the ministry said.
</P>
<P>
The yen averaged 114.18 to the U.S. dollar in February, up 10.2
percent from a year earlier. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990318.0241 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Leaders of Mexican Ruling Party to Step Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, March 17 (Xinhua) -- The president and secretary-
general of Mexico's ruling Institutional Revolutionary Party (PRI)
announced on Wednesday that the president would step down to let a
new leadership work out rules for selecting PRI candidates for the
2000 presidential elections.
</P>
<P>
PRI President Mariano Palacios Alcocer and his Secretary-
General Carlos Rojas Gutierrez made the surprise announcement at
the start of the new session of the party's governing council.
</P>
<P>
Palacios explained that the reason for his resignation was "to
renew the party's strength ahead of the 2000 elections" and to
make the selection of the PIR 2000 presidential candidates more "
democratic and transparent."
</P>
<P>
Well-informed sources said the two PRI leaders were resigning
under heavy pressure from inside the party. The president's
resignation is effective as of April 1.
</P>
<P>
Two weeks ago the PRI, the world's longest-ruling party,
celebrated its 70th anniversary in power. President Ernesto
Zedillo announced at the celebration that he would break with
tradition and not hand-pick the party's presidential candidate. He
urged the party to hold an internal election.
</P>
<P>
Replacements for the two leaders will be chosen through the
first democratic election within the PRI in the party's history.
</P>
</TEXT>
