<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Uruguay Reduces Trade Deficit With Mercosur </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MONTEVIDEO, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Uruguay slashed its trade
deficit with its three associate countries of the Southern Common
Market (Mercosur) by more than half last year.
</P>
<P>
According to the Central Bank, the trade deficit dropped by 55
percent from 260 million dollars in 1997 to 117 million dollars in
1998.
</P>
<P>
Argentina, Brazil and Paraguay were listed as the principal
trade partners of Uruguay in 1998, taking 55 percent of the
country's total exports and providing 43 percent of imports.
</P>
<P>
Argentina, Brazil, Paraguay and Uruguay are the four members of
the customs union Mercosur (the South American Common Market),
which is also the largest trade bloc in Latin America.
</P>
<P>
Last year, trade between Uruguay and its three partners had
reached 3.18 billion dollars, of which 1.53 billion dollars were
registered as exports while 1.64 billion dollars were imports.
</P>
<P>
The total trade volume between Uruguay and Brazil was put at 1.
72 billion dollars, including 935.2 million dollars of exports and
793.4 million dollars of imports, a trade surplus of 141.8 million
dollars in favor of Uruguay.
</P>
<P>
Uruguay's exports to Argentina were valued at 513.2 million
dollars, while its imports were 839.3 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
The bank information reported a relatively low record with
Paraguay, with exports registered at 83.9 million dollars and
imports at 16.4 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
In 1998, the total external sales of Uruguay were calculated at
2.76 billion dollars, with an overall deficit of 1.04 billion
dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
