<HEADLINE> Xinhua World Economic News Summary at 0500, March 18 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The strong economic growth of 1998 brought the
new year with robust consumer spending, brisk construction
activity and increasing demand for labor, the U.S. Federal Reserve
said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, prices of most goods remain little changed and
businesses remain reluctant to press for price increases, the Fed
said in a survey of regional economic conditions before March 8,
known as the "Beige Book." Analysts said the combination of
thriving economic growth and absent inflation detected in the
survey implies Fed policy-makers probably will opt for no change
in interest rates when they meet on March 30. (US-Economy-
Prediction)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
TEGUCIGALPA -- The International Monetary Fund (IMF) this year
will pay out 100 million dollars of the 220- million-dollar fund
approved for Honduras over three years.
</P>
<P>
Sources from the Honduran Economic Cabinet said on Wednesday
that the money would be used to help balance payments under the
Reinforced Service of Structural Adjustment (RSSA) agreement. The
rest of the money will be paid in 2000 and 2001, depending on the
compliance with the RSSA agreement, which established a six-month
revision to check on compliance and the results. (IMF-Honduras)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
