<HEADLINE> German, Austrian Premiers Discuss EU Issues </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
VIENNA, March 17 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU) summit
scheduled for next week in Berlin should make the formation of a
new European Commission a priority, German Federal Chancellor
Gerhard Schroeder said here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference following his meeting with Austrian
counterpart Viktor Klima, Schroeder said he believed incumbent
European Commission President Jacques Santer would not run for
another term as commission president.
</P>
<P>
The 20-member European Commission resigned on Tuesday after
independent experts accused it of turning a blind eye to fraud and
cronyism, of losing control of the EU bureaucracy and shirking
responsibility.
</P>
<P>
Ending the crisis stemming from the commission's resignation
has topped the agenda of Schroeder's tour to EU member countries.
</P>
<P>
The EU should make a decision soon on the formation of a new
commission after its Berlin summit, Schroeder said, adding that
the new executive arm should be more "transparent, honest and
clear" and should be able to monitor the use of funds better in
the future.
</P>
<P>
Schroeder hoped the Berlin summit would reach consensus on the
Agenda 2000 financial reform plan.
</P>
<P>
Germany, the current president of the EU, would press hard for
farming and structural reform plans and Agenda 2000, the EU's
spending reform plan for the years 2000 to 2006, Schroeder said.
</P>
<P>
Schroeder, who began a tour of EU capitals Monday in
preparation of the Berlin summit, arrived in Vienna Wednesday and
will head for Greece and Italy the same day. 
</P>
</TEXT>
