<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Germany Favors Peaceful Solution to Kosovo Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, March 17 (Xinhua) -- The German government on Wednesday
expressed deep concern over the stalemated Kosovo peace talks
underway in Paris and said it will work to "the last minute" for a
peaceful solution to the Kosovo crisis.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for the Foreign Ministry said that Germany would
continue to push for a peaceful settlement to the Kosovo crisis if
only the co-chairman of the Kosovo peace talks, French Foreign
Minister Hubert Vedrine and British Foreign Minister Robin Cook,
have not declared a breakdown of the talks.
</P>
<P>
Kosovo, with a population of 2 million, is an Albanians-
dominated province in southern Serbia, Yugoslavia's main republic.
Fighting has been going on since early last year between the
secessionist Albanians and Serbian security forces, leaving nearly
2,000 dead and tens of thousands homeless.
</P>
<P>
Under the pressure from Western countries to end the conflict,
the Serbian delegation and the representatives of ethnic Albanians
began a second round of peace talks in Paris on Monday.
</P>
<P>
But the talks are now in an impasse as the Serbs still refuses
the deployment of NATO peace-keepers in Kosovo despite NATO's
threats of strikes against Yugoslavia's strategic targets.
</P>
<P>
Observers here said hopes are slim for the two sides to sign
the U.S.-sponsored peace plan which is composed of a political
part and a military part. The stationing of NATO troops in Kosovo
is the centerpiece of the military part.
</P>
<P>
The Albanians expressed their willingness to sign the peace
plan before the resumption of the negotiations, but so far they
have not done so.
</P>
<P>
NATO spokesman Jamie Shea on Monday reiterated NATO's threat.
Speaking on a German television, he warned that the Yugoslav
government should sign the peace agreement this weekend at the
latest or will "face serious consequences."
</P>
<P>
However, he said that only after the rival parties sign the
peace accord will the nearly 10,000 NATO troops, currently
stationed in Macedonia, enter the embattled province. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
