<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkmenistan to Withdraw From CIS Mutual Visa Exemption Pact </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ALMA ATA, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Turkmenistan has decided to
withdraw from the agreement between the Commonwealth of
Independent States (CIS) on the "mutual exemption of visas"
because of "chaotic" exchanges on its borders with immigrants and
other personnel crossing in great numbers, the Interfax News
Agency reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The news agency quoted the Turkmen Foreign Ministry source as
saying that the ministry has sent notes on the withdrawal to the
competent CIS executive authorities based in Moscow and Minsk, the
Belarus capital.
</P>
<P>
Executive authorities will spend at least three months
reviewing the application for a withdrawal from the agreement.
Turkmenistan intends to formally withdraw from the agreement in
June, the source was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
In explaining reasons for the withdrawal, the source said the
chaotic exchange of personnel has made it difficult to control the
situation at border areas. However, the withdrawal does not
necessarily mean that Turkmenistan will sever its relations with
other CIS states, which were once union republics of the former
Soviet Union, according to the source.
</P>
<P>
The CIS agreement on mutual exemption of visas was signed in
1992. Turkmenistan has been the first country to withdraw from it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
