<HEADLINE> China's Traditional Medicine Industry Eyes Overseas Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 18 (Xinhua) -- China plans to promote the entry
of traditional Chinese medicine into the world market through
furthering overseas understanding of Chinese medical culture.
</P>
<P>
The State Administration of Traditional Chinese Medicine (TCM)
has been carrying out a 10-year program for TCM development abroad
since 1997, according to today's China Daily.
</P>
<P>
The program would see the establishment of about 60 TCM clinics
overseas, the opening of TCM courses in 10 foreign higher-
education institutes, and a rise of the sale of TCM products
worldwide, it said.
</P>
<P>
China exports herbal materials and TCM health food worth 600
million US dollars to some 130 countries each year.
</P>
<P>
An official with the administration told the newspaper that
progress has been achieved. Four medical schools overseas have
already established TCM courses, and two TCM drugs treating cardio-
and cerebralvascular diseases have been registered for import at
the Food and Drug Administration of the Untied States.
</P>
<P>
"We hope TCM can be incorporated into medical care and health
insurance systems in a number of foreign countries by 2008," said
Li Zhenji, the deputy administrator.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper revealed that Singapore and Victoria state of
Australia planned to introduce legislation to accept TCM on a
formal basis.
</P>
<P>
In order to encourage more countries to accept TCM, China has
sent hundreds of medical teams abroad in the past three decades,
whose members helped train local medical workers in TCM while
treating patients.
</P>
<P>
China has trained about 150,000 overseas students from 130
countries and regions in TCM over the past 30 years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
