<HEADLINE> U.S. Newspapers Dismiss Lab-Theft Fantasy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Some U.S. newspapers have
published articles criticizing the anti-China campaign championed
by some media organizations and Republican Congressmen and calling
for continued engagement with China.
</P>
<P>
In a commentary on Tuesday, the Los Angeles Time described the
lab-theft charges against China as "absurdly overblown" and "a
nostalgia for confrontation".
</P>
<P>
"The current China spy hysteria is based on a hyping of threats
that are woefully irrational," it said.
</P>
<P>
"For the past century, we have meddled in Chinese affairs as if
the Middle Kingdom were nothing more than a playground for our
great power fantasies," the article said. Despite its "
overwhelming" mischief-making, the U.S. always insists on "playing
the role of victim," it added.
</P>
<P>
The article lashed out at the New York Times, which has led the
"China spy" rhetorics since earlier this month, calling it a "
shame on the media". It also criticized those Republican
politicians "who play the frayed China card" just to win elections.
</P>
<P>
"In the process, they undermine a sensible policy of engagement
pioneered by President Richard Nixon some 30 years ago," the
commentary said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, "The Christian Science Monitor" also published an
article calling on the United States not to lose China again. It
said that some politicians in the U.S. tried to boycott China and
pressure that country into docile behavior, but "history gives
little support to such tactics."
</P>
<P>
"What's needed now is not U.S. confrontation, but continued
active engagement" with China, the paper stressed.
</P>
<P>
It suggested that the U.S. make "a constructive, truth-speaking
summit" with China's leaders in Washington next month, carry out
negotiations to bring China into the World Trade Organization,
make regular high-level consultations between the two militaries
to seek steps to curb nuclear proliferation and go ahead with
technology exchanges on pollution control.
</P>
<P>
"The Wall Street Journal" also voiced its worry over the
espionage propaganda. An article issued by the newspaper on
Tuesday said that a group of computer companies, including
International Business Machines Corp., Intel Corp., Sun
Microsystems Inc. and Unisys Corp, are launching a counter-
offensive.
</P>
<P>
According to the article, those computer giants have formed a
lobbying group called the Computer Coalition for Responsible
Exports. A study issued by the team shows that U.S. restrictions
on high-tech exports to China and other countries are "out of date.
"
</P>
<P>
"China will be the second-largest computer market in the world
by the year 2000," the article quoted Dan Hoydysh, director of
Unisys's Washington office as saying. The computer tycoons here
are trying to persuade the government to loosen export controls to
China because "the technology has left the restrictions behind,"
it said.
</P>
<P>
The article noted that the anti-China propaganda has put the
GOP -- the Republicans -- into a dilemma, since for all their high-
flight talks on national security, "Republicans ill afford to
completely alienate business, a core GOP constituency." 
</P>
</TEXT>
