<HEADLINE> IMF To Pay Out 100 Million Dollars To Honduras in 1999 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEGUCIGALPA, March 17 (Xinhua) -- The International Monetary
Fund (IMF) this year will pay out 100 million dollars of the 220-
million-dollar fund approved for Honduras over three years.
</P>
<P>
Sources from the Honduran Economic Cabinet said on Wednesday
that the money would be used to help balance payments under the
Reinforced Service of Structural Adjustment (RSSA) agreement.
</P>
<P>
The rest of the money will be paid in 2000 and 2001, depending
on the compliance with the RSSA agreement, which established a six-
month revision to check on compliance and the results.
</P>
<P>
The RSSA anticipates, among other things, the continuity and
strengthening of the process of privatization of various public
services, better training and administration of taxes and the
continuation of state modernization, which includes various health
institutions.
</P>
<P>
The agreement does not include new taxes or the extension of
present taxes. The document was presented to the directorate of
the IMF in Washington and approved for Honduras in January.
