<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Issues New Standards to Tighten Auto Emissions Controls </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 18 (Xinhua) -- The State Quality and Technical
Supervision Administration has promulgated four new standards
tightening controls over vehicle exhaust emissions to improve air
quality in China's cities.
</P>
<P>
The standards will be applied to a range of vehicles
manufactured after January 1, 2000, Yin Minghan, director of the
administration's Industry and Transportation Standardization
Department, was quoted as saying by today's China Daily.
</P>
<P>
Liquefied petroleum gas vehicles, compressed natural gas
vehicles and those powered by diesel engines, which are not
covered by the existing State standards, will also be regulated by
the new standards.
</P>
<P>
"Current vehicle exhaust emission standards were issued 10
years ago, when private cars were not so common and environmental
problems not so serious," said Yin.
</P>
<P>
Chinese vehicle population has increased by 1.5 times to
approximately 13 million during the past decade, and is expected
to exceed 20 million by 2000.
</P>
<P>
Urban air quality reports in Beijing indicate that more than 60
percent of environmental pollution comes from exhaust or tail gas
emissions.
</P>
<P>
Implementation of the new standards beginning next year is
expected to result in a remarkable improvement in air quality, the
official said. Tail-gas emissions are expected to be cut by 80
percent by then.
</P>
<P>
"Besides bringing about cleaner air, the standards will also
spur domestic auto manufacturers to work towards more advanced
technologies, and foster a stronger sense of responsibility for
the whole society," Yin said.
</P>
<P>
Key domestic auto manufacturers have been invited to
participate in drafting the standards to ensure that the 80
percent decrease in exhaust emissions is within their
technological capabilities.
</P>
<P>
State standards for unleaded petrol are expected to be
published by the administration this May, and are expected to take
effect on January 1, 2000, while standards for diesel fuels will
also be issued this year.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, the administration will work in close
cooperation with public security bureaus and transportation
departments to draft stricter exhaust emission standards for
vehicles manufactured before January 1, 2000, the official said.
</P>
