<HEADLINE> Albania, Macedonia Urge Yugoslavia to Sign Peace Deal Soon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIRANA, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Albania and Macedonia called on
Yugoslavia to sign the Kosovo peace plan soon; they are insisting
that the presence of NATO in Kosovo is the only way to ensure a
lasting peace in the province.
</P>
<P>
Albanian Defense Minister Luan Hajdaraga and his Macedonian
counterpart Nikola Kljusev made the statement at a press
conference in the Macedonian capital city of Skopje.
</P>
<P>
The two ministers discussed the current situation in Kosovo and
coordinated their positions on the crisis.
</P>
<P>
They said military forces from both countries were seeking a
political settlement to the Kosovo issue and hoped Yugoslavia
would sign the peace agreement in Paris soon.
</P>
<P>
Albania and Macedonian are neighbors of Kosovo. NATO has
deployed 10,000 troops in Macedonia which are preparing to enter
Kosovo after the peace talks end in Paris.
</P>
<P>
The peace talks are underway with little hope of ending in a
deal. Serbians still oppose NATO deployment in the province.
</P>
<P>
Rival ethnic Albanians have said they will sign the agreement,
which gives them self-rule in Kosovo instead of the independence
they seek. 
</P>
</TEXT>
