<HEADLINE> Philippine Rebels Agree to Free Abducted Officers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, March 18 (Xinhua) -- The New People's Army (NPA) rebels
will free a Philippine army general and three other military and
police personnel as soon as the details for their release are
worked out, the Philippine Star newspaper said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Jose Ma. Sison, head of the National Democratic Front, of which
the NPA is the military arm, was quoted as disclosing this in a
radio interview.
</P>
<P>
Sison said the rebel front still has to thoroughly discuss the
"procedural mechanics" for the eventual release of the captives.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he called on military units in Mindanao, the
southern Philippines, to "withdraw and halt their operations so
the release of the prisoners of war could be safely effected," the
newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
The office of Senator Loren Legarda, who joined a group of
priests negotiating the freedom of the officers, announced that
the captives were likely to be release early Friday, the newspaper
said.
</P>
<P>
The office also announced that the release would be
"unconditional," it.
</P>
<P>
Defense Department and armed forces officials welcomed the
offer of release, but said this was subject to consultations with
higher authorities, the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
Army General Victor Obillo and his aide were abducted on
February 17 by the NPA guerrillas while Police Inspector Roberto
Bernal and Army Staff Sergeant Alipio Lozada were snatched later
in separate raids.
</P>
<P>
The abductions forced the government to call off peace talks
with the rebels last month and suspend the scheduled release of
about 50 jailed rebel guerrillas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
