<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Inner Mongolia Introduces Extensive Ecological Program (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Cao Wenzhong, a Regional Forestry Department official, says
that in the past years the regional government has banned the
cutting of trees for farmland and adopted a series of measures on
planting trees, seeding, closing mountain forests, and water and
soil conservation for an environmental protection screen.
</P>
<P>
To encourage people to help improve the ecology, the regional
government also has worked out a contract and share-holding system
for planting trees on deserts and mountains.
</P>
<P>
Wang Minghai, a businessman, was one of those who volunteered
for the desert reclamation project and helped create the Engbey
miracle. In 1989, he gave up his business and began devoting
himself to desert control and spent nearly all of his savings on
the desert control project.
</P>
<P>
His actions moved Seiei Tohyama, a Japanese who later joined
Wang's program. In the past decade, the two men have turned more
than 7,000 hectares of deserts into oases.
</P>
<P>
Cao Wenzhong says that about 730,000 hectares of grassland or
forest have been planted or reclaimed by now.
</P>
<P>
Yunbulong, the region's chairman, says that this year the
region will increase spending on environmental protection and will
use around one billion yuan for this purpose.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
