<DOCNO> XIE19990318.0291 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Federal Reserve Predicts Further Economic Gains in 1999 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 17 (Xinhua) -- The strong economic growth of
1998 brought the new year with robust consumer spending, brisk
construction activity and increasing demand for labor, the U.S.
Federal Reserve said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, prices of most goods remain little changed and
businesses remain reluctant to press for price increases, the Fed
said in a survey of regional economic conditions before March 8,
known as the "Beige Book."
</P>
<P>
Analysts said the combination of thriving economic growth and
absent inflation detected in the survey implies Fed policy-makers
probably will opt for no change in interest rates when they meet
on March 30.
</P>
<P>
The Beige Book, a compilation of anecdotal information
collected by the Fed's 12 regional banks, confirmed statistical
reports showing the economy maintained its vigor through January
and February despite continuing problems in agriculture,
manufacturing and energy production.
</P>
<P>
The book said that even in manufacturing, where some companies
have struggled with exports lost to the world economic slowdown
that began in Asia in 1997, there are some improvements in most
districts.
</P>
<P>
Six banks of New York, Philadelphia, Richmond, Va., St. Louis,
Minneapolis and San Francisco reported stronger manufacturing and
five banks of Boston, Cleveland, Atlanta, Chicago and Dallas
reported mixed conditions. Only one, Kansas City Bank, said
manufacturing remained weak.
</P>
<P>
Though "foreign competition depressed textile, apparel and
energy-related industries," the survey said, "post-holiday
discounting and mild weather in some regions" contributed to
continued strength in consumer spending.
</P>
<P>
It said, "motor vehicle sales increased, led by light trucks,
and furniture sales benefited from robust home sales."
</P>
<P>
Agriculture, however, "continued to be plagued by low farm
commodity prices, and an increasing number of farmers were under
financial stress," the survey said. Also, three districts --
Minneapolis, Kansas City and San Francisco -- " reported that
falling oil prices were causing some oil and gas wells to be
withdrawn from production.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, the Beige Book said, the overall economy
retained its vigor and "labor markets remained tight."
</P>
<P>
"Finding qualified workers has become more difficult in several
districts, and reports of faster wage increases were more
widespread than in recent months," it said. And in the New York
and Kansas City districts, even "finding entry-level workers was
difficult."
</P>
<P>
However, it said, prices remain stable with the exception of
construction material such as lumber, drywall and insulation.
</P>
<P>
In a speech Tuesday, Fed Chairman Alan Greenspan said that
despite near-term challenges in agriculture, most farmers and farm
lenders remained optimistic about the sector's long-term prospects.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990318.0292 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0100 GMT, March 18 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The U.S. Senate voted overwhelmingly Wednesday to
approve a bill calling for a nationwide defense against limited
ballistic missile attack after President Bill Clinton and most
Senate Democrats dropped their long-standing opposition to the
legislation.
</P>
<P>
On a 97 to 3 vote, the Senate adopted the bill committing the
military to deploy a national missile as soon as "technologically
possible." (US-Senate-Missile-Bill)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
PARIS -- The conference on Kosovo will continue Thursday and
the Kosovo Albanian delegation will sign the peace agreement
before leaving Paris, said the three international mediators
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The European Union representative, Austrian diplomat Wolfgang
Petritsch, said that the Kosovo Albanian delegation will sign the
agreement without any delay. (France-Kosovo-Conference)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS -- The world has been far from tranquillity
since the beginning of this year, the last one in the outgoing
century. Gunshots have been heard in conflicts in such countries
as Afghanistan, Angola, Congo (K), Guinea-Bissau, Liberia and
Sierra Leone, and many children have been victimized in these
intra-state conflicts.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, an alarming trend has been the increasing
participation, direct and indirect, of children in armed conflicts.
(UN-Children-Armed Conflicts)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The United States has invited the Kosovo
Liberation Army (KLA) leader Hashim Thaqi to Washington for advice
on how to transform the guerrilla army into a political movement,
the State Department said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The invitation was issued in Paris earlier in the day at a time
when the peace talks on Kosovo was deadlocked because Yugoslavia
would not agree to NATO's entrance into its sovereign territory of
Kosovo. (US-Kosovo-Thaqi-Visit)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ABUJA -- A special committee set up by the Nigerian government
Tuesday presented a report to Nigeria's Head of State General
Abdulsalami Abubakar, advocating a 20-year master plan for the
development of Niger Delta.
</P>
<P>
Oladayo Popoola, chairman of the 22-member committee charged
with evolving short and long term development options for the area,
said here Tuesday that a development council would be set up for
the area to coordinate various development projects. (Nigeria-
Niger Delta)
</P>
<P>
