<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Crystal Palace: Venables Owed Two Million Pounds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Former England manager Terry
Venables is still owed two million pounds from Crystal Palace,
according to local reports on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Palace have been forced to call in administrators as the money
owed to Venables, who has already been paid almost one million
pounds, is just a fraction of their overall debts of 22 million
pounds, with a further 500,000 pounds being lost every month.
</P>
<P>
The club do have assets worth 13 million and chairman Mark
Goldberg, who has already lost the 23 million he paid to buy out
Ron Noades last summer, has invested a further 1.5 million. But
unless Goldberg and administrator David Buchler can cut the huge
wage bill, slash costs and attract new investment over the next
three months, even their optimism will count for nothing.
</P>
<P>
Crucial to Palace's future will be agreeing terms with their
long list of creditors, which include several English and European
clubs as well as banks - but most famously Venables and his former
assistants at the club.
</P>
<P>
The ex-England coach was paid his 750,000 pounds annual tax-
free salary up front last summer when he took over as well as
being given a Mercedes, the use of a house, an unsecured interest-
free loan and a cut of revenue from player sales.
</P>
<P>
Although a final deal has still not been reached with regard to
the settlement of the four years remaining on his contract, Palace
anticipate that it will be a further 2 million.
</P>
<P>
However, Venables is unlikely to receive the full amount as -
like many other creditors - he is expected to have to agree to
part-payment or to accept shares in the club instead to obtain
anything at all.
</P>
<P>
Goldberg said: "It is easy to say in hindsight that it was a
foolish deal. But there are clubs where managers are offered
certain salaries, bonuses and share options and it has been a
great success."
</P>
<P>
The Palace chairman was speaking alongside administrator
Buchler, who has previously turned around Millwall, as he
expressed his belief that the First Division club could survive
the current crisis.
</P>
<P>
But Goldberg also cautioned that Palace were not alone and that
their plight should serve as a warning to other clubs not to "
chase the dream" of an instant return to the hallowed land of the
Premiership by continuing to pay inflated salaries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
