<HEADLINE> Italy, Germany Agree on Swift Solution to EU Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Italian Prime Minister Massimo
D'Alema and German Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder agreed here
Wednesday on the need for a "very swift" solution to the
leadership crisis at the European Commission, the executive body
of the European Union (EU).
</P>
<P>
As EU duty president, Schroeder came here to brief D'Alema on
next week's special EU summit in Berlin on Agenda 2000 reform.
However, following Monday's resignation of the EU executive,
Wednesday's talks between the two leaders were dominated by the
crisis in Brussels.
</P>
<P>
The president of European Commission, Jacques Santer, resigned
along with his 20 commissioners on Monday night after a report on
mismanagement, fraud and cronyism.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to the press after their meeting, D'Alema reiterated
that Italy's prime candidate for the post of European Commission
president remained ex-premier Romano Prodi.
</P>
<P>
"We strongly support the candidacy of Romano Prodi both for the
esteem we have for him personally and because this is a reasonable
objective for Italy," D'Alema added.
</P>
<P>
The German chancellor, who has been on a whirlwind tour of EU
capitals, said that the EU government leaders he has spoken to so
far have all agreed on the need for a swift solution to the crisis.
</P>
<P>
He added that for the moment his efforts were not focused on
any specific name for the chief post, but said that the
speculation over two possible German candidates, former chancellor
Helmut Kohl and ex-finance minister Oskar La Fontaine, was pure
fantasy.
</P>
<P>
Schroeder also said that his talks with D'Alema were "very
confidential" and refused to reveal the details of their talks,
saying that he must remain neutral because of his role as the duty
president.
</P>
<P>
Turning his attention to the reform of EU budget and finances
to prepare for its expansion, D'Alema told the press that their
meeting had represented a "step forward."
</P>
<P>
The German chancellor praised D'Alema for playing a "positive
role" in the Agenda 2000 talks, and expressed his hope that the
Berlin summit on March 24-25 would have "true justice" for all EU
members.
</P>
<P>
At that summit, he added, the EU must "demonstrate an ability
to act" and reach an agreement on Agenda 2000.
</P>
<P>
After meeting with D'Alema, Schroeder left here for Lisbon,
where he will continue his Europe tour which will also take him
Thursday to Madrid and Luxembourg.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Italy's former Prime Minister Romano Prodi on
Wednesday declined to comment on reports that he was in the
running for the president of European Commission.
</P>
<P>
Members of Prodi's entourage said the situation was still "too
fluid," with the EU engaged in finalizing Agenda 2000 reforms.
</P>
<P>
EU duty chief Schroeder has ruled out a re-appointment of
Santer, but said some of the commissioners may keep their jobs,
especially the ones that did not receive censure in the report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990318.0302 </DOCNO>
