<HEADLINE> Germany Rules Out EU Commission Head Naming at </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, March 17 (Xinhua) -- A high-ranking German official
Wednesday ruled out the possibility that a new president of the
European Union (EU) Commission would be named at the EU's Berlin
summit scheduled for next week.
</P>
<P>
Guenter Verheugen, deputy foreign minister responsible for
European affairs, told the Deutschlandfunk radio that Germany's
top priority for the summit was to win an accord with its EU
partners over the Agenda 2000 reform package.
</P>
<P>
Serving as the EU's rotating president for the first half of
year 1999, Bonn has been expecting EU countries to pass the reform
plan, which covers budget, farming and aid spending of the EU.
</P>
<P>
Verheugen said it remained a problem to name a new commission
president before the European Parliament election on June 13 while
it was unclear what sort of majority would emerge from the vote.
</P>
<P>
After the mass resignation of the EU Commission Monday,
Luxemburg's Prime Minister Jean-Claude Junke told the press that
a new executive should be named prior to the European Parliament
election, indicating differences among EU members. 
