<BODY>
<HEADLINE> French Communist Newspaper Has Fundamental Transformation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, March 17 (Xinhua) -- The French Communist Party (PCF)'s
newspaper L'Humanite will from Thursday present itself with a
totally new face in both forms and contents, signaling a
fundamental transformation to survive market competition.
</P>
<P>
The PCF National Secretary Robert Hue told Xinhua at a
reception of L'Huma at the Stade de France football stadium in
Saint Denis outside Paris that the newspaper will remain
Communist, although it will not be the exclusive carrier of the
views of the PCF.
</P>
<P>
The new graphics of L'Huma are designed by Claude Maggiori, who
also designed the daily Liberation in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
The L'Huma will be a colorful newspaper instead of having
monotonous red and black printings.
</P>
<P>
The sickle and hammer insignia indicating the PCF ownership
will be removed.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper will abandon its old headings of pages on
domestic and international news, and will concentrate reportings
on some major events of the day and give more space to debates and
special subjects like cities, labor and tendency.
</P>
<P>
Prior to the transformation, the chief editor of L'Huma Claude
Cabanes said that he was worried that the newspaper would not be
able to survive long if it failed to have a radical
transformation.
</P>
<P>
Because of its strong partisanship, the newspaper's circulation
dropped from 106,000 in 1988 to 52,000 in 1998.
</P>
<P>
The reform of L'Huma began to be elaborated two years ago when
the newspaper director Pierre Zarka decided to give a new style to
its weekly periodical L'Huma Hebdo to draw buyers.
</P>
<P>
Ironically, the leftwing newspaper was hit itself by a series
of social disputes between its employees and the management over
the past two years because of its deteriorating economic
situation.
</P>
<P>
The reform of the newspaper of PCF goes parallel with the
reform of the election campaign strategy of the PCF for the
European Parliament elections to be held on June 13.
</P>
<P>
The PCF presented a list of candidates half of whom are not PCF
members to counter the rising influence of the Greens and
extreme-leftist parties.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
