<HEADLINE> U.S. Invites KLA Leader to Washington for Advice </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 17 (Xinhua) -- The United States has invited
the Kosovo Liberation Army (KLA) leader Hashim Thaqi to Washington
for advice on how to transform the guerrilla army into a political
movement, the State Department said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The invitation was issued in Paris earlier in the day at a time
when the peace talks on Kosovo was deadlocked because Yugoslavia
would not agree to NATO's entrance into its sovereign territory of
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said the invitation to Thaqi and the KLA goes one step
further, by honoring a separatist guerrilla movement that has not
always respected the conventional rules of war.
</P>
<P>
State Department spokesman James Foley, asked about the
rationale behind the visit, said: "We want to develop a good
relationship with them as they transform themselves into a
politically oriented organization under a Kosovo living in peace,
under the terms of the interim accord."
</P>
<P>
"We want to develop closer and better ties with that
organization," he added.
</P>
<P>
"We believe that we have a lot of advice and a lot of help that
we can provide to them if they become precisely the kind of
political actor we would like to see them," Foley said.
</P>
<P>
The invitation to Thaqi comes directly from U.S. Secretary of
State Madeleine Albright, who took a liking to him at their first
meeting in Rambouillet in France last month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
