<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Envoy Sees New Hope of Peace in Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, March 17 (Xinhua) -- A U.N. envoy Wednesday
said that he has "a new sense of hope" in Africa because "yearning
for hope is very strong."
</P>
<P>
Olara Otunnu, U.N. special representative for children and
armed conflict, told a press conference of his just-concluded
visit to Africa, which took him to Rwanda, Burundi and Sudan.
</P>
<P>
Otunnu said that he returned to the U.N. headquarters "with a
new sense of hope, especially with local people, especially (after
spending some time) with women and children in the three
countries, their yearnings for peace are very strong."
</P>
<P>
During his visit to Rwanda, he also met with Ernest Wamba Dia
Wamba, chairman of the Congolese Rally for Democracy (RDC), who
responded positively to several issues raised by Otunnu concerning
the protection and welfare of children, including the recruitment
and use of children in armed conflict and the protection of
civilian populations.
</P>
<P>
Wamba traveled from Goma, eastern Congo (K), to meet with the
U.N. special representative in Gisenyi, Rwanda, on February 22.
</P>
<P>
Wamba made the commitment to a temporary cease-fire in response
to the U.N. envoy's call for a respite in fighting in order to
allow for vaccinations and the special feeding of malnourished
children in Congo (K).
</P>
<P>
"I am encouraged by the positive response and commitments I
have received from Mr. Wamba. I look forward to following through
on these commitments and to urging the RDC (the Democratic
Republic of Congo) to translate them into concrete actions that
can provide greater protection to children exposed to armed
conflict in the DRC," said Otunnu.
</P>
<P>
The special representative said he, in his visit to the three
African nations, has expressed grave concern over the growing
trend towards the targeting of civilian populations in a situation
of conflict.
</P>
<P>
Otunnu said he visited Burundi "just a couple days after the
end of sanctions against the country," where he can see for
himself the impact on children of the sanctions.
</P>
<P>
He said he also sought ways by which the issue of protection
and the needs of children could be incorporated into the Burundi
peace process now going on in Arusha, Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. envoy had already raised the issue with former
Tanzanian President Julius Nyerere, who had in principle accepted
and welcomed the proposal.
</P>
<P>
U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan has appointed Otunnu as his
special representative for children in armed conflict. The
three-year-term appointment was announced on August 19, 1997 and
effective on September 1, 1997. He has since served as advocate
for children in armed conflict situations, promoting measures for
their protection in times of conflict and for their healing and
reintegration in conflict's aftermath. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
