<HEADLINE> U.S. Repeats Threat of Military Action on Yugoslavia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 17 (Xinhua) -- The United States said on
Wednesday that NATO is "prepared to act" if Yugoslav President
Slobodan Milosevic refuses to let it enforce peace in the
province of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
"We're obviously very concerned about what we're seeing in
terms of military movements by Serbia. It's a matter of serious
concern to us and it's something that the Serbs have heard
directly from us about our concerns," said White House deputy
National Security Adviser James Steinberg.
</P>
<P>
Yugoslavia on Tuesday asked a substantive changes to a
U.S.-drafted peace deal on Kosovo, which was, however, rejected
by the so-called Contact Group that presided over the peace
talks in Paris between the Serbs and ethnic Albanians.
</P>
<P>
Ethnic Albanians have agreed to sign the peace deal and the
talks were deadlocked as the Serbs refused to let foreign troops
in their sovereign territory of Kosovo as NATO had demanded.
</P>
<P>
Steinberg said NATO's patience was growing thin, and repeated
warning of bombing Yugoslav targets if Belgrade does not give up
its sovereignty in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
"The president has made very clear that if Serbian
intransigence and continued aggression causes this peace effort
to fail, there will be consequences, and we are watching it very
closely," Steinberg told reporters.
</P>
<P>
He threatened Yugoslavia that "NATO has authority to act." He
added NATO is "prepared to act" if Milosevic continue to refuse
the peace deal and move his troops in and around Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
State Department spokesman James Foley said that based on
reports from international monitors, the Serbs continued moving
reinforcements into Kosovo overnight.
</P>
<P>
Foley called the troop movements a "clear violation" of last
October's agreement between Milosevic and NATO.
</P>
<P>
Steinberg and Foley said there were two triggers for NATO
military action -- a refusal by the Serbs to agree to the
drafted Kosovo peace deal, and an armed offensive against the
Kosovo Albanians.
</P>
<P>
"And on both scores, we are seeing increasing evidence that
the Serbs are meeting the criteria for triggering a NATO
response," Foley said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
