<HEADLINE> Kosovo Conference to Continue Thursday in Paris </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, March 17 (Xinhua) -- The conference on Kosovo will
continue Thursday and the Kosovo Albanian delegation will sign the
peace agreement before leaving Paris, said the three international
mediators Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The European Union representative, Austrian diplomat Wolfgang
Petritsch, said that the Kosovo Albanian delegation will sign the
agreement without any delay.
</P>
<P>
He said that the Serb delegation still is not ready to sign the
agreement.
</P>
<P>
He also said that the conference on Kosovo is drawing to an end
and in order to obtain a positive result and a complete agreement,
the international mediators will accelerate the talks with the
Yugoslav side.
</P>
<P>
U.S. mediator Christopher Hill gave a more pessimistic tone,
saying that the Serb side failed to make any "new progress" in the
past three days of talks.
</P>
<P>
He said that the Kosovo Albanian side has agreed to sign the
agreement as it has been required to do, while it is not the case
for the other side of the talks.
</P>
<P>
Russian mediator Boris Mayorski refused to hold the Serb side
responsible for the deadlock of the conference, but said that only
one signature will not make up an agreement.
</P>
<P>
"There should be two to dance the tango," he said.
</P>
<P>
Mayorski said that as long as there is time and hope, the
international mediators will continue to work.
</P>
<P>
The Yugoslav delegation has stood firm in its opposition to the
deployment of a NATO force in Kosovo, which the Western countries
said will guarantee the implementation of the peace agreement on
autonomy in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
The Yugoslav delegation has also demanded that some amendments
be made in the political part of the agreement, as some articles
will undermine Serb sovereignty over Kosovo. 
</P>
</TEXT>
