<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IOC Formally Expels Six Members Over Scandal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAUSANNE, SWITZERLAND, March 17 (Xinhua) -- The International
Olympic Committee (IOC) formally expelled six members at its 108th
session held here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The six who have been expelled are Agustin C. Arroyo of
Ecuador, Zein El Abdin A. Gadir of Sudan, Jean-Claude Ganga of
Congo, Lamine Keita of Mali, Sergio Santander Fantini of Chile,
and Paul Wallwork of Samoa.
</P>
<P>
The expulsions of the first five were recommended on January 24
by the IOC ad hoc commission to investigate the conduct of certain
IOC members involved in the bidding process of the Winter Olympic
games in the Salt Lake City.
</P>
<P>
Wallwork was added to the recommendation when the ad hoc
commission presented its second report to the IOC executive board
on March 11.
</P>
<P>
A total of 10 delegates, almost 10 percent of the membership,
have now left the IOC for accepting bribes from Salt Lake City
which won the IOC vote in 1995 to stage the 2002 Winter Games. The
IOC has been reduced to 104 members.
</P>
<P>
Four members, Pirjo Haggman of Finland, Bashir Mohamed
Attarabulsi of Libya, David Sibandze of Swaziland and Charles
Mukora of Kenya, had already resigned before Wednesday's special
session. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990318.0319 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 </DATE_TIME>
