<DOCNO> XIE19990318.0320 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Children Should Be Protected From </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, March 17 (Xinhua) -- The world has been far
from tranquillity since the beginning of this year, the last one
in the outgoing century. Gunshots have been heard in conflicts in
such countries as Afghanistan, Angola, Congo (K), Guinea-Bissau,
Liberia and Sierra Leone, and many children have been victimized
in these intra-state conflicts.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, an alarming trend has been the increasing
participation, direct and indirect, of children in armed
conflicts.
</P>
<P>
"It is estimated that up to 300,000 children under the age of
18 are serving as combatants in government armed forces or armed
opposition groups in ongoing conflicts," Olara Otunnu, special
representative of the U.N. secretary-general for children and
armed conflicts, has said.
</P>
<P>
This brutal reality has been exacerbated by a qualitative
change in the nature and scope of conflict in recent times.
Today's conflicts are primarily internal, often fought by
multiple, semi-autonomous armed groups within existing state
boundaries.
</P>
<P>
Against a backdrop of increasingly accessible and destructive
conventional weapons, many of these conflicts pit compatriot
against compatriot, neighbor against neighbor.
</P>
<P>
In today's internecine warfare, the village has become the
battlefield and civilian populations are the primary target. The
driving force behind the tragic scene is what has been described
as "military adventurism," the warring parties seek to test their
fortune on the battlefield, and one government send troops to
fight in another country.
</P>
<P>
Millions of children and women, those most vulnerable and least
responsible for conflict, today represent the vast majority of
casualties in armed conflicts worldwide. About 90 percent of all
victims today are civilians, mostly children and women and mostly
in internecine wars.
</P>
<P>
In about 50 countries worldwide, millions of children today are
either swept up in armed conflicts or suffering in their
aftermath. Not only are they the victims of war, but all too often
they are its principle targets. In far too many cases, these
targets of war also become its instruments -- serving as child
soldiers.
</P>
<P>
More than 2 million children have been killed in the decade
from 1987 to 1997. At the same time, at least 6 million have been
maimed or permanently disabled. At least 1 million children have
been orphaned during the same 10-year period and half, or 11.4
million, of the world's refugees and displaced persons are
children. Some 300,000 children under 18 are soldiers, guerrillas
or their servants.
</P>
<P>
Even worse, illegal proliferation of light and small weapons
has made it easier for children to be recruited as soldiers
fighting in the conflicts.
</P>
<P>
It is often said that children represent the future of human
civilization and the future of every society. Indeed, to permit
them to be used as pawns in warfare, whether as targets or
perpetrators, is to cast a shadow on the future.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, the international community has an obligation to be
concerned about the protection of all non-combatants caught in the
midst of violent conflicts. Yet there is an urgent need to focus
special attention on the plight of children.
</P>
<P>
However, words on paper cannot save children in peril. The
international community should make concrete steps to protect
children affected by armed conflicts.
</P>
<P>
For its part, the United Nations has increasingly sought to
draw international attention to the plight of children in the
world.
</P>
<P>
Particularly, specific measures have to be taken to protect the
children affected by armed conflict.
</P>
<P>
First, efforts should be made to end the participation of
children in armed conflict and end their recruitment as soldiers.
</P>
<P>
The international community should step up pressure for
demobilization and reintegration, and raise the legal age of
recruitment from 15 to 18. In other words, no one under 15 should
carry arms.
</P>
<P>
Secondly, efforts should be made to reduce the impact of light
weapons on children. This means painstaking efforts to contain the
illegal smuggling of light and small weapons, particularly the
spread of such weapons into conflict-torn regions.
</P>
<P>
Thirdly, efforts should be made to assess and redress the
impact of sanctions on children. Children have been groaning in
the wake of sanctions, which have denied them the access to
fundamental food, not to mention sufficient nutrition. In Iraq,
many children died before they reached the age of 5 simply because
of the nine-year sanctions.
</P>
<P>
Lastly, the international community should also make efforts to
promote mine awareness and the rehabilitation of child victims,
and help the societies concerned to end the rape and sexual abuse
of children during armed conflict.
</P>
<P>
In short, international and national actors must take necessary
political, economic and social measures to prevent conflicts by
addressing the glaring imbalances within societies. Building
genuine democratic practice and respect for the rule of law are
essential because they provide regularized and non-violent
mechanisms to mediate competing claims that can lead to conflict.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
