<DOCNO> XIE19990318.0321 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Security Council Asked to Decide Fate of Khmer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, March 17 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary General
Kofi Annan asked Wednesday the Security Council or the General
Assembly to decide the fate of Khmer Rouge leaders, emphasizing
that cooperation from the Cambodian government is essential.
</P>
<P>
"The decision on the establishment of an international
tribunal, whether under Chapter VI or VII of the Charter of the
United Nations, is for the Security Council or the General
Assembly to make," said the U.N. chief in a letter addressed to
the two U.N. organs.
</P>
<P>
The secretary-general was submitting a report filed by a
three-member fact-finding team sent to Cambodian to probe into
the feasibility of trying the Khmer Rouge leaders before an
international or national tribunal.
</P>
<P>
The team was acting upon the request from the Cambodian
government headed by then Second Prime Minister Hun Sen for
assistance in bringing to justice Khmer Rouge leaders. However,
Phnom Penh has now insisted they be tried before a national
court.
</P>
<P>
Cambodian Foreign Minister Hor Nambong last week made it
clear that since the Khmer Rouge leaders and the victims of
genocide are all Cambodian, the court has to be in Cambodia.
</P>
<P>
Hor Nambong met the secretary-general for half an hour to
clarify his government's stand. However, it seemed that he
failed to convince Annan of the need to change his mind.
</P>
<P>
"I reminded the foreign minister that the Group of Experts
had carefully considered the feasibility of a national tribunal,
but concluded that the Cambodian judiciary in its current state
was unlikely to meet minimal international standards of justice,
even with external assistance," the U.N. chief said in the letter.
</P>
<P>
He insisted that if the international standards of justice,
fairness and the process of law are to be met, "the tribunal in
question must be international in character."
</P>
<P>
However, Annan stressed that this doesn't mean that it should
be modelled after either of the existing ad hoc tribunals or be
linked to them institutionally, administratively or financially.
</P>
<P>
"Other options may be explored, taking into account the
analysis and conclusions of the Group of Experts," the U.N.
chief said without elaboration.
</P>
<P>
Annan realized that the success of any international tribunal
of whatever character, depends on the full cooperation of the
Cambodian government and its readiness to apprehend the Khmer Rouge
leaders situated in its territory.
</P>
<P>
Observers here said that the 15-nation Security Council will
take up the issue for deliberation at Annan's request, but it is
unclear when and where it will lead to.
</P>
<P>
"It is hard to tell what will turn out at this stage since the
Security Council members would have to study the report carefully
before making up their mind," said an Asian diplomat, who asked
not to be identified.
</P>
<P>
China has said that it would respect the decision by the
Cambodian government.
</P>
<P>
It was believed that Russia would probably adopt a similar
stand on this matter, while France is taking a position different
from the United States and Britain.
</P>
<P>
Washington and London are believed to be the main driving
force for an international tribunal.
</P>
<P>
The General Assembly will be asked to make a decision if the
Security Council fails. But its resolution, if any, will not be
binding, the diplomat said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
