<HEADLINE> Top UK Finance Groups On Target For Year 2000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 17 (Xinhua) -- The great majority of Britain's
leading financial groups are on course to beat the Millennium Bug,
but there are a few in danger of not achieving Year 2000
compliance in time.
</P>
<P>
This was the theme of a report by Michael Foot, managing
director of financial supervision at the Financial Services
Authority (FSA), to a conference here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Foot gave a detailed analysis of the financial sector's Year
2000 readiness based mainly on the FSA's "Traffic Light"
assessment of information received from financial firms.
</P>
<P>
Foot said, "For High Impact groups, where problems could have a
big effect on retail customers or the markets, our assessment
shows around 58 percent are on track for Year 2000 compliance
(`blue').
</P>
<P>
"Thirty-five percent behind but likely to get on track
(`amber') and less than 8 percent (12 in number) pose a serious
risk (`red')."
</P>
<P>
"For Medium Impact groups, the overall position is that 40
percent are on track (`blue'), 45 percent behind (`amber') and 15
percent serious risk (`red')," he added.
</P>
<P>
The figures come with a number of qualifications, according to
the report. However, the FSA cannot check all the information
supplied by the many firms it supervises, the report said.
</P>
</TEXT>
