<HEADLINE> Annan Woos Positive Investment in African Forest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, March 17 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan on Wednesday called on the non-governmental
organizations and private sectors to make positive investment in
forest management in Central Africa.
</P>
<P>
"Forest protection is an essential investment in the future
well-being of people and the planet," Annan said.
</P>
<P>
Annan made the statement in a message to the opening of the
Central African Forest Summit in Yaounde, Cameroon.
</P>
<P>
"This summit must decide what to do to reverse the trend of the
degradation of tropical forests in the region," he said. "Never
before has there been such a coordinated and concerted regional
effort to come to grips with the wide range of issues involved."
</P>
<P>
"This summit can help us make the necessary adjustments, and
point us in the proper direction: towards implementation of forest
laws to reduce illegal logging; towards tax reforms and other
changes in economic policy that promote sustainable forest
management; towards national and local capacity-building,
particularly in the area of human resources; and towards improved
coordination of international forest assistance," he said.
</P>
<P>
"The forest system of Central Africa is the world's second
largest contiguous expanse of moist tropical forest," he said,
"Its direct economic contribution to the region's economy is
significant: more than 8 percent of foreign exchanges earnings, a
considerable share of total exports and substantial share of total
government revenue."
</P>
<P>
Annan said he has "every confidence" that scientists and
governments in Central Africa "will rise to the challenge and
pledge the support of the United Nations" for relevant efforts.
</P>
<P>
Klaus Toepfer, executive director of the United Nations
Environment Program, delivered the message on behalf of Annan at
the summit, which opened on Wednesday in Cameroon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
