<DOCNO> XIE19990318.0328 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Algeria Cuts Daily Oil Production </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ALGIERS, March 17 (Xinhua) -- The Algerian National Corporation
of Oil Products announced on Wednesday it will cut down its oil
production by 57,000 barrels per day as from next April.
</P>
<P>
A senior official of the firm was quoted by the Algerian News
Agency as saying the move is in response to the Hague accord
signed on Friday between OPEC members and other oil producing
countries to reduce oil production by 2.1 million barrels a day.
</P>
<P>
"The decision shows Algeria's full respect for its commitments
to the OPEC," Director General of the company Abdul-Meguid Attar
said.
</P>
<P>
The output cut will cover all of the country's productive
oilfields particularly those operating with foreign partners, he
added.
</P>
<P>
The efforts "proved to be fruitful in leading to the oil
production cut by 1.7 million barrels a day for a whole year as
from April," said Algerian Minister of Energy and Mines Youcef
Yousfi on Tuesday, who is currently chief of the Organization of
Petroleum Exporting Countries (OPEC).
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Oman will cut its production by 63,000 barrels a
day, Mexico by 125,000 barrels and Norway by 100,000
barrels. Russia is expected to declare its quota later Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The oil prices are expected to hit 18 U.S. dollars per barrel
by the end of this year, said the OPEC official.
</P>
<P>
Algeria's current quota in the OPEC stands at 788,000 barrels a
day. 
</P>
</TEXT>
