<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Senate Passes National Missile Defense Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 17 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Senate voted
overwhelmingly Wednesday to approve a bill calling for a
nationwide defense against limited ballistic missile attack after
President Bill Clinton and most Senate Democrats dropped their
long-standing opposition to the legislation.
</P>
<P>
On a 97 to 3 vote, the Senate adopted the bill committing the
military to deploy a national missile as soon as "technologically
possible."
</P>
<P>
The U.S. House takes up a similar version Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Senate passage came after the Clinton administration Tuesday
dropped a long-standing veto threat, saying several amendments had
made the measure more palatable.
</P>
<P>
One of those stressed a continued U.S. commitment to seeking
nuclear arms reductions with the Russians. Opponents had suggested
the original measure would have violated restrictions on a missile
defense in the 1972 Anti-Ballistic Missile (ABM) Treaty.
</P>
<P>
With passage of the legislation assured, senators had spent
most of the day skirmishing over political considerations, with
Republicans accusing President Clinton and congressional Democrats
of an 11-hour conversion.
</P>
<P>
Republicans welcomed the belated support of the administration
and its Democratic allies -- but questioned the timing.
</P>
<P>
The president "should pick his fights with Congress on foreign
policy issues" more carefully, claimed Republican Senator John
Warner, chairman of the Senate Armed Services Committee. He said
the debate over missile defense should have been resolved earlier
and that Clinton's slowness to recognize this set back development
of such a system.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said that the U.S. legislation and deployment of the
National Missile Defense System will not only violate terms of the
1972 ABM treaty, but also aggravate international arms race, thus
affecting world peace and stability. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990318.0331 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> African Countries Join Hands to Fight Wildlife </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, March 17 (Xinhua) -- An international organization,
Task Force, was established in Nairobi Wednesday with an aim to
fight wildlife crimes in Africa.
</P>
<P>
It is the first inter-governmental organization on wildlife
protection in the world, which is composed of law enforcement
officials from Republic of Congo, Kenya, Lesotho, Tanzania,
Uganda and Zambia.
</P>
<P>
The Task Force functions under the Lusaka Agreement on
Cooperative Enforcement Operations directed at Illegal Trade in
Wild Fauna and Flora, signed in the Zambian capital in 1994. The
objective of the agreement is to reduce and ultimately eliminate
illegal trade in wildlife.
</P>
<P>
So far the six countries have adopted the agreement which
entered into force in 1996. The establishment of the Task
Force will strengthen the effectiveness of the Convention on
International Trade in Endangered Species of Wild Fauna and Flora
(CITES).
</P>
<P>
The governing council of the Lusaka Agreement, consisting of
officials from the six countries, have been meeting at Kenya
Wildlife Service headquarters since Monday with the objective of
making the Task Force fully operational. Also present at the
meeting were observers from CITES and the United Nations
Environment Program (UNEP).
</P>
<P>
The Task Force was the idea of a group of wildlife law
enforcement officers from African countries who met in Lusaka in
1992. They stressed at the meeting the need for international
cooperation in order to fight wildlife crime successfully.
</P>
<P>
The national bureaux of the organization will work together
with their headquarters on joint cross-border operations against
wildlife crime. The director, intelligence officer and supporting
staff are expected to be appointed in the next few weeks.
</P>
<P>
Tanzania, Zambia and Lesotho have made contributions to the
budget of the Task Force. The Kenyan government offered free
office accommodation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
